\par\par \b \uc2 Domestic  \highlight22\uc2 spending \highlight\uc2  buoys GDP growth in first quarter\b0\par\par\uc2 563 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 11\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 Continued from page 1\par \par \uc2 She went on to say that 5.11 percent was the highest first-quarter growth figure the country had reached since 2014.\par \par \uc2 The BPS report shows that GDP--which measures the total value of goods and services produced nationwide-- dropped to Rp 5,288.3 trillion (US$330 billion) in the first quarter from Rp 5,302.5 trillion in the fourth quarter of 2023 in a typical seasonal effect observed over the years.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  output jumped from the first to the second quarter in each of the past three years, and then declined gradually over the following quarters. Most of the Islamic festive period also fell into the second quarter during those years.\par \par \uc2 Even though the country has maintained a trade surplus for nearly four years, during which the value of exports exceeded that of imports, cross-border trade weighed on GDP growth in the first quarter of 2024 as the surplus over the first three months of the year weakened when compared to the same period of 2023.\par \par \uc2 Every sector of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  posted yoy growth, except for agriculture, which contracted by 3.54 percent in a decline blamed on harvest disruption prompted by the El-Ni?o climate phenomenon.\par \par \uc2 Correspondingly, agriculture lost some 240,000 workers from February 2023 to February this year, while it continues to employ more people than any other sector.\par \par \uc2 The largest sector in terms of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  output is manufacturing, which alone accounted for just shy of a fifth of the country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the first quarter, followed by trade.\par \par \uc2 As BPS also announced on Monday, the unemployment rate dropped significantly to 4.82 percent in February from 5.32 percent in August last year. That figure was below the 4.94 percent reading posted in February 2020, before the pandemic shook the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Private lender Bank Permata chief economist Josua Pardede wrote in an analysis released on Monday that Indonesia was facing internal and external pressure in the first half of 2024.\par \par \uc2 Internally, risks lay in food inflation caused by El-Ni?o, which consequently might impact household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Moreover, the transition to a new government is also causing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  that "may lead investors" to take a "wait-and-see" approach and therefore affect capital \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The risk of a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown, on the other hand, continues to loom as an external threat for Indonesia, Southeast Asia's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Josua noted that "growth opportunities exist" if the government can accelerate national strategic projects (PSN) and the Nusantara Capital City (IKN) megaproject.\par \par \uc2 "Moving into the second half of 2024, as the election [and transition period] conclude and the potential for global \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate cuts materializes--albeit not as extensive as initially anticipated--external pressures are expected to gradually diminish. Consequently, a resurgence of direct investment and capital inflows is anticipated," said Josua.\par \par \uc2 He predicted full-year GDP growth of around 5.07 percent.\par \par \uc2 Bank Danamon economist Irman Faiz placed his bet at 5 percent flat for the entirety of 2024, citing weaker global and domestic demand thanks to a hawkish interest rate "environment".\par \par \uc2 In his assessment, the growth improvement in the first quarter was "mostly driven by one-off factors", namely the election, heavy social security disbursement as well as Ramadan taking place earlier than last year.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240506ek5700004\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 Mirae Economist Warns of Declining Purchasing Power Despite Indonesia's  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  Growth\b0\par\par\uc2 441 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. Despite Indonesia's robust \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, Chief Economist at Mirae Asset Sekuritas, Rully Arya Wisnubroto, cautioned the government about the declining trend in consumer purchasing power in the last two quarters.\par \par \uc2 "Consumer purchasing power has seen a slight decrease, with household consumption growth staying below 5 percent year on year for two consecutive quarters," Rully Arya Wisnubroto told Beritasatu.com on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 Household consumption was the main contributor to gross domestic product (GDP) with a growth of 4.91 percent in the first quarter of 2024, compared to the same period last year, contributing to 54.93 percent of GDP.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the first quarter of 2024 reached 5.11 percent year on year (yoy), slightly below the Finance Ministry's projection of around 5.17 percent.\par \par \uc2 Rully attributed the decline in purchasing power to several factors, including high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , volatile food prices, and imported inflation during periods of rupiah depreciation.\par \par \uc2 According to data from the Central Statistics Agency, inflation for April 2024 reached 0.25 percent monthly, with a year-on-year rate of 3 percent and a calendar year inflation of 1.19 percent.\par \par \uc2 He mentioned that this decline in purchasing power affected various socio-\b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  groups, from the lower to the upper-middle class. While the government has provided substantial social assistance to the lower-income group, the middle class has been somewhat overlooked.\par \par \uc2 "To address this, the government needs to focus on the middle class, possibly by improving infrastructure and facilities such as \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  transportation to support \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity among the middle class," he suggested.\par \par \uc2 As a result of declining purchasing power and consumer demand, footwear company \uc2 Sepatu Bata\uc2  announced last week the closure of its factory in Purwakarta after 30 years of operation. As a result, 233 employees lost their jobs.\par \par \uc2 President \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2  said the closure of the factory does not reflect Indonesia's overall \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  condition.\par \par \uc2 Finance Minister Sri Mulyani attributed the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth to strong domestic demand and prudent state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  management.\par \par \uc2 She highlighted that as Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grows, the unemployment rate decreases, even reaching pre-pandemic levels. In February 2024, unemployment decreased by 9.89 percent compared to the same period last year.\par \par \uc2 Sri Mulyani also pointed out the global risks Indonesia faces, such as \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies by The Fed, geopolitical tensions, and disruptions in the global supply chain.\par \par \uc2 In response, the government will closely monitor potential impacts from global dynamics. Utilizing the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  as a shock absorber, Indonesia aims to maintain people\u8217\'20\'19s purchasing power and sustain \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth momentum.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240508ek5800009\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s Foreign Exchange  \highlight22\uc2 Reserves \highlight\uc2  Drop to $136.2b in April\b0\par\par\uc2 183 \uc2 words\par \uc2 8 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  dropped from $140.4 billion in March to $136.2 billion the following month, according to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  attributed the decline to the government\u8217\'20\'19s payment of foreign debts. Efforts to stabilize the rupiah amid the increasingly \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  global financial markets also led to a drop in foreign exchange.\par \par \uc2 According to \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s spokesperson Fadjar Majardi, the current foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  position is equivalent to paying 6.1 months of imports. It is also equivalent to 6 months of imports and government foreign debt payments. This also surpasses the international adequacy standard of 3 months of imports.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWe believe that the foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  are enough to support our external sector resilience, while also ensuring macroeconomic and financial system stability,\u8221\'20\'1D Fadjar said in a press statement on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia will likely continue to have adequate foreign exchange \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the country keeps its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability under control. \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  mix will also help maintain this stability, according to Fadjar.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240508ek580000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
