\par\par \uc2 FEATURES\par \b \uc2 INDONESIA  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMIC \highlight\uc2  OUTLOOK STRONG AMID GLOBAL HEADWINDS\b0\par\par\uc2 1,297 \uc2 words\par \uc2 10 May 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Raka Adji Putra\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - Continuing geopolitical \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and turmoil have increased the pressure on global and domestic financial markets.\par \par \uc2 Ongoing geopolitical conflicts, such as in the Middle East, could increase the risks of a commodity price surge, which could potentially hinder the progress made in controlling inflation.\par \par \uc2 The spike in inflation in the past few months and the continued strong \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance of the United States (US) have fueled expectations of high global \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  for a longer period, causing the US dollar to strengthen and putting pressure on developing countries.\par \par \uc2 Apart from increasing borrowing costs, hikes in US \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  or Fed Fund Rate (FFR) policies have put significant pressure on financial markets in several countries, pushing capital outflows and causing depreciation of local currencies, especially in emerging market countries.\par \par \uc2 Though the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has shown resilience and is projected to continue to grow, the growth is expected to slow for several years.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  has estimated global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 3 percent in 2024 amid high \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the financial market.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, inflation in developed countries, such as the US, has remained above the target.\par \par \uc2 According to the January 2024 update of the World \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook (WEO) report released by the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2  (\uc2 IMF\uc2 ), the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is predicted to grow 3.1 percent in 2024, or 0.2 percentage points higher than the previous projection made in the WEO of October 2023.\par \par \uc2 It has been projected that global growth in 2024\u8211\'20\'132025 will remain below the historical average (2000\u8211\'20\'132019) of 3.8 percent, with high \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  reducing inflation rates, withdrawal of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  support amid high debt weighing on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity, and low basic productivity growth.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, global inflation is projected to decline to 5.8 percent in 2024 and 4.4 percent in 2025. The projected rate for 2025 is lower than the previous forecast.\par \par \uc2 However, Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has managed to show good performance, with growth of 5.05 percent recorded in 2023, supported by strong domestic demand and moderate inflation.\par \par \uc2 According to Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2 , the country"s \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been effective in steering the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the aftermath of the COVID-19 pandemic and the current global shock.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia is among the few countries whose \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  position has continued to improve significantly. The nation"s \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  declined significantly from 6.1 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP) during the pandemic in 2020 to 1.65 percent in 2023. Thus, the debt-to-GDP ratio continued to fall.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia"s short-term \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects remain strong. This resilience is reflected in the Purchasing Managers" Index (\uc2 PMI\uc2 ), which has continued to show expansion, with the manufacturing index reaching a level of 54.2 in March 2024.\par \par \uc2 In terms of demand, consumer confidence remains robust, with the Consumer Confidence Index in the optimistic zone at 123.8 as of March.\par \par \uc2 Domestic demand\par \par \uc2 The resilience of the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  amid increasing global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has also been reflected in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the first quarter of 2024, which stood at 5.11 percent year on year (yoy), higher than the 5.04 percent yoy growth recorded in the previous quarter.\par \par \uc2 According to the director of the BI"s communication department, Fadjar Majardi, this year, national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is projected to remain strong in the range of 4.7 percent to 5.5 percent yoy, supported by domestic demand, especially continued growth in consumption and investment in building infrastructure, in keeping with the continuity of National Strategic Projects (PSN).\par \par \uc2 The higher \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the first quarter of 2024 was supported by higher domestic demand. Household consumption grew by 4.91 percent yoy on account of the 2024 General Elections, national holidays, and collective leave.\par \par \uc2 The consumption of Non-Profit Institutions Serving Households (LNPRT) was high at 24.29 percent yoy, driven by activities related to the General Elections and the Islamic holy month of Ramadan.\par \par \uc2 Government consumption swelled 19.90 percent yoy, driven by an increase in goods \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially related to the implementation of the 2024 General Elections \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and government workers" \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Investment grew 3.79 percent yoy, especially investment in building infrastructure \u8212\'20\'14 in line with the continuity of infrastructure development.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, export growth slowed by 0.50 percent yoy, especially goods exports, in keeping with the decline in the prices of main export products and amid demand from several main trading partners, which continued to grow.\par \par \uc2 Increased \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth was also reflected in the business and spatial aspects.\par \par \uc2 In terms of business sectors, almost all sectors showed positive performance with high growth in the first quarter, including those related to mobility, especially transportation and warehousing, provision of accommodation and food and drink, as well as wholesale and retail trade.\par \par \uc2 The processing industry, as the main contributor to growth, also grew well on the back of sustained domestic and global demand.\par \par \uc2 Spatially, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the first quarter in most regions of Indonesia, except Sumatra and Java, was higher than in the previous quarter.\par \par \uc2 The highest growth was recorded in Sulawesi-Maluku-Papua (Sulampua), followed by Kalimantan, Bali-Nusa Tenggara (Balinusra), Java, and Sumatra.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Indonesia"s inflation rate was maintained in line with the target of 2.5 percent plus minus one percent. According to data from Statistics Indonesia (BPS), in April 2024, annual inflation reached 3 percent yoy, while calendar-year inflation was recorded at 1.19 percent year to date.\par \par \uc2 For inflation control, \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  coordination between the central government and the governments of several regions is continuing to be improved under the National Food Inflation Control Movement (GNPIP) by the central and regional inflation control teams.\par \par \uc2 Overall, Indonesia"s financial system stability was maintained in the first quarter, supported by \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary policies and a stable financial sector. The positive performance was bolstered by a resilient financial system and sustained domestic consumption, especially during the General Elections period and religious holidays.\par \par \uc2 However, fast-changing global dynamics must continue to be monitored to maintain sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Several global risks will still need to be faced in the future, including the direction of the US \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  or the Fed"s \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , especially its benchmark interest rate, escalation of geopolitical tensions, and global supply chain disruption that has not yet fully recovered.\par \par \uc2 To this end, monetary and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  coordination is continuing to be strengthened to maintain the stability of the macroeconomy and the momentum of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  synergy among members of the Financial System Stability Committee (KSSK) is continuing to be pushed to maintain the stability of the financial system and boost credit or financing to businesses.\par \par \uc2 The KSSK will continue to carry out forward-looking assessments of the latest \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial sector performance, in line with the risk posed by increasing global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and geopolitical turmoil.\par \par \uc2 The committee is committed to continuing to bolster coordination and synergy as well as increase vigilance against the risks of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial market as well as geopolitical turmoil, including their impact on the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial sectors.\par \par \uc2 The KSSK comprises the Minister of Finance, the Governor of \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2 , head of the board of commissioners of the \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK)\uc2 , and head of the board of commissioners of the Indonesia Deposit Insurance Corporation (LPS).\par \par \uc2 Therefore, through collaboration, synergy, and quick response of institutions and stakeholders, as well as support from the community, Indonesia can continue to anticipate and face the risks of impacts from global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and turmoil on the country"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 These could help Indonesia continue on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth path amid shifting global dynamics.\par \par \uc2 (T.KR-RAP/A/R013/R013) 10-05-2024 21:37:11\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240510ek5a001jl\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Post-Election Indonesian  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  Growth Challenges\b0\par\par\uc2 605 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 May 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 INDONESIA\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  remains relatively robust. The latest data for the first quarter of 2024 shows the country\u8217\'20\'19s Gross Domestic Product (GDP) expanding by 5.11 percent year to date, surpassing the 5.04 percent recorded in the fourth quarter of 2023.\par \par \uc2 Several factors have contributed to this notable growth. One significant catalyst was the massive influx of funds into the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  during the general elections in February. Trillions of rupiah were spent on campaigns by presidential and tens of thousands of \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  candidates across the country. This substantial funding stimulated small businesses and household consumption, thereby stimulating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity.\par \par \uc2 The government certainly played a significant role as well. Before the election, substantial social assistance funds had been disbursed. This injection of funds acted as a booster, increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  among low-income households. Additionally, a considerable portion of the government\u8217\'20\'19s expenses was allocated to the general election, reaching even the most remote parts of the country. Government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  surged by 19.9 percent compared to the previous quarter. This notable increase propelled government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to become the largest component of GDP in the first quarter of 2024.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth figures are more suitable as historical records, reflecting past performance. Financial markets have already factored in this past growth. For investment decisions, the more crucial indicator is what comes next. What will \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance be in the ongoing quarter, and what lies ahead?\par \par \uc2 Notably, for the second quarter of 2024 and subsequent quarters, election \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not provide an additional boost. Consequently, investors cannot expect significant increases in government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , depriving the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of an extra growth \b \highlight22\uc2 stimulus\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Another challenge on the horizon is the sluggish recovery of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s export commodity prices, which has led to a narrowing trade surplus or even a potential \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Persistent trends in this direction could further depreciate the rupiah, causing the prices of the US dollar and other foreign currencies to rise.\par \par \uc2 Externally, conditions remain unfavorable for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Global financial markets continue to be highly volatile, with ongoing speculation surrounding the \uc2 Federal Reserve\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s interest rate decisions. An endless tug-of-war between the Fed and the market seems to be underway.\par \par \uc2 This \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has led to instability in the rupiah\u8217\'20\'19s value, complicating corporate decision-making. Consequently, numerous investment decisions have been postponed, potentially weakening \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 Market volatility and the depreciating rupiah prompted \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  to raise its benchmark interest rate, the BI Rate, at the end of last month. While this increase is intended to curb the rupiah\u8217\'20\'19s weakening, it has adverse implications for growth. Higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  lead to increased borrowing costs for businesses and consumers, dampening purchasing power and slowing \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  elevate the risk of non-performing loans, necessitating banks to bolster bad debt provisions, which erodes profits. Increased borrowing costs also dampen demand for credit. Therefore, higher BI rates increase risks, reducing banks\u8217\'20\'19 business volume and profitability.\par \par \uc2 Hence, we witnessed the stocks of various banks, both private and state-owned, plummet in the past two weeks. For instance, shares of \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2  (BMRI) fell by as much as nine percent in just a week, as of Thursday, May 8. Similarly, the stock price of \uc2 Bank BCA\uc2 , the market darling in the banking sector, also experienced a decline of 4.34 percent.\par \par \uc2 These challenges underscore the threat of declining growth facing Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Meanwhile, the ongoing political transition adds to the prevailing \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Markets await clearer signals from President-elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  on how his administration will tackle these formidable challenges.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/05/13/860928/860928_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240513ek5c0000j\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
