\par\par \b \uc2 Navigating turbulent waters: Strategies for resilient banking\b0\par\par\uc2 1,016 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Darmo Wicaksono , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The Financial Services Authority (OJK) issued \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 5/2024 at the end of March, which focuses on determining the supervision status and addressing issues in commercial banks. This \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is crucial as Indonesia grapples with an increasing risk of a banking crisis stemming from the depreciation of the rupiah.\par \par \uc2 The rupiah's exchange rate against the United States dollar has surged above 16,000, surpassing a critical psychological threshold and nearing the lowest level observed during the 1998 monetary crisis at 16,800.\par \par \uc2 This development triggered immediate repercussions, with major bank stocks experiencing a decline when the stock exchange resumed trading after the Idul Fitri holiday in April. For instance, on the first trading day of May, the Joint Stock Exchange Index dropped by 1.61 percent to 7,117.42. Notably, Bank Mandiri and Bank BNI witnessed significant falls of 8.33 and 8 percent, respectively, in the LQ45 index representing 45 selected companies with strong liquidity.\par \par \uc2 The global macroeconomic landscape has further exacerbated the situation, with the US grappling with soaring inflation levels well beyond market expectations and the \uc2 US Federal Reserve\uc2 's target of 2 percent. This high inflation makes it challenging to anticipate interest rate reductions by the Fed. Additionally, escalating tensions in the Middle East have contributed to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Despite the rupiah's depreciation, stress tests conducted jointly by \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  and the OJK revealed that the weakening currency has not substantially impacted bank capital. This can be attributed to national banks' favorable net foreign exchange position, with the ratio of foreign currency assets to liabilities relative to capital standing at 1 to 5 percent, significantly below BI's 20 percent threshold.\par \par \uc2 Maintaining stability and ensuring the resilience of the banking sector amid such demanding \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions necessitates a thorough understanding of the implications and stipulations set forth in OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 5/2024.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  assumes a critical role in enhancing the oversight and management of commercial banks by particularly emphasizing the identification and resolution of potential liquidity, efficiency and profitability issues. A key focal point of the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is its emphasis on supervisory status to ensure that banks operate within the required regulatory framework and are prepared to effectively address financial challenges.\par \par \uc2 The guidelines outlined in the OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  aim to address liquidity concerns for banks to maintain an adequate level of liquidity, which is crucial to fulfill their obligations and mitigate potential risks, especially during \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  such as the current scenario with rupiah depreciation impacting bank liquidity. The \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  emphasizes the importance of setting clear liquidity management parameters to enhance banking sector stability and reduce the risk of a liquidity shortage.\par \par \uc2 In terms of efficiency enhancement, the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  introduces measures to improve operational efficiency within commercial banks by streamlining processes and enhancing internal controls. These measures help lower costs and boost overall performance, which is particularly essential in a competitive and challenging \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  environment.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  also addresses profitability issues by setting requirements for banks to maintain a healthy level of profitability while efficiently managing risks. With the potential rise in the BI rate, banks are confronted with the challenge of balancing profitability with funding costs.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  sparked discussions and debates within Indonesia's banking sector. It serves as a cautionary signal to banks regarding the critical \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  situation and the need for prudence. One key aspect highlighted by the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the directive for banks to bolster their \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  to prepare for potential crises. Banks are mandated to uphold capital surcharges or boost their capital to 1-1.35 percent of weighted assets.\par \par \uc2 For instance, banks falling under the bank grouping based on Core Capital (KBMI) I category must maintain core capital of Rp 6 trillion (US$375 million) before the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 's enforcement. Undoubtedly, this new \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  presents a significant challenge for small banks; nonetheless, it underscores the regulatory authorities' dedication to fortifying the national banking system, a goal aligned with BI's objectives.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia currently houses 105 conventional and sharia banks, a decrease from the 237 banks during the 1988 monetary crisis. Ensuring the stability and resilience of the banking sector is crucial. The promotion of fewer, larger banks over numerous smaller banks is suggested as a potential solution to enhance the Indonesian banking system's strength.\par \par \uc2 A significant portion of Indonesia's banking assets is held by a few major banks categorized under KBMI IV, such as \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2 , \uc2 Bank BNI\uc2 , Bank BRI and Bank Central Asia (BCA), collectively representing half of the national banking system's assets.\par \par \uc2 The concentration of assets underscores the importance of consolidating the banking sector to improve overall stability and efficiency.Considering the capital requirements outlined in the OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , smaller banks may encounter difficulties meeting the specified criteria. In such a scenario, regulatory authorities may encourage these banks to explore options such as an acquisition or merger with other institutions, aiming to streamline the banking sector, foster consolidation and enhance sector resilience.\par \par \uc2 The OJK is enhancing the implementation of the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  by collaborating closely with key stakeholders, including BI, the Indonesia Deposit Insurance Corporation (LPS) and the Finance Ministry. By fostering coordination with BI, the OJK can leverage expertise in monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and financial stability to assess regulatory impacts on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This collaboration allows for a comprehensive approach to address liquidity and capital adequacy requirements in commercial banks.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, partnering with the LPS strengthens depositor protection mechanisms and boosts confidence in the banking sector. The OJK and the LPS work together to enhance the resilience of financial institutions and safeguard depositor interests by aligning regulatory frameworks and sharing risk management practices.\par \par \uc2 OJK \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 5/2024 defines an intermediary bank as a tool of resolution owned by the LPS to accept troubled bank asset transfers, established under specific conditions to address financial system threats. Engaging with the Finance Ministry ensures regulatory coherence and alignment with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  objectives, benefiting from consultation on \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies and frameworks.\par \par \uc2 ____________________\par \par \uc2 A senior economist at the International Department, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240514ek5f00007\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
