\par\par \uc2 INTERNATIONAL NEWS\par \b \uc2 APEC\uc2  GDP EXPANDED TO 3.5 PERCENT IN 2023,  \highlight22\uc2 UNCERTAINTIES \highlight\uc2  LOOM LARGE\b0\par\par\uc2 578 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 May 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Yuni Arisandy Sinaga\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - \uc2 APEC\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s gross domestic product (GDP) grew by 3.5 percent in 2023 as compared to 2.6 percent in 2022, though there will be a moderation in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2025 and 2026 due to geopolitical \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 It was stated in the latest report by the APEC \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Support Unit (PSU), according to a release issued by the APEC Secretariat and received here on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 "\uc2 APEC\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth is outpacing the 3.2 percent global growth. Government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  as well as the health services sector, especially the solid recovery of travel and tourism, have also contributed to this expansion," Carlos Kuriyama, director of the APEC \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Support Unit, stated.\par \par \uc2 "However, we are seeing a moderation in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2025 and 2026 due to geopolitical \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , trade protectionism, and fluctuations in commodity prices," Kuriyama remarked.\par \par \uc2 He affirmed that such challenges call for stronger multilateral cooperation between \uc2 APEC\uc2  member economies.\par \par \uc2 The inflation rate has eased steadily, posting an average of 3.9 percent last year as compared to 5.9 percent in 2022. It is expected to decrease further to 2.9 percent this year. However, the report cautioned economies not to let their guards down.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWith inflation showing signs of moderation, economies are expected to lean toward easing their monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rates to support growth,\u8221\'20\'1D Rhea C. Hernando, an analyst with the \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Support Unit, stated.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CNevertheless, economies need to stay alert to dampen inflationary pressures that could come from possible supply chain disruptions, such as reduced crude stock in key oil-producing economies, alongside ongoing geopolitical issues as well as exchange rate movements,\u8221\'20\'1D Hernando cautioned.\par \par \uc2 The report noted that in the past 12 months, 17 currencies in the \uc2 APEC\uc2  region have depreciated against the US dollar, ranging from -2.1 percent to -16.7 percent as of April 2024.\par \par \uc2 Another development to watch out for is the extended drought and increased maritime risks observed at the Panama and Suez Canals.\par \par \uc2 These choke points have led to a significant escalation in freight costs, reaching their peak in late January of 2024 and persisting at levels 50 percent higher than usual as of April 2024 as compared to a year ago.\par \par \uc2 "\b \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  have dampened trade activity in 2023, affecting \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  decisions and causing sluggish demand," Glacer Ni\u241\'00\'F1o A. Vasquez, a researcher with the \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Support Unit, stated.\par \par \uc2 "Accumulation of restrictive and unpredictable trade policies, such as anti-dumping measures, tariffs, and countervailing duties, continued to increase, which can further curb trade activity," Vasquez added.\par \par \uc2 Trade numbers are reported to have contracted in 2023, although the report foresees a rebound on the horizon.\par \par \uc2 The volume of \uc2 APEC\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s merchandise exports grew marginally by 0.3 percent, while imports contracted by 1.4 percent. The value of merchandise trade fell by -6 percent for exports and -6.7 percent for imports.\par \par \uc2 "Looking ahead, strengthening cooperation in the face of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  is critical to overcoming obstacles and continuing the progress toward sustainable and inclusive growth that we have made since the COVID-19 pandemic," Kuriyama remarked.\par \par \uc2 "By remaining vigilant, reducing debt and rebuilding buffers, implementing productivity-enhancing structural reforms, and deepening cooperation, \uc2 APEC\uc2  economies can effectively navigate the complexities of the current landscape, strengthening \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals and regional ties for a future that is inclusive, sustainable, and prosperous," he concluded.\par \par \uc2 (T.Y012/C/A075/A075) 16-05-2024 14:14:38\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240516ek5g000dx\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
