\par\par \b \uc2 Shaking the Foreign Ministry out of its comfort zone?\b0\par\par\uc2 1,003 \uc2 words\par \uc2 18 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Desra Percaya , London,\par \par \uc2 In his thought-provoking piece, published in The Jakarta Post on May 13, Endy Bayuni, a long-time friend of the Foreign Ministry, suggested president-elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  consider a non-career diplomat to head the institution in his cabinet.\par \par \uc2 While each writer may have his or her own argument on the merits of who they believe best to lead Indonesia's diplomacy, what strikes me the most is the main reasoning behind Endy's suggestion, which is to "shake the ministry out of its comfort zone to come up with policies that reflect the current geopolitical reality".\par \par \uc2 Fully recognizing president-elect Prabowo's prerogative to appoint cabinet members, I question myself whether the ministry and its diplomats have become too complacent and by becoming so, have found themselves sitting in a comfort zone over the years.\par \par \uc2 As an Indonesian diplomat with more than three decades in this line of duty, I know for certain that it is against our nature to allow ourselves to live in a comfort zone amid dynamic global situations.\par \par \uc2 The international milieu that we are living in continues to change from era to era, and therefore the capacity to adapt and collaborate among various stakeholders is a must.\par \par \uc2 This was evident during our struggle for independence, where diplomats and soldiers worked side by side to fight for our sovereignty and to gain international recognition.\par \par \uc2 Today's challenges are indeed more complex and multidimensional. Foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  formulations and execution must fully take into account the interplay between domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and security interests with regional and international developments.\par \par \uc2 As such, underpinned by a set of principles and goals found within a democratic political system, our diplomats--career and non-career--continue to promote activism in diplomacy to seize new \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political opportunities.\par \par \uc2 Living in continuous global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  with perennial challenges, such as protracted conflicts and fierce \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  competition, I can say with confidence that the politik luar negeri bebas aktif (independent and active principle) has allowed Indonesia to maneuver its diplomacy in a prudent and strategic manner.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 Lowy Institute\uc2  recognizes Indonesia's diplomatic achievements against such difficult circumstances. Its 2023 Asia Power Index report mentioned Indonesia as "one of only six countries in the region to upward change in its overall score, albeit below pre-pandemic levels".\par \par \uc2 It also stated, "Indonesia's diplomatic influence continues to show strong growth reflecting its important role in ASEAN and as the 2022 chair of the G20."\par \par \uc2 I may further argue that the prudent and strategic approach adopted by Indonesia's leaders has contributed to the rise of the country as a middle power on the international stage in the last 20 years.\par \par \uc2 This recognition does not make us in the ministry complacent, let alone resort to being idle in our comfort zone.\par \par \uc2 Looking back to the ideas and examples articulated by my good friend, Endy Bayuni, I wish to make the following observations.\par \par \uc2 First, on ASEAN. Let us not forget that from the outset, our investment in ASEAN has always been geared toward securing our immediate region.\par \par \uc2 Yet, keeping ASEAN secure and vibrant is undoubtedly more challenging in the current geopolitical landscape and regional developments.\par \par \uc2 Second, on Indonesia's diplomacy in the wider region of Indo-Pacific.\par \par \uc2 While keeping the strategic importance of ASEAN, we actively engage the region beyond. Our ASEAN Outlook on the Indo-Pacific (AOIP) is part of a long-term evolving vision, and as its initiator, Indonesia's role is vital.\par \par \uc2 The overarching strategy of the AOIP provides us with dual strategic purposes in the national and regional realms, in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and politico-security terms.\par \par \uc2 Third, on a more defense-oriented foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . While I fully agree with the need to continuously increase Indonesia's defense capabilities, it is equally important as an emerging middle power for Indonesia to enhance its role as a peacemaker.\par \par \uc2 Coupled with stronger \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  foundations, our smart defense diplomacy will strengthen our national resilience. Indeed, this is aligned with our national interest as the principal guidance of our foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Fourth, on Indonesia's leadership at the global level. As a practitioner, I acknowledge the high expectations from many quarters of Indonesia's global leadership.\par \par \uc2 To be able to play such a role, one needs to earn it through consistency and honesty, and Indonesia has been and will continue to make contributions through diplomatic activism.\par \par \uc2 As a middle power, Indonesia has further earned respect internationally, as its position is heard and considered on issues such as protracted conflicts in the Middle East, prolonged war in Ukraine, and other global challenges.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's position and voice on global issues are highly valued and sought after by other countries--big or small, superpower or middle power. This is because our leaders and diplomats have consistently served as earnest bridge-builders for many over these past few decades. Standing on the sidelines is not an option for our diplomats.\par \par \uc2 Fifth, in the context of democratic Indonesia, and in the interest of transparency and accountability, the call for a foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  white paper is a valid one.\par \par \uc2 In the meantime, the Foreign Minister's Annual Press Statement serves as a platform to inform the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  about Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  direction, priorities and implementation. I understand that this practice is well-received by the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 As a final thought, it is encouraging to see growing \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  interest, attention and expectations in how Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and diplomatic machinery can be recalibrated in the next cabinet.\par \par \uc2 Let us not forget that with his robust experience, credentials and statesmanship, president-elect Prabowo comprehends very well the current and future challenges as well as opportunities for Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 He has all the wisdom to decide who will be the next foreign minister, whose priority is none other but to serve the nation and the national interests.\par \par \uc2 _________________\par \par \uc2 Indonesian ambassador to the United Kingdom, Ireland and the \uc2 International Maritime Organization\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240517ek5i00005\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
