\par\par \b \uc2 BI keeps interest rate unchanged as rupiah stabilizes\b0\par\par\uc2 Aditya Hadi, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 526 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  has kept its benchmark interest rate unchanged at 6.25 percent as it sees the rupiah stabilizing thanks to increased capital inflows following last month's 25-basis-point (bps) rate hike.\par \par \uc2 Briefing reporters after the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's two-day monthly monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  meeting, BI Governor \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2  noted an increased probability of the \uc2 United States Federal Reserve\uc2  cutting itsinterest rate by the end of this year.\par \par \uc2 "At the same time, the worsening geopolitical situation [seen] in April has not continued. A decline in US treasury yields compared withmid-April has caused capital inflowsto emerging countries and reduced the pressure on local currencies," Perry said on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 In last month's briefing, BI decided to lift itsbenchmark BI Rate by 25 bps to 6.25 percent. It also raised the rates for its deposit facility and lending facility by the same amount to 5.5 and 7 percent, respectively.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  characterized the move as a "preemptive measure" in light of global risks caused by the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  outlook for monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the US and geopolitical tension in the Middle East.\par \par \uc2 In times of conflict, investors tend to reallocate funds to so-called safe-haven assets, such as the US dollar and gold, resulting in money flowing out of emerging markets and weighing on the countries' currencies.\par \par \uc2 In April, right before BI announced its interest rate hike, the rupiah touched a multiyear low of Rp 16,265 per US dollar.\par \par \uc2 According to the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the rupiah strengthenedby 1.66 percent between the end of April and May 21 thanks to foreign capital inflows into Indonesian government bonds, underlining the effectiveness of the BI Rate hike in April.\par \par \uc2 Perry noted that the rupiah, while still down 3.74 percent year-to-date, had done better than the currencies of other emerging countries, such as the Philippine peso, South Korea's won and Thailand's baht, which had depreciated by 4.91 percent, 5.52 percent and 5.59 percent, respectively.\par \par \uc2 "In the future, we expect the rupiah to continue to be stable with a tendency to get stronger, pushed by better yields after the benchmark rate hike, a decrease in risk premium, better \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  prospects and the \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2 's commitment to keep the rupiah stable," Perry said.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  expects domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of between 4.7 and 5.5 percent this year, after a year-on-year increase of 5.11 percent logged in the first quarter due to strong consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  during Ramadan and the election, as well as increased government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Private lender Bank Danamon economist Irman Faiz wrote in an analysis on Wednesday that a 100-bps spread between the Fed's federal funds rate and the BI Rate was sufficient to keep the rupiah stable.\par \par \uc2 "Therefore, we expect BI to hold the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate throughout this year, with a 25-bps federal funds rate cut in December. Then, BI will have room to follow the Fed's cut cycle in the first quarter next year at the earliest," Irman said.\par \par \u