\par\par \b \uc2 Embracing humanity: A call to rethink refugee policies in RI\b0\par\par\uc2 997 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Alldo Fellix Januardy , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 In recent months, the shores of Aceh in Indonesia have seen a steady influx of boats carrying refugees, contributing to the existing population of displaced individuals in the country. Once regarded as a safe haven for Rohingya refugees, Aceh has now adopted a stance of aloofness, treating these refugees as outsiders rather than fellow humans in need of compassion and support.\par \par \uc2 According to \uc2 United Nations High Commission for Refugees\uc2  (\uc2 UNHCR\uc2 ) data, Indonesia currently hosts 13,458 refugees from 51 different countries, with around 8 percent of these being Rohingya refugees. Most of the rest are from Afghanistan.\par \par \uc2 Despite not being a signatory to the 1951 Refugee Convention, Indonesia has become a critical transit point for refugees, owing to its vast archipelago consisting of 17,000 islands and an extensive coastline spanning 99,000 kilometers that provides ample opportunities for boat entry.\par \par \uc2 However, this transient status has turned into a prolonged limbo for many refugees, with some being stranded in Indonesia for up to eight years, and others living in the country for over 15 years with no prospects of resettlement.\par \par \uc2 Why does the resettlement process to the destination take years? Well, let us just leave the question for the \uc2 UNHCR\uc2  and state members to answer.\par \par \uc2 While it is understandable that Indonesia, like other nations, harbors concerns about the strain refugees may place on limited resources, it is imperative to view this issue through a lens of shared humanity and moral responsibility.\par \par \uc2 Refugees do not choose to leave their homes; they are compelled to flee persecution, violence and conflict, often rooted in religious or ideological tensions.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has long been a crucial transit point for refugees fleeing conflict and persecution in their home countries.\par \par \uc2 However, as a nation that did not ratify the 1951 Refugee Convention, Indonesia's treatment of refugees has often been characterized by restrictions and limitations that hinder their integration and ability to lead dignified lives. The current \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  framework, which prohibits refugees from accessing education, \uc2 employment and social security\uc2  benefits, reflects a pragmatic but arguably inhumane approach.\par \par \uc2 This situation raises questions about the efficacy and humanity of Indonesia's refugee policies. While acknowledging resource constraints, it is time for the Indonesian government to shift from a purely assistance-based approach to empowerment and integration. In fact, several individuals and organizations have led by example, showing the other side of the coin when it comes to handling refugees' well-being.\par \par \uc2 Social businesses such as Liberty Society and grassroots efforts like the Refugee and Asylum Seekers Information Centre (RAIC) Indonesia highlight the potential for refugees to achieve empowerment and self-reliance.\par \par \uc2 Refugees often face \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , made worse by limited job opportunities that often confine them to charitable work. This dependence can lead to mental health challenges.\par \par \uc2 Recognizing this issue, Liberty Society empowers refugees, aiming to equip them with practical skills that facilitate their resettlement process. The social business was recently featured in Forbes Asia's 30 under 30 2024 in the social impact category.\par \par \uc2 Iranian asylum seeker Mozhgan Moarefizadeh has experienced a similar life as an outsider in a foreign land. Due to her refugee status, she was denied basic needs during her stay in Indonesia for almost 15 years. Along with her friend Jafar Salemi, another Iranian refugee, she established RAIC, a volunteer-led initiative, a few years ago.\par \par \uc2 They rely on sporadic donations but have been overwhelmed with requests for aid from desperate refugees, indicating the pressing need for support. These efforts have received tremendous support from Indonesians, myself included, especially in providing medical and legal access.\par \par \uc2 The refugee-led organization once received funding worth US$3 million to support their work with other Southeast Asian refugee organizations. Mozghan's inspiring story was produced as a podcast titled "The Wait", which won Amnesty Australia Media Awards in 2021.\par \par \uc2 Situated in Bogor regency, West Java, lies a glimpse of hope for the refugees to get access to education: learning centers for refugee children such as RLC, RLN, Roshan and HELP initiated by fellow refugees along with Indonesians. These centers emphasize English-language education, which is crucial for potential resettlement.\par \par \uc2 These efforts show hope and commitment to a progressive refugee \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in Indonesia. As a Muslim-majority country, Indonesia is in a unique position to showcase solidarity and empathy by extending a helping hand to refugees.\par \par \uc2 This is not just a legal obligation but a moral imperative grounded in our collective values of compassion and justice.\par \par \uc2 Aceh, with its historical reputation as a refuge, can play a pivotal role in reshaping Indonesia's approach to refugees.\par \par \uc2 The province that enacts sharia can lead by example and become a beacon of hope and compassion for refugees in Indonesia and beyond.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  argument for refugee integration cannot be ignored. Recent studies have shown that refugees when allowed to work and access education, not only improve their livelihoods but also contribute significantly to the host country's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The studies illustrate a positive net \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  impact of refugees on the United States \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  over 15 years. Collectively, these groups have contributed a staggering $123.8 billion more than they have cost in governmental expenditures, highlighting their \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefit.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia can learn from models like Iran's inclusive education policies for refugee children and collaborate with organizations like the \uc2 UNHCR\uc2  to ensure quality education and employment opportunities for refugees by embracing a holistic approach to creating a conducive environment for refugees to thrive.\par \par \uc2 It is time to move beyond transient responses and embrace a vision of inclusivity and humanity. Aceh might have had a change of heart toward refugees recently, but perhaps a second thought is all it takes for a better change that will benefit us all.\par \par \uc2 ___________________\par \par \uc2 A managing partner at the Jakarta-based AVYA law firm, which has offered pro bono advice to various refugee foundations, and an advisor at RAIC Indonesia and Same Skies International. The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240524ek5p0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Special Updates\par \b \uc2 Minister Airlangga Reveals Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s Growth Strategies at 2024 Nikkei Forum\b0\par\par\uc2 566 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. Chief \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  recently talked about how Indonesia grew its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  amidst global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  at the 2024 Nikkei Forum.\par \par \uc2 According to Airlangga, Indonesia managed to maintain its \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth during the Covid-19 pandemic.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1COur \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been growing within a range of 5 percent year on year [yoy] since the second quarter of 2021,\u8221\'20\'1D Airlangga told the forum, as reported by a ministerial press release.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  also expanded by 5.11 percent this first quarter. The country\u8217\'20\'19s inflation stood at 3 percent in April. Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s gross domestic product (GDP) per capita has been growing since the pandemic as the government seeks to propel the figure to $5,500 this year.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIndonesia is pushing for stable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth through social and political stability. Of course, this serves as a great condition for both investors and businesses,\u8221\'20\'1D Airlangga said.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia today is currently shifting to a new administration as the government tries to ensure the continuity of existing programs. This includes the incumbent President Joko \u8220\'20\'1CJokowi\u8221\'20\'1D Widodo\u8217\'20\'19s efforts to propel Indonesia to a golden era by its centennial in 2045. To avoid being in the middle-income trap, Indonesia has prepared two scenarios. The first is a transformative scenario in which the country achieves a 6 percent growth each year to escape the middle-income trap by 2041. An optimistic scenario sees Indonesia escaping the middle-income trap by 2038 as long as its annual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth stands at 7 percent, according to Airlangga.\par \par \uc2 The senior minister added that Indonesia had also made structural reforms to improve its investment climate, among others, by launching the Job Creation Law. Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s membership bid to the Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Co-Operation and Development (\uc2 OECD\uc2 ) is set to drive more structural reforms. Indonesia is hoping to be a full-fledged \uc2 OECD\uc2  member in 3 years. \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms by referring to \uc2 OECD\uc2  standards will not only increase \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  predictability and transparency, but Indonesia will help determine the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  standards so that it becomes a benchmark for sustainable and quality investment, Airlangga said.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CHopefully we can achieve our target of $30,300 in GDP per capita in 2045 by adopting \uc2 OECD\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s standards,\u8221\'20\'1D Airlangga said.\par \par \uc2 To book robust growth, Indonesia will continue to adopt \u8220\'20\'1Cconventional growth engines\u8221\'20\'1D such as infrastructure development, food security, and international cooperation. But the country will also combine it with new growth engines such as massive industrialization, digitalization, and energy transition.\par \par \uc2 According to Airlangga, Indonesia has been engaging with the Comprehensive and Progressive Agreement for Trans-Pacific Partnership (CPTPP) and the Indo-Pacific \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Framework (IPEF) to expand markets and encourage increased investment. The minister also spoke of Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s domestic processing \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of its minerals as it seeks to play a pivotal role in the electric vehicle battery and renewable energy industries. Indonesia is home to \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  of nickel, copper, bauxite, and tin. These minerals are part of the renewable industry, space industry and even the defense industry.\par \par \uc2 "On energy transition, Indonesia --as one of the initiators of the Asia Zero Emission Community [AZEC]-- highlights the importance of inclusive funding for decarbonization cooperation and the transfer of low-carbon technology. Currently, there are at least 12 cooperation projects within the AZEC framework and 3 of them are already in the implementation stage," Airlangga said.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240525ek5p00005\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Slow Import Permit Issuance Leads to Garlic Price Hikes\b0\par\par\uc2 2,886 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 May 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 THE soaring price of garlic has forced the Presidential Staff Office to take action. Deputy III of the Presidential Chief of Staff Edy Priyono said that on Friday, May 17, his office summoned garlic importers who had received import permits but had less than 50 percent import realization. \u8220\'20\'1CThe results were presented during a coordination meeting on inflation control at the Home Affairs Ministry,\u8221\'20\'1D Edy told Tempo on Tuesday, May 21.\par \par \uc2 The Presidential Staff Office (KSP) summoned 40 importing companies, but only 17 were physically present. Fourteen companies participated in the meeting via a digital conference application, while nine were absent.\par \par \uc2 Edy said that the absent companies could not be reached because the government had the wrong contacts. This was unfortunate, he said, because the purpose of the meeting was to identify the problems that led to the hike in garlic prices. The Presidential Staff Office has categorized garlic as a food commodity with \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  price status and high inter-regional price disparities.\par \par \uc2 Edy Priyono, Deputy III of the Presidential Chief of Staff. ksp.go.id\par \par \uc2 The summoning of importers was a follow-up agenda after the Presidential Staff Office gathered officials from seven ministries and state agencies on Wednesday, May 8, 2024. The minutes of the meeting noted the government\u8217\'20\'19s statement that low import volumes caused high garlic prices. Overall, the volume of imported garlic is less than half of the total import permits issued by the government.\par \par \uc2 During the meeting, it was revealed that the Trade Ministry had issued import approvals (PI) to 56 companies to bring in 328,000 tons of garlic from overseas. This volume amounts to 122 percent of what is needed for five months. The import approvals were issued at the request of companies that received horticultural product import recommendations (RIPH) from the Agriculture Ministry, which issued RIPHs for 200,000 tons of garlic. The Trade Ministry and the Agriculture Ministry claimed that the large number of new importers was the reason for the delays in import realization.\par \par \uc2 Unloading imported garlic at the Kramat Jati Market, Jakarta, October 19, 2023. TEMPO/Tony Hartawan\par \par \uc2 However, the Presidential Staff Office noted signs that the high prices of garlic were linked to the slow issuance of import approvals. According to Edy, data obtained by the Presidential Staff Office showed that 13 out of 15 companies with zero imports of garlic had received their licenses only on May 6 and 13 this year. Claims regarding the low import realization rate due to the high number of new players were also refuted. Edy said that 13 companies present at the meeting with the Presidential Staff Office had only received import approvals for the first time. Five of them had already realized imports ranging from 21 to 41 percent of their quotas. \u8220\'20\'1CThere is no indication that new players are having difficulties with realizing imports,\u8221\'20\'1D said Edy.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, entrepreneurs stated that the low import realization rate is due to difficulties in obtaining garlic supplies from supplier countries like China. They claimed that the goods currently in China are last year\u8217\'20\'19s harvest stored in warehouses for months, resulting in inferior quality. Garlic supply is estimated to enter Indonesia in June after the harvesting season in China.\par \par \uc2 Edy estimated that garlic imports would arrive in Indonesia between mid-June and August. There are 11 importers who will conclude imports by August at the latest. Therefore, he explained, this condition needs to be anticipated to prevent stockpiling of imported garlic. \u8220\'20\'1CAccumulation of imports during this period can cause shortages in the following period.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Garlic was one of the commodities that were highlighted during a coordination meeting to curtail inflation chaired by the Home Affairs Ministry on Monday, May 20. The Statistics Indonesia (BPS) recorded that garlic prices experienced an inflation of 5.51 percent in April, accounting for 0.02 percent of the national inflation rate.\par \par \uc2 I Gusti Ketut Astawa, Deputy for Food Availability and Stabilization at the National Food Agency, said the import permits issued were in line with demand. As of Thursday, May 16, import permits have been issued for 349,000 tons of garlic, or 54 percent of the allocation determined in the limited coordination meeting of the Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  on December 13, 2023. The problem is that only 124,000 tons, or 19 percent, have been realized. Another problem is the low distribution volume of imported garlic, which has only reached 43,000 tons.\par \par \uc2 In addition to this problem, Astawa said that the price of garlic in China is still higher than last year. In March 2023, he explained, the price of garlic in China was 7.5 yuan per kilogram. Meanwhile, this month\u8217\'20\'19s price is 11.56 yuan per kilogram. With this price, the price of garlic in Indonesian ports could reach Rp28,000 (around US$1.74) per kilogram and the market price Rp36,000 (US$2.24) per kilogram. \u8220\'20\'1CRelatively higher,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Director of Basic Needs and Essential Commodities at the Trade Ministry, Bambang Wisnubroto, ensured that garlic supplies to markets have started increasing in the past few days to prevent the situation from worsening, although most are still below normal supply. He stated that the Trade Ministry continues to monitor import realizations based on quotas or permits issued, while expediting the issuance of import permits to increase supply.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 THE price of garlic has been on an upward trend since the end of last year. The National Food Agency\u8217\'20\'19s price panel shows that the average price of garlic at the trader level was Rp42,830 (US$2.67) per kilogram on Wednesday, May 22, far above the maximum retail price limit of Rp32,000 (US$1.99) per kilogram set by the Trade Ministry. This figure is much higher than the average price of Rp35,220 (US$2.19) per kilogram in May 2023 and last year\u8217\'20\'19s highest monthly average price of Rp39,990 (US$2.49) per kilogram.\par \par \uc2 The high price of garlic is attributed to limited supply. Monitoring by the Trade Ministry on Friday, May 17, showed that garlic supply at 14 out of 19 wholesale markets was still below normal. Bambang Wisnubroto stated that the average supply in the past week across 19 markets was 151 tons, whereas it is usually not less than 191 tons. \u8220\'20\'1CWe will continue to monitor,\u8221\'20\'1D he said during the coordination meeting on inflation control at the Home Affairs Ministry on Monday, May 20.\par \par \uc2 Garlic supply also drew government attention. In the coordination meeting on inflation control on Monday, May 13, Home Affairs Minister Tito Karnavian stated that the increasing price of garlic is not solely due to high prices from the countries of origin. \u8220\'20\'1CBut because our management is not good. Those who have been granted permits have not realized imports according to the target,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Dwi Andreas Santosa, a professor at the Bogor Agricultural Institute (IPB University), West Java, stated that the problem in garlic management arises from a mix-up between price stabilization programs and self-sufficiency programs. He gave an example that, in order to achieve self-sufficiency, the government imposes mandatory domestic garlic planting schemes for importers seeking RIPHs. Such a process, he continued, would slow down the import process. \u8220\'20\'1CIf imports are withheld, prices will surely soar,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 In 2019, import problems caused garlic prices to skyrocket. At that time, the retail price of garlic was nearly Rp65,000 (US$4.51) per kilogram, although the international price at the port was only Rp10,000 (US$0.69) per kilogram. Based on Andreas\u8217\'20\'19 calculations, the unreasonable price increase in March-May 2019 could have caused consumer losses of nearly Rp1 trillion (US$69.5 million).\par \par \uc2 Garlic in a stall at Pasar Besar in Madiun City, East Java, April 18, 2022. ANTARA/Siswowidodo\par \par \uc2 According to Andreas, the current conditions are different from 2019 because now the international price of garlic is also rising. Based on Andreas\u8217\'20\'19 records, the price of garlic upon arrival at the port has been climbing. From Rp16,000 (US$1.13) per kilogram in 2020, to Rp17,000 (US$1.08) per kilogram in 2022, and to Rp18,000 (US$1.16) last year. Today, the price has reached Rp30,000 (US$1.87) per kilogram. To overcome this problem, the government needs to separate the price stabilization program from its self-sufficiency ambitions.\par \par \uc2 Andreas said that controlling the price of garlic should not be difficult since most of the domestic demand is met by imports. Monthly garlic demand, he explained, tends to be stable, so imports can be carefully calculated. \u8220\'20\'1CIf the importers don\u8217\'20\'19t comply, just give them a slap on the wrist,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Recently, however, the government and the business community have been pointing fingers at each other over the issue. The government blames the slow implementation of imports as the cause of high prices, while entrepreneurs complain about the slow issuance of import permits. Jaya Sartika, a garlic importer, claimed to have obtained the RIPH and applied for the import approval letter (SPI) in January. \u8220\'20\'1CUntil today, the SPI has not been issued,\u8221\'20\'1D said the Chief Executive Officer (CEO) of Jaya Agra Barokah on Tuesday, May 21. Typically, Jaya explained, the SPI can be issued no later than 30 days after submission.\par \par \uc2 Jaya did not deny the information that quality and price issues have also made entrepreneurs who have received SPI more selective. In addition, he added, China will enter the harvest season this coming June. However, Jaya believes that if the government expedites the issuance of the permits, garlic supply to Indonesia could be higher and the price could be immediately controlled. \u8220\'20\'1CIf the permit is issued this week, we will immediately move so that the goods can come in,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Jaya is not the only trader who has not received the permit. The General Chair of the Indonesian Garlic and Root Vegetable Traders Association, Antonius Reinhard Batubara, said most of his members had not received SPI. \u8220\'20\'1CThe application period varies, some at the beginning of the year, others just recently,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Another importer, Sonny Kurniawan, a member of the Indonesian Fresh Fruit and Vegetable Importers-Exporters Association (Aseibssindo), said he had not received a RIPH, which is a prerequisite for submitting an import license application. As a result, Sonny has not received an import permit to date. He admitted to having difficulties applying for the RIPH because the application period was very short and used an open-close system. The slow issuance of import permits means that importers cannot immediately purchase goods from the country of origin, where prices continue to soar.\par \par \uc2 Because of these obstacles, Aseibssindo sent several letters to the Agriculture Ministry and the Trade Ministry. To the Trade Ministry, they requested that Trade Minister \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 36/2023 on Import Policies and Regulations, which is the basis for the Prohibition and Restriction Regulations, also known as lartas, be reviewed, especially for horticultural products such as fruits and onions. They also asked the Agriculture Ministry and the Trade Ministry to review the RIPH system.\par \par \uc2 Aseibssindo General Chair Ayub A. Fina said his association actually supports the RIPH as a tool for monitoring imported horticultural products. However, he explained that Aseibssindo members face difficulties in obtaining such recommendations. \u8220\'20\'1CInstead of not having the necessary paperwork to do business, we submitted a request to review the regulations.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 At the end of April, the Trade Ministry issued \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 7/2024, which updated the rules on import policies and regulations. In the latest \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the ministry no longer requires a RIPH in the application process for most horticultural products. However, this provision does not apply to garlic.\par \par \uc2 In the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government still requires an RIPH containing a verification report, recommendations or technical considerations from the Agriculture Ministry as a condition for issuing an import permit for garlic. According to Arif Sulistiyo, Director of Imports at the Trade Ministry, the reason for this is that garlic has been included in the transitional commodity balance scheme since 2023, so there needs to be verification from the ministry or the agricultural commodity development institution before an import permit is issued.\par \par \uc2 Member of the Indonesian Ombudsman, Yeka Hendra Fatika, said that RIPH should no longer be a condition for applying for import permits. The reason is that the institution in charge of food safety is no longer the Agriculture Ministry, but the National Food Agency. The authority for inspections is no longer with the Agriculture Ministry, but with the Indonesian Quarantine Agency. \u8220\'20\'1CAdministrative documents such as permits do not require RIPH,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 AN investigation by the Indonesian Ombudsman found maladministration and alleged misconduct in the importation of garlic, both in the issuance of RIPH by the Agriculture Ministry and in the issuance of SPI by the Trade Ministry. The Ombudsman published its final investigation report (LAHP) on the alleged neglect of legal duties by the Trade Ministry on October 16, 2023, while the investigative LAHP on the initiative regarding garlic RIPH was issued at the end of March 2024.\par \par \uc2 In the case of SPI, the Ombudsman found several pieces of information, including that certain parties within the Trade Ministry had interfered in the process of issuing garlic import permits, resulting in imports not being carried out in accordance with procedures. There were also reports that certain parties in the ministry had intimidated several garlic importers, telling them not to apply for import permits for more than 5,000 tons. These individuals also asked the importers not to file complaints with any party about problems with the issuance of SPI. If a complaint is made, the permit will not be issued.\par \par \uc2 A merchant stacks sacks of garlic at Senen Market, Jakarta, January 12. TEMPO/Tony Hartawan\par \par \uc2 Other information received by the Ombudsman came from a complainant who said he had received an offer from someone claiming to be able to issue an SPI for garlic at a cost of Rp4,500 to Rp5,000 (US$0.28-0.31) per kilogram. \u8220\'20\'1CIn dealing with this information, the Ombudsman has fully handed it over to law enforcement authorities as the more competent party and related agencies to investigate or conduct further inquiries,\u8221\'20\'1D said Yeka Hendra Fatika on October 17, 2023.\par \par \uc2 In the case of the RIPH, the Ombudsman found maladministration in the form of neglect of legal duties, lack of competence, and excessive use of authority. This maladministration resulted in prolonged permit issuance, discrimination, procedural deviations, and incompetent garlic RIPH service implementation.\par \par \uc2 According to the Ombudsman, the Agriculture Ministry, as the reported party, has been incompetent in supervising the implementation of RIPH services and mandatory planting, which could lead to corrupt practices.\par \par \uc2 In addition, Yeka said, weak supervision and evaluation by superiors and those in charge at the Directorate-General of Horticulture is a form of neglect of their legal duty to supervise the online services of the RIPH system. Based on these findings of maladministration, the Ombudsman issued recommendations for corrective action. \u8220\'20\'1CIf they are not implemented, we will submit recommendations to the president,\u8221\'20\'1D said Yeka.\par \par \uc2 Tempo contacted Muhammad Taufiq Ratule, Secretary of the Directorate-General of Horticulture at the Agriculture Ministry, and Arif Sulistiyo, Director of Imports at the Trade Ministry, for comment on the allegations of levies in the issuance of RIPH or SPI. Both denied reports of levies in import licensing.\par \par \uc2 Regarding the RIPH of garlic, Arif said that these requirements are in line with Presidential \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 32/2022 on Commodity Balance. Based on this \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Arif said, the government has established commodity balance sheets for rice, sugar, beef, salt and fisheries. For commodities that do not yet have a commodity balance, export and import recommendations will be issued through the commodity balance information system. \u8220\'20\'1CGarlic is among the commodities that do not yet have commodity balances,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 The Coordinating Ministry for the \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has held a series of coordination meetings. In the fourth week of November 2022, the government set the transitional horticultural commodity balance. Arif said that garlic was included in the transitional commodity balance in 2023, so it needs to be reviewed by the Agriculture Ministry. I Gusti Ketut Astawa, Deputy for Food Availability and Stabilization at the National Food Agency, said that the plan is to include garlic in the commodity balance in 2025.\par \par \uc2 However, IPB University professor Dwi Andreas Santosa suggested removing the quota system for garlic imports as a solution to stabilize prices and supply. \u8220\'20\'1CFree imports and prices will stabilize,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. The proposal was also echoed in a discussion by the Business Competition Supervisory Commission on Tuesday, May 21.\par \par \uc2 Andreas said that import exemption would force importers to compete, which would lead to fair prices. According to him, the implementation of the quota system has resulted in abnormal profits, leading to uncontrolled market prices. If the government still hopes to achieve self-sufficiency, it can introduce a \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  system for imports. The funds could be used to improve farmers\u8217\'20\'19 welfare. \u8220\'20\'1CNot through compulsory planting but by not regulating prices.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/05/26/861874/861874_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \u