\par\par \b \uc2 Discourse: Indonesia-EU trade pact doable but requires 'give and take'\b0\par\par\uc2 1,049 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 Established in 2014, the European Union-ASEAN Business Council (EU-ABC) serves as a platform for European businesses within the region. As an independent body, it works to promote changes in policies, rules and regulations that facilitate European investment and business development across ASEAN.\par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post's Ruth Dea Juwita sat down with EU-ASEAN Business Council executive director Chris Humphrey during his visit to Jakarta on May 15 to talk about progress on trade negotiations and about business strategies for navigating Indonesian rules on local content and imports as well as the EU's \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  on deforestation (EUDR).\par \par \uc2 Question: Is there any progress on the Indonesia-European Union Comprehensive \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Partnership Agreement (IEU-CEPA)? We haveheard reportsitis dead in the water.\par \par \uc2 Answer: Indonesia and the EU have been negotiating the IEU-CEPA for seven years now. I'm not sure the finalization is going to happen, because the deadline for completion is Oct. 19, [and] the new government takes office then, which requires a renewal of the negotiation mandate. The new president might bring different ideas, and the future remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  until the new administration settles in.\par \par \uc2 Negotiations with Indonesia remain ongoing with some holding onto hope for completion before President \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2 's departure. But I'm not. The EU would tell you it's a lack of progress on things like government procurement practices, treatment of state-owned enterprises, local content requirements, commodity trade imbalances and other significant issues.\par \par \uc2 What is the issue with the local content requirements?\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  of local content requirements is a major concern. I know firms that have established operations in Indonesia under one set of rules only to be surprised later with demands for increased local content, which keeps changing from 20 to 30 to 40 percent, forcing them to scramble for solutions.\par \par \uc2 A perfect solution would be clear, transparent \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  tenders with fair competition through open bidding processes. The EU might be willing to compromise, but European businesses need a genuine chance to win contracts, even against state-owned enterprises.\par \par \uc2 If Indonesia really wants to do business with Europe, there will need to be a little bit of give and take on both sides. We are in a position where a rough diamond is better than no diamond at all. If the deal provides market access, lower tariffs, more certainty on import licenses and a more open service sector, then it's better than no deal.\par \par \uc2 What about Indonesia's import curbs? Do they hamper European businesses and investment coming to Indonesia?\par \par \uc2 If you can't be certain that you're going to be able to import materials you need and you're not too sure when the phone calls are coming to say you need to increase your local content, that becomes a massive issue. Imagine investing in a factory only to be unsure if you'll be able to import the materials needed to keep it running.\par \par \uc2 I can understand Indonesia's goal to source supplies locally to create jobs and retain value within the country, but this strategy only works if the local \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  can provide the required quality andquantity.\par \par \uc2 If negotiations are stalled between the two, would it not be easier to have an ASEAN-EU trade agreement?\par \par \uc2 No. They have tried to negotiate it and then stopped trying, because there was a big ambition disconnect between what the EU and ASEAN thought they could deliver. The EU wanted a region-to-region deal mirroring the agreements with Singapore and Vietnam, which cover not just core trade issues but also nontrade areas like sustainability, labor rights and human rights.\par \par \uc2 But it was just too difficult to negotiate with 10 member states, because the differences between the members were too great. Some weren't ready or willing to negotiate this wide-ranging agreement.\par \par \uc2 HaveEU-initiated trade disputes at the \uc2 World Trade Organization (WTO)\uc2  over Indonesian palm oil and nickel hampered negotiations ontheIEU-CEPA?\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian negotiators have been pretty good at separating issues like the palm oil dispute, deforestation concerns and the nickel dispute from free-trade agreement negotiations. But, of course, there's some bleed across, particularly at the political level.\par \par \uc2 The palm oil dispute has been over-criticized and misrepresented. There was never a ban on [Indonesian] palm oil; the issue was specifically about using palm oil for biofuels, targeting a particular segment of exports. Indonesia portrayed it as a ban, which it never was, and the \uc2 European Commission\uc2  failed to effectively communicate this. They got away with it because no one in Europe wanted to challenge them on it.\par \par \uc2 They're happier with Malaysia than they are with Indonesia because [Malaysia] has implemented strong sustainability certification processes, including standards for traceability, labour rights, child labor and land use rights. Although the \uc2 European Commission\uc2  cannot formally recognize Malaysia's certification, they're beginning to accept it. I think Indonesia could benefit from adopting similar measures.\par \par \uc2 The deforestation directive is a whole different ballgame. It's widely accepted that deforestation is harmful, but the implementation and cost of compliance is still a problem. The Commission needs to build bridges with Southeast Asian countries and others, providing more explanations, support, and [being] a bit more receptive to different ideas within the ASEAN context.\par \par \uc2 Will the EU-ABC help businesses navigate the EUDR?\par \par \uc2 Yes. We have positioned ourselves to be a communications bridge between the \uc2 European Commission\uc2  and ASEAN governments to address these communication problems, so you pass information in both directions. We also have a joint working group between the EU and ASEAN member states that functions well, as well as visits from the EU directorate general for the environment to discuss the issues.\par \par \uc2 But we still hear concerns especially from Indonesia. We hear these concerns voiced during our regular business missions to the region, and the EU green deal regularly comes up in meetings with Indonesian government officials.\par \par \uc2 It's important to remember that we are an independent business body, separate from the \uc2 European Commission\uc2 . We sympathize with Indonesia's concerns and we relay messages to the Commission to find alternative methods to reach the goal, because it also causes anxiety for European businesses, particularly those operating in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240528ek5t0000b\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
