\par\par \b \uc2 Anticipating \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2 's foreign  \highlight22\uc2 economic policy \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 990 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Noto Suoneto , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Indonesia will enter a new chapter of governance under president-elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  from October of this year to October 2029. Prabowo is expected to be a leader with more of a foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  focus than his soon-to-be predecessor President \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Months before his official inauguration, Prabowo has visited China, Japan, Malaysia and the Middle East, where he also spoke at the Qatar \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Forum.\par \par \uc2 At that forum in Doha, Prabowo again repeated the same nationalistic narrative of Indonesia's domestic and foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , with the line, "every country in the world will fight or protect the national core interests of its people" in reply to a question about Indonesia's tendency toward protectionism. That line sounded consistent with what he pledged during the election campaign period.\par \par \uc2 His vision of Indonesia's gross domestic product (GDP) growth is also very ambitious, intending to achieve 8 percent growth within two to three years of his presidency. This figure requires significant reform in national \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  development policies, not the least in reviewing the country's strategy to attract more foreign direct investment (FDI), and increasing export earnings.\par \par \uc2 There are some rumors surrounding how Prabowo will set his ministerial structure and composition in charge of these matters. For instance, there is talk that the Foreign Ministry could be combined with International Trade, modeled on the Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade (DFAT) in Australia, or that the Trade Ministry and Industry Ministry could merge to avoid any complicated trade-offs and miscoordination between the two ministries' functions in the future.\par \par \uc2 However, months before the inauguration, it is critical to address what should be considered for Prabowo's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Besides the momentum from the transition to new leadership, Indonesia is also benefiting from two years in a row of regional and multilateral chairmanship, first from the \uc2 Group of 20\uc2  and then ASEAN.\par \par \uc2 These years of global activism have somewhat elevated Indonesia's reputation as a country with confidence and strong modality to drive its international \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  agenda.\par \par \uc2 Just last year, the ASEAN Outlook on Indo-Pacific (AOIP), for instance, was brought to the table, with the priority of bringing concrete \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  partnerships into this regional commitment, adding more value to ASEAN's traditionally heavily political context. Indonesia was then seen on a positive trajectory as an Indo-Pacific power.\par \par \uc2 Thus, with many more eyes on Indonesia and its greater \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  visibility, here are some suggestions as to what Prabowo should have in the pipeline.\par \par \uc2 First, Indonesia will always require international trade diversification, both in partners and products, to reduce the risk of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  vulnerability and supply chain disruption due to global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Today, Indonesia is integrated into about 45 free trade agreements (FTAs), either already signed or under negotiation. However, ratifying an agreement is just an instrument without its optimal implementation.\par \par \uc2 Prabowo's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be directed toward the greater execution of such trade agreements. Negotiating to ratify trade agreements may be complex already, but implementing them requires more powerful platforms.\par \par \uc2 The ongoing process of establishing the \uc2 Regional Comprehensive \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Partnership\uc2  (\uc2 RCEP\uc2 ) Support Unit, to ensure the effectiveness of the \uc2 RCEP\uc2  agreement is a good example. Another benchmark is also the Indonesia-Australia Comprehensive \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Partnership Agreement (IA-CEPA) Katalis, which was established to maximize the benefits of increasing market access, and promoting trade and investment between Indonesia and Australia.\par \par \uc2 If the DFAT structure is adopted, Prabowo will need a high-caliber minister who is able to better strategize international trade as one of the significant engines of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Technocratic ministers are highly suggested to take care of this, with strong portfolios in international relations.\par \par \uc2 Appointing trade envoys might also be considered, despite this role now very much being conducted by Indonesia's ambassadors worldwide.\par \par \uc2 In the United Kingdom, the prime minister appoints trade envoys to engage promising markets for more substantial trade and investment relationships, championing the country's trade potential.\par \par \uc2 Second, to support such a vision, Indonesia needs an overarching foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  strategy that incorporates a unique approach for each region across the globe. It remains debatable whether Prabowo will release a grand foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  strategy, although experts have said this is necessary for the country.\par \par \uc2 As global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fragmentation deepens, the variability and vulnerability in supply chains is also becoming more complex among regions. It is critical for Indonesia to review its strategy in engaging almost all parts of the globe. The pandemic has led to a push for supply chain resilience and diversification, whereby Indonesia should also look to other regions, both for demand and supply.\par \par \uc2 This will entail a comprehensive outlook on priority regions for Indonesia's trade, including the identification of specific countries as the gateways, intermediaries and end targets.\par \par \uc2 Third, the crucial step above requires a strong evidence-based and well-researched foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 economic policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  formulation. Prabowo may consider the establishment of a prominent research institution that is designed to assist the government with meticulous analysis of the potential, risks and strategy in engaging the global partners economically.\par \par \uc2 The Korea Institute for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  (KIEP) could be considered an ideal example. This kind of institution will not only help the function of the Foreign Ministry, but also other related \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ministries. The mis-coordination of \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  implementation in Indonesia is evident.\par \par \uc2 On another note, "Indonesia Incorporated" has to be realized effectively on the ground. Effective coordination with the private sector is critical to assure that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  presence globally is perceived as a united force, a consolidated effort to defend what Prabowo states as "national core interests".\par \par \uc2 After all, Indonesia's expanded \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  visibility on the international level must benefit all stakeholders, particularly those at home.\par \par \uc2 ___________________\par \par \uc2 A foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 