\par\par \b \uc2 The  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2  in 2024: Growth on weakening fundamentals\b0\par\par\uc2 1,079 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 May 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Winarno Zain , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Indonesia'sgross domestic product (GDP) growth of 5.1 percent in the first quarter of 2024 showsthat the country has been successful in navigating the macroeconomic fallout from global shocks. Growth has remained resilientand strong. Indonesia has maintainedyear-on-year (yoy) growth above 5percent for nine consecutive quarters.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, the end of the commodity cycle boom, high global interest ratesand the prospect of slowing global trade as a result ofgeopolitical tensions are causing strong headwinds going forward and limiting the space for high-growth macroeconomic \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Several macroeconomic indicators in the first quarter have indicated that even to reach growth of 5 percent this year would be challenging.\par \par \uc2 Government \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  collection remained weak,contractingby 8.8 percent yoy in the first quarterto Rp 394 trillion (US$25.4 billion), mainly due to a 16 percent drop in value-added and luxury sales \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  receipts. The primary balance surplus was Rp 122 trillion but the ultimate \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  balance surplus was only Rp 8 trillion.\par \par \uc2 This means the government has spent Rp 114 trillion for paying interest on its debts, 14 percent higher than in the first quarter of 2023, though the outstanding government bonds (SBN) only increased 3.7 percent. This shows that higher borrowing costs have started to bite into the government's finances.\par \par \uc2 Nontax revenues will likely be lower in 2024, as commodity prices softened and dividend payments from state-owned enterprises (SOEs) are lower. Net profits of SOEblue chips in financial and telecommunication services were substantially lower in the first quarter of this year.\par \par \uc2 For instance, the net profits of \uc2 Bank Rakyat Indonesia\uc2  (BRI) and \uc2 Bank Mandiri\uc2  only increased 2.7 percent and 1.4 percent, respectively, in this year's first quarterafter a profit gain of 17.5 percent and 33.7 percent in 2023. \uc2 PT Telkom\uc2 's net profit also fell 7.1 percent.\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian manufacturing sector,the largest sector in the GDP, is not in a good shape either. Its growth continued to weaken. In the first quarter it grew only 4.1 percent, down from 4.9 percent in 2022 and 4.5 percent in 2023. Some manufacturing industries have faced declining demand and sales.\par \par \uc2 Car and motorcycle sales have declined and cement factories are working at 50 percent capacity. Textile and footwear factories have laid off hundreds of thousands of workers, as export demand falters and higher minimum wages have been legally increased.\par \par \uc2 These are all signs of weakening consumption, which was also supported by declining imports of consumption goods since the third quarter of 2023and the sharp drop in domestic VAT by 24 percent in the first quarter of this year.\par \par \uc2 According to data from the \uc2 Investment Coordinating Board (BKPM)\uc2  foreign investments in the manufacturing sector continued to decline from $4.9 billion in the second quarter of 2023 to $2.5 billion in the year's third quarter and to $2.1 billion in the first quarter of 2024.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile foreign investment in the trade sector in the first quarter of 2024 grew strongly, soaring to $1.6 billion, surpassing the $1.3 billion mark achieved in the whole of 2023.\par \par \uc2 This data underlines the strong growth of the service sector in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  (whichincludes wholesale and retail trade, transport, information and communication, financial, education and health), which grew 7.5 percent in this year's first quarterafter growing 5.9 percent in 2023, all above the national average.\par \par \uc2 The deceleration of manufacturing growth followed by the acceleration of service sector growth could have profound effects on the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in terms of job creation, productivity and income.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian exports also continued to decline. After contracting 11 percent in 2023, exports fell by $4.4 billion yoy, or 5.1 percent, in the first four months of 2024, mostly caused by a $3 billion drop inexports to China.\par \par \uc2 China is the biggest market for Indonesian exports, contributing 22 percent in the first quarter of 2024. But growth in China will be slower this year, as it is engaged in \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  war with the United States. And as \uc2 Donald Trump\uc2  and \uc2 Joe Biden\uc2  harbor protectionist and populist instincts, the \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  war against China will escalate whoever wins the White House in November.\par \par \uc2 Domestically, China has to deal with the bust in its property sector, declining productivity, overproduction in its factories, an aging population and weak consumer demand.\par \par \uc2 According to the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2 , China's growth will not return to 5 percent, and it has projected that China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will slow down to 4.6 percent in 2024and then to 4.2 percent in 2025.\par \par \uc2 China can no longer be expected to be the main driver of Indonesia's export growth. The Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is also facing external pressures coming from the tighter monetary situation.\par \par \uc2 Underpinned by high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  for a much longer period than expected in the US and the strength of the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the dollar is looking increasingly formidable.\par \par \uc2 The greenback has risen by 4 percent measured against a trade-weighted basket of currencies. These have adversely affected the rupiah and capital flows in Indonesia. The rupiah has depreciated 3.8 percent since Jan. 2this year.\par \par \uc2 Net portfolio investment recorded a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of $1.8 billion in the first quarter (yoy), after recording a surplus of $2.3 billion in 2023.\par \par \uc2 Indonesian private investors, facing global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , increased their investments overseas by acquiring various investment instruments, thereby causing a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of $5.5 billion in the "other investment" balance.\par \par \uc2 Ultimately, the balance of payments recorded a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of $4.5 billion, but foreign exchangereserves at \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  fell by $6 billion in March, indicating that BI might have used $1.5 billion for market intervention to help support the rupiah rate.\par \par \uc2 In its attempt to stabilize the rupiah, BIhiked its \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate by 250 basis points in April to 6.25 percent, bringing the spread with the Fed rate back to 750 basis points, the same level as in March 2023.\par \par \uc2 However, this measure was not enough, as the rupiah continued to weaken against the US dollar. It still needed support from BI intervention.\par \par \uc2 The incoming government, however, seemed ignorant of the weakening \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  indicators as president elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  continued to talk about expansive \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to finance populist programs he promised in his election campaign.\par \par \uc2 ____________________\par \par \uc2 An economis