\par\par \b \uc2 Indonesia may become LNG importer, association says\b0\par\par\uc2 Yohana Belinda, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 475 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 June 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 It is projected that Indonesia will become highly reliant on imported liquified natural gas (LNG) in the future, as demand in the country has not been met with a sufficient increase in domestic supply.\par \par \uc2 Salis L Aprilian, senior advisor to the Indonesian Gas Society (IGS) said on Thursday that the increased role of natural gas--as a transitionary energy source on the road toward renewables--would fuel demand in the country, as it is deemed to have much lower emissions than other fossil fuels.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, most of the country's local LNG production is for the export market, as quoted from Kumparan. Indonesia has also been struggling to maintain output amid a natural decline in domestic gas fields.\par \par \uc2 "Therefore, Indonesia could be a net importer of LNG in the future," Salis said, as quoted from Antara, citing a study conducted by IGS and research firm \uc2 Rystad Energy\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Indonesia faces the risk of becoming a net natural gas importer despite its rich gas \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  and position as a net LNG exporter and one of the top exporters in the world.\par \par \uc2 The country exported 16.22 million tonnes of LNG in 2023, equivalent to 4.78 percent of the world's total LNG exports, S&P Global data showed.\par \par \uc2 The IGS and Rystad study also revealed that infrastructure limitations have kept firms from monetizing potential gas fields located far from a source of demand.\par \par \uc2 It also mentioned \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in regulations and lengthy bureaucracy as factors that worsen the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  viability of a natural gas project.\par \par \uc2 The government could consider incentives for businesses in the natural gas industry in the form of \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  cuts and low interest rate financing as well as expediating permit issuance. It also recommends that the government evaluate affordable industrial gas price policies.\par \par \uc2 Southeast Asia's largest \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is projected to face a shortage of around 10 LNG cargoes in 2024, according to S&P Global analysts on Jan. 26. The shortage is expected to continue to between 2025 and 2027.\par \par \uc2 S&P Global analysts also expect the gap between imports and exports to close as the country faces increased domestic demand, declining local gas supplies and existing export commitments.\par \par \uc2 State-owned electricity company PLN said in April that it was looking to import its first-ever LNG shipment to make up for a potential gas supply shortfall in the country, which it anticipates will occur in second half of this year.\par \par \uc2 PLN has not previously imported LNG despite being permitted to do so by the government since 2017, as domestic supply has been sufficient to meet PLN's demand for electricity generation.\par \par \uc2 In May last year, the government considered prohibiting LNG exports to help supply domestic industries, claiming that it would only affect export contract renewals instead of ongoing commitments.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240614ek6f0002w\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
