\par\par \uc2 FEATURES\par \b \uc2 INDONESIA CHARTS SOLID  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMIC \highlight\uc2  PERFORMANCE\b0\par\par\uc2 1,080 \uc2 words\par \uc2 15 June 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Raka Adji Putra\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - After being hit by the COVID-19 pandemic, the world found a bright spot, with \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth projected at 2.6 percent in 2024 despite looming global geopolitical tensions and global \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  remaining high for long.\par \par \uc2 This growth is primarily due to the continued solid expansion of the US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In 2025\u8211\'20\'132026, the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to expand by an average of 2.7 percent, in line with strengthening trade growth and a broad but measured easing of monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to support \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity.\par \par \uc2 However, the growth rate is far below the average of 3.1 percent in the decade before COVID-19. Both developed and developing countries will grow more slowly as compared to the decade before the COVID-19 pandemic, according to the latest Global \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Prospects report from the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Global growth in 2024\u8211\'20\'132025 will also be below the average growth in 2010 in almost 60 percent of countries, which represent more than 80 percent of the global population. Amid increasing conflict escalations, the prospects in many vulnerable countries are still weak.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, developing countries in 2024\u8211\'20\'132025 are projected to grow at an average of four percent, slightly slower than in 2023.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, global inflation is projected to slow down to 3.5 percent in 2024 and 2.9 percent in 2025, though the rate of decline in inflation was slower than earlier estimated.\par \par \uc2 China will grow slower in 2024 and even at a more sluggish pace in 2025\u8211\'20\'132026, with cyclical challenges weighing on growth in the near future as the structural slowdown continues.\par \par \uc2 Excluding China, growth in emerging markets and developing economies is expected to increase to 3.5 percent in 2024 and then strengthen to an average of 3.9 percent in 2025\u8211\'20\'132026, in line with declining inflation, improving financial conditions, and increasing external demand.\par \par \uc2 Major challenges are still in the way of vulnerable nations, including low-income countries and those facing high levels of conflict and violence, where growth prospects are deteriorating.\par \par \uc2 According to the chief economist of \uc2 the World Bank Group\uc2  and Senior Vice President for Development Economics, Indermit Gill, Indonesia and India are two countries that have robust \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia is projected to benefit from the growth of its middle class and generally prudent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies, with a projected average \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 5.1 percent over the next two years.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, India"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has improved on the back of strong domestic demand, a surge in investment, and strong service activity.\par \par \uc2 India is projected to grow at an average of 6.7 percent per \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  year from 2024 to 2026, which could make South Asia the fastest-growing region in the world.\par \par \uc2 This performance shows high growth, yet it can be maintained even in difficult situations. Countries can increase their long-term growth by enacting policies that build human capital, boost productivity, increase the efficiency of \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and encourage more women to enter the workforce.\par \par \uc2 Solid growth\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  revised the projection of Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2024 to five percent from the previous forecast of 4.9 percent by considering the upward revision of the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth prediction, especially for the US and China, which are Indonesia"s main trading partners.\par \par \uc2 In particular, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  estimated that Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth will be solid, as it is supported by the growth of the middle class and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  policies that tend to be extra cautious or prudent.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  also revised upward the projection of Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2025 to 5.1 percent, an increase of 0.2 percentage points from the previous projection. Likewise, Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2026 is also projected to be at 5.1 percent.\par \par \uc2 According to the chair of the board of commissioners of the \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK)\uc2 , Mahendra Siregar, Indonesia"s financial services sector is also maintained in a stable condition.\par \par \uc2 The continued stability of the financial services sector is supported by strong capital levels and adequate liquidity amid global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  due to high geopolitical tensions, the potential for widespread trade wars, and global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance that is still below expectations.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the first quarter of 2024 stood at 5.11 percent (year-on-year/yoy).\par \par \uc2 In terms of projection, the gross domestic product (GDP) growth in most countries in the Asia-Pacific region (except China), including Indonesia, Malaysia, and the Philippines, will be supported by strong growth of the private sector, low inflation, a decline in loan costs, and strong labor market conditions.\par \par \uc2 Head economist of \uc2 Bank Permata\uc2 , Josua Pardede, stated that Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in 2024 will still be around 5 to 5.1 percent, in line with the projections of the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  and the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2  (\uc2 IMF\uc2 ).\par \par \uc2 However, there is still a downside risk to \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, especially the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consumption component, where the rate is still below national growth in line with the potential decline in people"s real income amid the increase in the cost of living, especially for middle-class people.\par \par \uc2 To this end, the condition where consumers tend to hold back on \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  has the potential to affect the sales performance of businesses.\par \par \uc2 The government needs to focus on efforts to prevent the community"s living costs from increasing significantly and be careful in making adjustments to the prices of goods or services that it regulates, such as fuel, liquefied petroleum gas (LPG), and electricity.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the plans to adjust plastic excise rates and excise on packaged sweetened beverages, which are also expected to increase people"s living costs, also call for exercising caution.\par \par \uc2 Hence, to this end, the government must manage the momentum so that the community"s purchasing power does not decline in line with the plans related to the prices of goods or services that it regulates, as well as encourage food price stability that can also affect the community"s purchasing power.\par \par \uc2 In addition, the government should encourage quality \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth that can absorb a large number of workers, which has the potential to increase people"s real income and reduce unemployment and poverty rates.\par \par \uc2 With the increase in the community"s real income, it is hoped that consumers" optimism and the community"s purchasing power will increase and eventually support solid \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 (T.KR-RAP/A/R013/R013) 15-06-2024 18:56:20\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240615ek6f000un\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Muhammadiyah\u8217\'20\'19s Hundred Trillion Rupiah Businesses\b0\par\par\uc2 1,389 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 June 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 THE 30th anniversary logo is displayed at the offices of Bangun Drajat Warga Sharia People\u8217\'20\'19s Financing Bank (BPRS BDW). This bank is owned by the Muhammadiyah Regional Executive Board in Yogyakarta. The building facade also features the Muhammadiyah logo, a shining sun with 12 rays surrounding the shahadah (bearing the witness to faith) inscription.\par \par \uc2 Every year on February 2, BPRS BDW with offices located at Jalan Gedongkuning Selatan in Banguntapan and Jalan Jenderal Sudirman in Bantul\u8212\'20\'14both in Yogyakarta\u8212\'20\'14celebrates its anniversary. This year, the bank is three decades old. BPRS BDW is a bank that collects funds from members of Muhammadiyah as well as the general \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and then channels them back to the people.\par \par \uc2 When Tempo visited the BPRS BDW Gedongkuning Selatan office on Wednesday, June 12, there was only one teller serving customers, and only three customers were seen making transactions. One of them is Muhammad Hafidz, a student of Janabadra University in Yogyakarta, who has been a customer of BPRS BDW Gedongkuning Selatan branch since 2012. He puts his money in the bank to save for his college needs.\par \par \uc2 Hafidz used to put his money in conventional banks. But when he used the banks\u8217\'20\'19 digital transaction feature, he encountered problems. \u8220\'20\'1CThe system often had errors and my money kept getting deducted for fees, so I decided to save money manually,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. Consequently, BPRS BDW became his choice.\par \par \uc2 BPRS BDW was established in 1994 at the suggestion of the Council for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of the Yogyakarta Muhammadiyah Executive Board, which believed that there were still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  about the halal (permitted) status of banking institutions with their interest system. The bank has 42 founders, all of whom were Muhammadiyah activists. One of them, Herry Zudianto, said the bank was basically founded on zeal rather than a large amount of capital. \u8220\'20\'1CThe spirit to fight loan sharks,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 Muhammadiyah-owned Bangun Drajat Warga Sharia People\u8217\'20\'19s Financing Bank in Bantul Regency, Yogyakarta, June 12. TEMPO/Shinta Maharani\par \par \uc2 Citing Mediamu.com, a media outlet affiliated with the Yogyakarta Muhammadiyah Executive Board, the founders of BPRS BDW initially observed Kotagede Market, Sentul Market, and Bantengan 3 Market, which were rampant with loan shark practices that were detrimental to the community due to high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . This situation prompted Muhammadiyah to set up a bank. In addition, the schools established by Muhammadiyah were growing rapidly and were in need of funding.\par \par \uc2 The founders then gathered numerous Baitul Maal wat Tamwil or BMTs (people\u8217\'20\'19s small \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  business institutions) owned by Muhammadiyah to discuss the establishment of the bank. BPRS BDW uses corporate social responsibility (CSR) funds for the community. It develops capital within Muhammadiyah, Lazizmu, and other financial institutions.\par \par \uc2 According to the bank\u8217\'20\'19s financial report, as of March, BPRS BDW has total assets of Rp216 billion (around US$13.6 million), up from Rp171 billion (US$11.3 million) a year earlier. In the first quarter, BPRS BDW posted a net profit of Rp565.7 million (US$35,684) and a net non-performing loan (NPL) ratio of 5.5 percent.\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 BANGUN Drajat Warga Sharia People\u8217\'20\'19s Financing Bank (BPRS BDW) is just one of the many business lines associated with Muhammadiyah. In general, the Muhammadiyah social enterprises (AUM) are involved in education, social, health, disaster affairs, community empowerment and community fund management, to name a few. These programs extend from the Muhammadiyah Central Executive Board level to the village level.\par \par \uc2 Data from the Muhammadiyah Central Executive Board (PP Muhammadiyah) Secretariat as per its 111th anniversary last year, the organization\u8217\'20\'19s programs are mainly in the education sector. This can be seen from the number of affiliated universities, which includes 172 universities, colleges and other institutions. There are also 5,345 Islamic schools or madrasas and 440 Islamic boarding schools or pesantren. In several publications on the websites of Muhammadiyah-affiliated institutions, the asset value of the Islamic organization founded by Ahmad Dahlan could reach up to Rp400 trillion (US$24.52 billion).\par \par \uc2 Abdul Mu\u8217\'20\'19ti, Secretary-General of Muhammadiyah Central Executive Board, said that education is the first and most important program of Muhammadiyah. \u8220\'20\'1CThe face of Muhammadiyah is the face of education,\u8221\'20\'1D he said during Muhammadiyah Central Executive Board\u8217\'20\'19s National Coordination Meeting for the Assembly of Primary-Secondary Education and Non-Formal Education on Sunday, June 2, as posted to the Muhammadiyah website.\par \par \uc2 Aside from Muhammadiyah Social Enterprise, Muhammadiyah also began working to create an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  ecosystem from upstream to downstream, calling it the Muhammadiyah Closed Loop \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . To create this ecosystem, the organization established the Muhammadiyah Jaringan Saudagar (merchants\u8217\'20\'19 network), the Baitut Tamwil (business house), and the Muhammadiyah-Owned Business Entity. This ecosystem was created to maximize the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  potential of the organization.\par \par \uc2 Syafrudin Anhar, former General Chair of PP Muhammadiyah\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Entrepreneurship Council, said that by 2022, the contribution of the affiliates to the circulation of money in Jakarta could reach Rp2 trillion (US$127.13 million). At the national level, the numbers will be larger The Muhammadiyah Closed Loop \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is considered as maximizing this potential.\par \par \uc2 Unlike the Muhammadiyah Social Enterprise, the establishment of a Muhammadiyah-Owned Business Entity can be proposed by anyone, but its establishment must be approved and carried out by the leadership of the organization. Later, 51 percent of the shares of the limited liability company must be owned by and in the name of Persyarikatan Muhammadiyah (Muhammadiyah organization). Thus, dividends could be distributed to shareholders other than the organization. Meanwhile, since its establishment, Muhammadiyah Social Enterprises' purposes and funds have been for social and religious purposes.\par \par \uc2 One of the officials of a Muhammadiyah-affiliated institution said that this type of business structure is what greases the wheels of the organization. In the future, it is possible that business entities under Muhammadiyah could be involved in other sectors, such as mining. According to this official, Muhammadiyah is still deliberating its stance on Government \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  No. 25/2024 on the Mineral and Coal Mining Business. One of the points in the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is the opportunity for religious mass organizations to manage special mining permits or IUP. Since the beginning of May, Muhammadiyah has discussed this issue in three board meetings.\par \par \uc2 Within the organization, the PP Muhammadiyah\u8217\'20\'19s Legal and Human Rights Council and \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Advocacy Institute have given their legal opinions on the government\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of granting business permits to religious mass organizations. The two councils presented the problems in the business permit \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  for mass organizations.\par \par \uc2 Tempo contacted a number of Muhammadiyah Central Executive Board leaders for comment. Anwar Abbas, Chair of the Micro, Small, and Medium Enterprises, Community Empowerment, and Environment, stated he was unaware of the progress of these discussions as he was on a haj pilgrimage. Meanwhile, Muhadjir Effendy, Chair of the Halal \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Business, and Industry, suggested Tempo to talk to the General Chair of Muhammadiyah Central Executive Board, Haedar Nashir. \u8220\'20\'1CIt would be better for you to ask this directly to Pak Haedar,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. However, Haedar did not respond to Tempo\u8217\'20\'19s inquiries.\par \par \uc2 On Monday, June 3, Muhammadiyah Secretary-General Abdul Mu\u8217\'20\'19ti said that the organization had not received an offer from the government to manage mines. Muhammadiyah, he said, will not rush into it and will first measure its own capabilities so that if it decides to accept the offer, the management of the mine will not cause problems for the organization, society and the country.\par \par \uc2 Director of the Institute for Demographic and Poverty Studies, Yusuf Wibisono, said the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  potential of Indonesian Muslims is enormous, stemming from halal products, education, sharia (based on Islamic law) tourism, and sharia banking. Other potential comes from all forms of philanthropic funds, such as zakat (obligatory alms), infaq (voluntary charity), sedekah (voluntary alms), and waqf (endowment).\par \par \uc2 Success in managing philanthropic funds, Yusuf said, creates an avenue for Islamic mass organizations to enter the sharia business by establishing schools, universities, opening hospitals, haj-umrah (minor pilgrimage) travel agencies, and sharia-based community financing banks. According to Yusuf, one of the main characteristics of a good Islamic organization is financial independence, not needing monetary support from other parties. \u8220\'20\'1CIn this way, the organization becomes an independent force and is not easily co-opted by other forces.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/06/16/863380/863380_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/06/16/863381/863381_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240617ek6g00007\par }\page {\par\fs20\b  \highlight22\uc2 Uncertainty \highlight\uc2  in  \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal Policy \highlight\uc2 , Push the Rupiah Down\b0\par\par\uc2 687 \uc2 words\par \uc2 16 June 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 TWO contrasting sentiments emerged almost simultaneously in the global financial markets last Wednesday. The positive sentiment came first: the annual inflation rate in the United States had eased. By the end of May, it stood at 3.4 percent, down from 3.6 percent at the end of April.\par \par \uc2 This figure represents core inflation, which excludes volatile food and energy prices. This is one of the most watched data points in the market, as the \uc2 US Federal Reserve\uc2  uses it as the main reference for making interest rate decisions.\par \par \uc2 Easing core inflation is definitely a good sign. The Fed might soon slash its reference rate. Lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the US could accelerate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Positive ripple effects would also spread globally. No wonder this data release sparked optimism in global financial markets. Alas, this positive drive was short-lived.\par \par \uc2 Only a few hours later, negative sentiment emerged from the announcement of the Federal Open Market Committee\u8217\'20\'19s (FOMC) meeting results, coincidentally held on the same day. There were three important takeaways from the meeting that directly changed investors\u8217\'20\'19 moods.\par \par \uc2 First, the Fed left \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  unchanged, maintaining the current range of 5.25 percent to 5.5 percent for a longer period. Second, the so-called dot plot indicated that any rate cut would occur only once this year. The dot plot is a visual graph that shows how each member of the FOMC projects future \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Lastly, despite the easing of core inflation in May, the Fed raised its core inflation forecast for this year from 2.6 percent to 2.8 percent.\par \par \uc2 The markets quickly concluded that the Fed is not yet done with its endeavor to fight stubborn inflation. Market hopes for an imminent Fed rate cut were dashed. Instead, investors now have to brace for the likelihood that high rates will persist for a longer period. The long-awaited cut would likely not come until at least next September, as the dot plot indicates.\par \par \uc2 The Fed\u8217\'20\'19s decision also put pressure on the rupiah. Initially strengthening to around Rp16,150 per US dollar in New York trading following the May inflation data release, the rupiah fell again in Jakarta the next day. On Thursday, June 13, the rupiah weakened to nearly Rp16,300 per US dollar, marking its lowest point in four years.\par \par \uc2 The rupiah\u8217\'20\'19s current weakening is slowly creeping, yet seems unstoppable. If prolonged, the decline could have serious consequences for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . For consumers, the weakening currency would lead to inflation in imported goods, eroding purchasing power. Industries that sell their products domestically but rely on imported raw materials would face rising production costs and dwindling profits.\par \par \uc2 For the government, the rupiah\u8217\'20\'19s depreciation presents a serious problem. The net effect of a weaker rupiah will be a bigger \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The current State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  uses an exchange rate of Rp15,000 per dollar as its basic assumption, which is increasingly disconnected from current realities. If the average exchange rate hovers around Rp16,300 per dollar, the government could face an additional \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  of approximately Rp81 trillion this year. Amid volatile financial markets and a high-interest-rate environment, this added burden could be highly problematic.\par \par \uc2 Another significant factor is the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  ahead of the government transition, making investors increasingly sensitive when assessing Indonesian financial assets. In such a critical situation, there has been no \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  response from the government or financial authorities to at least ease the pressure. Additionally, there has been no positive signal from President-elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  that he acknowledges the rising \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  risks and will make serious efforts to address them.\par \par \uc2 As a result, market confidence in the rupiah truly evaporated by the end of the week. The exchange rate plummeted to near Rp16,500 per US dollar. If Prabowo wants to avoid starting his administration with a crisis triggered by the rupiah\u8217\'20\'19s collapse, he must immediately change course and commit to maintaining \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline. Without such decisiveness, the financial markets will further penalize Indonesia.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/06/16/863399/863399_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240617ek6g0000c\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
