\par\par \b \uc2 Double continuity: Basis for Singapore and RI  \highlight22\uc2 economic \highlight\uc2  ties\b0\par\par\uc2 939 \uc2 words\par \uc2 19 June 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Lawrence Loh , Singapore\par \par \uc2 With both Indonesia and Singapore seeing significant political changes in 2024, the future of their \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  partnership hangs in the balance. Former general \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  and Prime Minister of Singapore Lawrence Wong can leverage the stability they both promised to bring to their terms regarding political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  vision, policies, and projects. This will provide certainty to investors and sustain the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth enjoyed by both parties.\par \par \uc2 In March, Indonesia announced the results of the 2024 general election, naming Prabowo and Gibran Rakabuming Raka as president and vice president-elect for the 2024-2029 term. Leadership changes often create \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , disincentivizing investors.\par \par \uc2 However, Prabowo has pledged a smooth transition from the current \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2  administration by continuing his policies and programs, including the Nusantara new capital city project. This commitment is crucial for maintaining investor confidence and ensuring \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability.\par \par \uc2 Across the straits, Singapore's \uc2 Lee Hsien Loong\uc2  handed the baton to Wong on May 15. While the choice of his successor was expected, the timing coincided with Indonesia's election result.\par \par \uc2 Wong stated there would be no major changes in the upcoming cabinet until the next general election due in 2025. This double permanence promises new mutual growth for Indonesia and Singapore.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  relationship between Indonesia and Singapore has always been complementary, with trade between the two countries amounting to US$50.6 billion in 2023.\par \par \uc2 Singapore has been Indonesia's top source of foreign direct investment since 2014. The promised stability from both leaders is crucial for ensuring investor confidence and fostering further collaborations.\par \par \uc2 A seamless transition in leadership can ensure a smooth flow of capital, especially as the new administrations galvanize investments into Nusantara and other projects. Indonesia has emerged as one of the most attractive investment destinations, experiencing approximately 5 percent gross domestic product (GDP) growth in the post-pandemic era.\par \par \uc2 This success is supported by robust production capabilities and a large consumer base, positioning Indonesia as not just a market, but also a thriving hub for entrepreneurship.\par \par \uc2 Investor confidence is further bolstered by specific initiatives such as the 20 Singaporean private investors who have already pledged their intent toward the Nusantara (new capital) project. Meanwhile some organizations have also signed MoUs for investments in East Java's Special \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Zone. In the renewable energy sector, collaborative projects such as the planned construction of the largest battery manufacturing and solar power plants in Indonesia illustrate significant investment and cooperation between both countries. These examples underscore the robust and multifaceted nature of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  relations, pointing toward a promising future of enhanced collaboration and mutual growth.\par \par \uc2 To sustain this \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  momentum, investment in talent development and education is crucial. Indonesia, home to more than 2,400 start-ups, needs access to networks and financing, which Singapore can provide.\par \par \uc2 Singapore's leadership in technology and innovation also complements Indonesia's growing tech sector. Joint ventures in fintech, e-commerce, and digital services can spur innovation and create new market opportunities. Such industries also require education and workforce development to mature.\par \par \uc2 It is thus a win-win for both countries. Singapore's low fertility rate suggests a future workforce shortage, necessitating complementary foreign talent. Indonesia can provide this talent pipeline. Singapore's advanced education system, emphasizing skills development, can help train and enhance the productivity and capability of Indonesian workers. This can be done through joint educational programs, vocational training, and talent exchanges.\par \par \uc2 University education is another prime example of long-term talent exchange. Both countries can benefit from the mobility of students and ideas. At the Indonesia-Singapore Business Forum, current Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Trade and Industry \uc2 Gan Kim Yong\uc2  announced a program for fresh graduates to pursue tech-related jobs in each other's countries, further supporting the growing entrepreneurship in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 BLOCK71, an initiative by NUS Enterprise, has collaborative and strategic partnerships with established corporations and government agencies. It is a tech ecosystem builder and global connector that catalyzes and aggregates the start-up community, spearheads new initiatives, and provides mentorship and growth opportunities in local and global markets.\par \par \uc2 Across Indonesia, including Jakarta, Bandung, and Yogyakarta, overseas tech companies exploring business opportunities in Indonesia can leverage these facilities to better understand the Indonesian market, set up shop, and expand business networks. Conversely, Indonesia-based entrepreneurs, companies, and investors can learn more about NUS research and technologies, gaining access to Singapore, Southeast Asian, and other international markets.\par \par \uc2 Despite opportunities, both administrations must ensure that \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  continuity does not perpetuate red tape. Indonesia's rank of 73rd in the ease of doing business index reflects the need for regulatory improvements.\par \par \uc2 Simplifying Indonesia's regulatory framework could enhance its ease of doing business ranking, encouraging more foreign investment.\par \par \uc2 Businesses and investors will also appreciate a conducive political climate to operate optimally. Looking forward, we can expect to see new partnerships emerging in key sectors that drive growth, such as green energy. Singapore has the potential to contribute to Indonesia's sustainable energy by providing connectivity to the global market and access to finance.\par \par \uc2 Both countries are poised for a period of collaboration under their new administrations. This is crucial for maintaining stability and fostering \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, particularly in terms of investor confidence, \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  consistency, and talent exchange.\par \par \uc2 By addressing shared challenges through continued collaboration and strategic initiatives, the upcoming administrations have the potential to strengthen bilateral ties and drive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  cooperation for the good of Southeast Asia and the world.\par \par \uc2 _______________________\par \par \uc2 Director of the Centre for Governance and Sustainability (\uc2 CGS\uc2 ) at Business School, \uc2 National University of Singapore\uc2 . The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240618ek6j0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
