\par\par \uc2 NATIONAL NEWS\par \b \uc2 HIGHER  \highlight22\uc2 PUBLIC \highlight\uc2  SATISFACTION IS APPRECIATION FOR WIDODO GOVT: OFFICIAL\b0\par\par\uc2 326 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 June 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Kenzu Tandiah\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - Coordinator of the president"s advisors, Ari Dwipayana, said that a Kompas R&D survey showing an increase in satisfaction with the Joko Widodo administration is proof of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  appreciation for the government"s performance.\par \par \uc2 As per the Kompas R&D survey, the level of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  satisfaction with the Joko Widodo-Ma"ruf Amin administration increased from 73.59 percent in December 2023 to 75.6 percent in June 2024, Dwipayana informed in a written message received here on Friday.\par \par \uc2 "Thank you for the trust, appreciation, and support given by various elements of society to the President and all levels of government. The Kompas R&D survey result is proof of the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 "s appreciation for the government"s hard work," he said.\par \par \uc2 He added that given the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political situation, the increase in \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  satisfaction has not made the government complacent.\par \par \uc2 The positive appreciation from the masses, he added, has motivated the government to continue its efforts to complete the development priority agenda and ensure that its performance in all sectors improves.\par \par \uc2 Toward the end of his leadership term, President Widodo has continued to be committed to working optimally, remaining consistent in carrying out leadership that prioritizes the people and is close to or based on the interests of the community, in addition to national interests.\par \par \uc2 "Even though his term in office is about to end, President Widodo keeps being there for the community to ensure that priority agendas run well and have an impact on improving the quality of life throughout the country," Dwipayana said.\par \par \uc2 According to the Kompas R&D survey, \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  satisfaction with the current administration on its work on equal development distribution reached 74.5 percent \u8212\'20\'14 the highest level of appreciation for the Widodo-Amin administration in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sector.\par \par \uc2 (T.KR-KZU/B/A043/A043) 21-06-2024 19:36:36\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240621ek6l000ul\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Industries Impacted by the Rising Dollar Exchange Rate\b0\par\par\uc2 1,309 \uc2 words\par \uc2 23 June 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 HOSPITALS in Indonesia are facing a new problem. The weak rupiah exchange rate against the dollar, which continues to strengthen, is expected to drive up the prices of medicines and operational costs of medical equipment. Consequently, hospitals are confronted with a choice: increasing tariffs that may lead to patient protests or absorbing losses due to the increasingly expensive dollar.\par \par \uc2 Even so, hospital management cannot just increase their rates. According to the Private Hospitals Association Chairperson Iing Ichsan Hanafi, more than 70 percent of hospitals in Indonesia are in partnership with the Health Care and Social Security Agency (BPJS Kesehatan), which sets the initial tariffs. \u8220\'20\'1CWhereas, the prices of drugs have become higher and out of proportion to the hospitals\u8217\'20\'19 income,\u8221\'20\'1D he said on Thursday, June 20.\par \par \uc2 According to Iing, hospital managements are forced to implement temporary measures. To reduce costs, they use domestic products. Adjustments are also made to the choices of medicines and medical equipment. \u8220\'20\'1CWe collaborate with doctors to control cost without sacrificing service quality,\u8221\'20\'1D he said, dismissing concerns that hospitals would reduce the quality of their services.\par \par \uc2 The soaring dollar exchange has been unstoppable. In early January, the rupiah exchange rate was 15,400 per United States dollar. On Friday, June 21, the rupiah exchange rate on the Jakarta Interbank Spot Dollar Rate or Jisdor broke 16,458 per US dollar. Most banks have even started selling the American dollar at Rp16,500-16,700 per dollar. This further affects businesses that rely on imported products, including the health industry and hospitals.\par \par \uc2 This is also why Febie Yuriza Poetri, the Marketing and Finance Director of Graha Teknomedika, a medical equipment manufacturer, expressed concern over the dollar\u8217\'20\'19s price increase exceeding their calculations. Medical equipment distributors are worried because 70 percent of the products on the market are imported, while local products still depend on imported raw materials and components. Febie said medical equipment manufacturers have already hedged about 35 percent of their exposure to the US dollar. \u8220\'20\'1CBut the current exchange rate is above that level, eroding our profit margins,\u8221\'20\'1D she said on Thursday, June 20.\par \par \uc2 A store selling medicines and medical equipment at Pramuka Market, Jakarta, October 2023. TEMPO/Tony Hartawan\par \par \uc2 Just like the situation hospitals face, raising the price of medical equipment is not an easy choice for Febie\u8217\'20\'19s company. She explained that the majority of medical equipment is absorbed by the government under long-term contracts with fixed prices. \u8220\'20\'1CThe government already has plans in place, so we cannot just increase prices arbitrarily,\u8221\'20\'1D said Febie, who also serves as Chair II of the Association of Indonesian Medical Equipment Manufacturers (Aspaki).\par \par \uc2 Local medical equipment businesses relying on imported raw materials and components are most affected by the rise in the US dollar exchange rate. This is because domestically sourced substitute components are very limited. Most raw materials and components for medical equipment are imported from China, but suppliers from there use US dollars in their transactions. Febie provided an example that local hospital bed manufacturers require raw materials such as medical-grade 316 stainless steel. \u8220\'20\'1CWe have to import them,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 Amid the difficult situation, Aspaki members are trying to find more affordable alternatives to the raw materials and components without reducing specification and quality. \u8220\'20\'1CWhat is inevitable is that we have to cut down on labor and investment,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Elfiano Rizaldi, Executive Director of the Indonesia Pharmaceutical Association, stated that the industry\u8217\'20\'19s dependence on imported drug raw materials, which exceeds 80 percent, has caused troubles for businesses. Moreover, he added, the pharmaceutical industry is tightly regulated, making it difficult to simply seek alternative raw material sources. \u8220\'20\'1CWe have to re-register to obtain new marketing approvals from the Food and Drug Monitoring Agency,\u8221\'20\'1D he explained.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, Efliano continued, pharmaceutical companies have to select which products to be sold so as not to lose money. \u8220\'20\'1CWhat products still yield good margins, and what products should be abandoned because they are no longer competitive,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. Implementing efficiency measures and increasing drug prices remain a last resort because there are still options available. \u8220\'20\'1CAt least there\u8217\'20\'19s raw material stock for the next two months that was purchased when the dollar was around Rp15,000," Elfiano noted.\par \par \uc2 There is another problem, though. Dwindling raw material stocks has forced pharmaceutical manufacturers to import amid a weakening rupiah exchange rate. \uc2 Kalbe Farma\uc2  President Commissioner Vidjongtius said that raw materials supplies typically run out in three to four months, while the level of dependency on imported drug raw materials reaches 90 percent. \u8220\'20\'1CIn the end, we have to find economical sources of raw materials through supply chain optimizations,\u8221\'20\'1D he said on Thursday, June 20.\par \par \uc2 Other efforts include signing contracts to purchase raw materials over a longer period and implementing a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  of maintaining foreign currency cash \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  equivalent to US$50-60 million on the company\u8217\'20\'19s balance sheet. To deal with eroding business margins, \uc2 Kalbe Farma\uc2  is pushing its business lines outside pharmaceuticals to reduce losses. \u8220\'20\'1CFor example, pushing the distribution and logistics business, which contributes around 30 percent,\u8221\'20\'1D said Vidjongtius.\par \par \uc2 Bio Farma Chief Executive Officer (CEO) Shadiq Akasya said that the national pharmaceutical industry cannot avoid the impact of the weakening rupiah. The state-owned holding company in the pharmaceutical sector also struggles to compete with raw material producers from China and India. According to Shadiq, the root cause of this disparity is Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s lack of basic chemical and biological products for pharmaceutical raw materials. Therefore, the price of domestically produced pharmaceutical raw materials sold by Bio Farma is twice as expensive as imported products from China or India.\par \par \uc2 In addition to affecting the pharmaceutical and health industries, the sluggish rupiah exchange rate also raises concerns among business actors in other sectors. Shinta Widjaja Kamdani, Chair of the Indonesian Employers Association (Apindo), stated that the dollar exchange rate exceeding Rp16,400 is highly unsafe for businesses. According to her, the depreciation of the rupiah also impacts logistics and transportation costs, as well as financial stability. \u8220\'20\'1CThere will be a decline in business performance, reduction in employment, and risks of non-performing loans,\u8221\'20\'1D she said.\par \par \uc2 Amidst these conditions, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  has been aggressively conducting monetary operations. BI Governor \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2  mentioned that all monetary instruments have been deployed, from increasing interventions in the foreign exchange market and spot transactions, issuing domestic non-deliverable forwards and Government Securities in the secondary market, strengthening the structure of \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the rupiah money market, to optimizing \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Securities, Foreign Exchange Securities, and Foreign Exchange Sukuk (sharia-compliant bonds) instruments.\par \par \uc2 Having carried out all these efforts, the \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  Board of Governors Meeting on June 19-20, decided to maintain the BI-Rate benchmark interest rate at 6.25 percent. The \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  has maintained the benchmark interest rate at that level for three months to prevent an \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturn. \u8220\'20\'1CThis is also considering the high \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the global financial markets amid the prospect of a stronger world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D said Perry.\par \par \uc2 Based on BI\u8217\'20\'19s records, the rupiah exchange rate against the United States dollar has depreciated 0.70 percent point-to-point so far this month. Global market \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  influence the weakening of the rupiah due to the push and pull of the interest rate hike plan of the US \b \highlight22\uc2 central bank\b0 \highlight\uc2  or the \uc2 Federal Reserve\uc2 . Another factor that makes the dollar more expensive is increased corporate demand, including for dividend repatriation.\par \par \uc2 Nevertheless, Perry believes the rupiah exchange rate will soon strengthen and return to below 16,000 per United States dollar. His optimism is based on the strengthening \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals, including the domestic inflation rate, which remains at 2.8 percent, and the current account balance, which is still in surplus.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/06/23/863864/863864_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/06/23/863865/863865_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240624ek6n0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
