\par\par \b \uc2 Unleashing the bull: Predicting Indonesian stock market's next move\b0\par\par\uc2 1,121 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 June 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Ibrahim Kholilul Rohman and Fadli Jihad Dahana, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian stock market (IHSG) is experiencing an unfavorable condition. After peaking at an all-time high of 7454.45 in mid-March, the index has declined by 9.75 percent to 6726.92 as of June 19, and has not yet shown a clear sign of a long-term reversal. This is aligned with a study from IFG Progress on the IHSG's technical analysis, which states that the market was in an overbought condition by late-2023, signaling a possible downtrend afterwards.\par \par \uc2 Consequently, foreign investors are offloading blue-chip stocks such as BMRI, BBNI, BBCA, SMGR and GOTO. Major stocks like BMRI, which declined by 20.21 percent over the past three months, have seen significant drops. Similar patterns can be observed in BBCA (down 9.85 percent) and SMGR (down 38.07 percent).\par \par \uc2 Thus, it is crucial to determine whether these changes are seasonal or indicate more structural shifts. Here, we argue that the IHSG might not rebound shortly.\par \par \uc2 There are at least two reasons supporting this possible trajectory. First, the global macroeconomic situation remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . During the June 16 United States Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meeting, the \uc2 US Federal Reserve\uc2  maintained its target rate in the 5.25-5.50 percent range for the seventh consecutive time.\par \par \uc2 The accompanying Summary of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Projections (SEP), prepared by Fed board members, revealed that year-end core inflation in the US is projected to reach 2.8 percent, up from the previous 2.6 percent, thereby further deviating from their long-term inflation target of 2 percent.\par \par \uc2 Consequently, the board implied that a 25-basis-point rate cut would occur only once this year, down from a previously planned three times. This suggests that the period of a high Fed target range, which has affected emerging markets through capital outflows to advanced markets and subsequent currency depreciations, will persist longer than anticipated.\par \par \uc2 Since the Fed first raised its target rate in March 2022, major Asian emerging market stock indices and currencies have weakened. In Hong Kong, the HSI Index has declined by 25.3 percent. While the Hong Kong dollar has only depreciated by about 2 percent, there has been a significant increase in US dollar/Hong Kong dollar volatility over the last two years.\par \par \uc2 In Malaysia, although the KLSE has recently begun to recover, it dropped by more than 13 percent from March 2022 to December 2023. Meanwhile, the ringgit has depreciated by more than 10 percent against the US dollar.\par \par \uc2 In contrast, divergent patterns are evident in Asian advanced markets. For instance, the Japanese Nikkei 225 Index has risen by 52.6 percent, while Singapore's STI Index has increased by 2.06 percent. This demonstrates that because of the high Fed rates, capital flowed from emerging markets to advanced markets.\par \par \uc2 As one of the major emerging markets in the region, Indonesia is not insulated from these dynamics. On June 17, the US dollar/rupiah reached an all-time high of nearly Rp 16,500 per US dollar. This occurred because higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  abroad made domestic assets less attractive. This can lead to a sell-off of domestic assets, reducing demand for domestic currency and thereby depreciating it against foreign currencies.\par \par \uc2 From the beginning of the year until the end of April, foreigners recorded a net sale of more than US$2 billion in the government bond (SBN) market. Foreign exchange (FX) volatility adds further \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  to the entire financial market, prompting capital outflows from IHSG stocks. On June 20, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  maintained its \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate at 6.25 percent amid the condition. However, there was a short-term betterment of the IHSG (up 1.39 percent a day to 6820.22) while the US dollar/rupiah kept increasing (up 0.31 percent a day to 16,469).\par \par \uc2 The trajectory of the IHSG is further challenged by a second factor: \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  surrounding the country's future \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  sustainability. There are rumors that the incoming Indonesian government intends to continually increase debt to achieve a 50 percent debt-to-GDP ratio in order to sustain 8 percent annual \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 Despite recent official statements dismissing these rumors, market participants remain skeptical about the new administration's commitment to maintaining \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline, especially given forthcoming programs that could potentially strain finances. Notably, \uc2 Morgan Stanley\uc2  has downgraded Indonesia's stocks to underweight, which could exacerbate foreign outflows from the IHSG.\par \par \uc2 Arguably, the dominant factor explaining the downward trend of the IHSG is this \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  issue. If the pressure were primarily from the impact of the high Fed rate, we would expect similar patterns in other emerging markets. However, many emerging market stock indices showed significant gains over the last six months.\par \par \uc2 From January 2024 to June 2024, the Malaysian KLSE index has gained 11 percent, the Hong Kong HSI index has gained 6.81 percent and the Shanghai SSE index has gained 2.49 percent. The suggested explanation is that since the Fed rate has remained unchanged for almost a year, the market has already "priced in" this information when investing in emerging markets. Therefore, the fact that the IHSG has declined by 4.81 percent over the same period sheds light on investors' particular aversion to the IHSG.\par \par \uc2 The question now is when will the international appetite for the IHSG return? If the market witnesses that the new administration can manage the country sustainably amid their ambitious goals, its confidence in Indonesia's financial market will gradually come back.\par \par \uc2 Investments in infrastructure and human capital, if done effectively, will also shift the country's long-run aggregate supply curve, boosting future outputs. These ameliorating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions will then attract investors, providing more funds to finance productive investments in the country in a virtuous cycle. Nevertheless, the realization of such optimistic scenarios remains speculative.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, the June SEP displays that US inflation will converge to the long-term goal of 2 percent by 2026, implying a lower Fed rate of 2.6-3 percent in the period thus reflecting a low-risk global macroeconomic environment in the future. This would make US assets less attractive, leading to the return of funds to emerging markets.\par \par \uc2 If this macroeconomic condition holds, and Indonesia is also on the right path to prove their worth to global investors once more, the IHSG will once again be regarded as a bull market.\par \par \uc2 ____________________\par \par \uc2 Ibrahim Kholilul Rohman is a senior research associate at IFG Progress and a Lecturer at Universitas Indonesia, and Fadli Jihad Dahana is a master's degree student in international finance at \uc2 Columbia University\uc2  and a research intern at IFG Progress. The views expressedaretheirown.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240623ek6o00008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley