\par\par \uc2 BUSSINESS\par \b \uc2 INDONESIA'S  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMY \highlight\uc2  SUPPORTED BY STRONG MACROECONOMIC POLICIES\b0\par\par\uc2 398 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 June 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 By Cindy Frishanti Octavia\par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  stated that Indonesia"s successful \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance is supported by the implementation of strong government macroeconomic policies that support sustainable growth and attract investment into the country.\par \par \uc2 "Indonesia"s successful \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance is largely thanks to the government"s strong macroeconomic \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  framework, which helps attract investment," \uc2 World Bank\uc2  Director for Indonesia and Timor-Leste Carolyn Turk stated in Jakarta, Monday.\par \par \uc2 In its latest report titled Indonesia \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Prospect June 2024 edition, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  stated that a prudent and consistent macroeconomic \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  framework has become the basis for the success of Indonesia"s \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance, which is recognized by the market.\par \par \uc2 For instance, the credit default swap rate and the \uc2 JP-Morgan\uc2  Emerging Market Bond Index (EMBI) spread for Indonesia have continued to decline since the COVID-19 pandemic and are lower than in several comparable countries.\par \par \uc2 The credit rating agency has also maintained an investment grade rating for sovereign credit, including a stable outlook, so Indonesia succeeded in overcoming external shocks, attracting investment, and supporting growth.\par \par \uc2 "It is important to maintain macro policies that are prudent, credible, and transparent while creating \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  space that allows priority \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on social protection as well as investing in human capital and infrastructure," Turk remarked.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  estimates that the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will grow resiliently at a stable pace in the coming years, driven by increased \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , increased business investment, and stable consumer demand.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia"s gross domestic product (GDP) growth is projected to reach an average of 5.1 percent per year from 2024 to 2026, despite facing rising obstacles from declining commodity prices, increasing volatility in food and energy prices, and growing geopolitical \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Indonesia"s GDP growth of 5.1 percent in the first quarter of 2024 remains strong and exceeds the average growth of middle-income countries.\par \par \uc2 Private consumption reached 57 percent of the GDP growth, reflecting consumer confidence supported by falling non-food product inflation, rising wages for civil servants, and good consumer service performance.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consumption strengthened again in the first quarter of 2024, driven by election and social \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This strengthening exceeded the negative contribution of net exports due to weak global demand and falling commodity prices that reduced export revenues.\par \par \uc2 (T.C009/A/A063/A063) 24-06-2024 13:15:32\par \par \uc2 Document ANTARA0020240624ek6o0002t\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 World Bank\uc2  Upgrades Indonesia's GDP Growth to 5.1 Percent\b0\par\par\uc2 565 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 June 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  has upgraded Indonesia's expected gross domestic product (GDP) growth to an average of 5.1 percent per year from 2024 to 2026, up from the earlier projection of 4.9 percent for both 2024 and 2025.\par \par \uc2 According to the \uc2 World \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 , Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to maintain a steady growth trajectory in the upcoming years, driven by increased \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , rising business investments, and stable consumer demand. This outlook holds despite challenges such as a declining commodity boom, greater fluctuations in food and energy costs, and rising geopolitical \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CIndonesia\u8217\'20\'19s strong \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance largely stems from the government\u8217\'20\'19s robust macroeconomic policies, which have bolstered investment attraction,\u8221\'20\'1D said Carolyn Turk, \uc2 World Bank\uc2  Director for Indonesia and Timor-Leste in a statement on Monday. \u8220\'20\'1CIt is crucial to uphold prudent, credible, and transparent macro policies while creating \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  room for prioritizing expenditures on social protection, human capital, and infrastructure.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian government and parliament are targeting \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth between 5.1 percent and 5.5 percent in 2025, surpassing the 5.05 percent recorded in 2023 and the 5.2 percent target for the current year.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  report highlights that rising food prices contributed to headline inflation increases this spring, with consumer prices rising 2.8 percent year-over-year in May, up from a 2.6 percent increase in January. Adverse climate conditions led to reduced domestic rice harvests, impacting food prices more broadly. Headline inflation is anticipated to average around 3 percent in 2024 and stabilizes at 2.9 percent thereafter, staying comfortably within BI\u8217\'20\'19s target range but facing upward pressure from food and energy costs.\par \par \uc2 In April 2024, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  raised its benchmark interest rate by a quarter percentage point to 6.25 percent, the highest level since 2016. This move was in response to delayed \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  rate cuts by central banks in advanced economies, prompting significant outflows in portfolios and other investments, and exerting currency pressures on Indonesia and other emerging markets. \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to initiate rate cuts next year.\par \par \uc2 "Higher \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  could raise borrowing costs and restrict external financing access, potentially increasing \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debt servicing expenses. External shocks like heightened armed conflicts or geopolitical \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  could lead to an unexpectedly sharp decline in terms of trade, resulting in reduced revenues and a more stringent \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  position," the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  wrote in its report.\par \par \uc2 Despite declining revenues from diminishing commodity windfalls, the government is intensifying social \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  and \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  investments. However, projections indicate that the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  will widen but stay within the 3 percent threshold.\par \par \uc2 The report also focuses on Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s path from a middle-income country to a high-income status by 2045. To achieve this, Indonesia must accelerate annual growth to more than 6 percent. This would require a productivity increase of 3 percent\u8212\'20\'14one percentage point higher than recent averages. \uc2 World Bank\uc2  data shows labor productivity declined from $7,530 per worker in 2015 to $5,336 in 2023, partly due to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  impacts of the Covid-19 pandemic\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CTo accelerate long-term growth, there is a need for enhanced private sector investment and dynamism,\u8221\'20\'1D emphasized Habib Rab, \uc2 World Bank\uc2  Lead Economist for Indonesia and Timor-Leste. \u8220\'20\'1CThis necessitates regulatory reforms that facilitate market openness and boost firm productivity across manufacturing and services.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240624ek6o0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
