c\b0 \highlight\uc2  activities.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is projected to grow by 18 percent yoy because of several factors. One of them being the government boosting social assistance to mitigate the effects of the El Ni?o weather phenomenon on food prices.\par \par \uc2 The government has decided to extend rice aid until December after the \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  ended in June, but the extension would only be for disbursements every two months instead of each month.\par \par \uc2 The country's subsidiesalso faced pressure from high international oil prices and the rupiah's depreciation against the US dollar, which driven by geopolitical tensions and global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  also pointed to the potential risk from rising interest payments from the government debt issuance, which could eat into funding forother priorities and growth-driver \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  said on Monday that Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  currently hovered at 0.1 percent of GDP, which equaled to Rp 21.8 trillion (US$1.32 billion) in the first five months of this year.\par \par \uc2 May was the first month the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  dove into a \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  after four months of booking a surplus.\par \par \uc2 As of May, state revenue dropped by 7.1 percent yoy to Rp 1.12 quadrillion, driven by a drop in both \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  and nontax revenue. Meanwhile, state \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew by 14 percent yoy to Rp 1.14 quadrillion in the same period.\par \par \uc2 Sri Mulyani emphasized that the state of the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  still remained within the government's planning and expecta