\par\par \b \uc2 The  \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties \highlight\uc2  in today's employment landscape\b0\par\par\uc2 938 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 June 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Tauchid Komara Yuda , Hong Kong, China\par \par \uc2 In the second week of June, I attended the 20th East Asian Social \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  (EASP) Research Network Conference, a leading \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  conference in both the Asian region and the world. The conference discussed social \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  issues ranging from digital transformation and environmental concerns to demographic shifts, issues that have increasingly challenged the sustainability of social protection systems in various East Asian countries and beyond.\par \par \uc2 The presentation by Prof. Yasuhiro Kamimura from Japan's Nagoya University provided insights on the \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  of today's employment landscape.\par \par \uc2 Kamimura outlined four job typologies based on his research findings.\par \par \uc2 The first typology of decent work represents the ideal form of formal employment. It is characterized by job security, social protections, specifically health and income protection, and meaningful work.\par \par \uc2 The term "meaningful" is subjective, but broadly refers to employment that is not only desired but also fulfilling and valued by the worker.\par \par \uc2 This concept of work sounds appealing, doesn't it?\par \par \uc2 However, the reality often falls short of this ideal. The formal sector, long coveted by many job seekers, still grapples with issues of alienation, where numerous employees find that their roles lack meaning.\par \par \uc2 Kamimura described this condition as "bull**** jobs", in which many workers feel trapped due to the limited capacity of the labor market to absorb new entrants, especially younger workers.\par \par \uc2 Most workers around the world might argue that the nuances and frustrations of their jobs are secondary concerns, as long as they can secure welfare benefits and a salary sufficient to maintain a decent standard of living.\par \par \uc2 On the flip side, employers often overlook the grievances of their employees.\par \par \uc2 This disregard is particularly evident in countries like Indonesia, where the imbalance between job seekers and job availability is stark. This imbalance allows employers to undervalue labor, often remarking that "there are plenty of others willing to work", thus perpetuating low wages.\par \par \uc2 This situation is deeply concerning. How can we expect productivity in a company if employees are dissatisfied and disengaged from their work?\par \par \uc2 One might argue that adhering to company procedures could sustain operations. However, this approach may lead to employee burnout due to a disconnect between the reality of their jobs and their expectations. Unknown to many, this dissatisfaction is a catalyst for the increasing mental health issues reported in the workplace.\par \par \uc2 The consequences of ignoring these issues are pervasive, affecting not only personal relationships but potentially leading to severe outcomes, including suicide. This phenomenon contributes to what I term a "depressed society", a state most visible in Indonesia's urban areas, characterized by a diminishing sense of community compassion.\par \par \uc2 The situation is grim, but there exists an even more dire employment condition known as a "s*** job". According to Kamimura, such jobs are often found in the informal sector and deemed meaningful, but lack social protection and fair wages for their workers.\par \par \uc2 Adding to this, many self-employed individuals, including artists, find themselves in this category. They are passionate about their work, yet their welfare is largely overlooked by society at large.\par \par \uc2 The most severe condition, however, is the "oppressed job". According to Kamimura, these positions offer neither income protection nor significant personal fulfillment. Workers in industries such as oil palm cultivation and garment manufacturing frequently report subminimum wages, excessive working hours and unstable job security.\par \par \uc2 The critical question we face is how to transition from the precarious states of "s*** jobs" and "oppressed jobs" to a more secure and fulfilling employment environment.\par \par \uc2 Formalizing the labor market is often seen as an unclear solution. However, achieving decent work for all requires navigating a complex landscape, particularly when investor confidence in Indonesia is hampered by perceived bureaucratic hurdles and a labor force lacking the competitive skills needed in the global job market.\par \par \uc2 Although Indonesia's Human Development Index saw an improvement from 68.90 in 2014 to 72.91 in 2022, mirroring advances in educational participation and infrastructure, these gains alone are insufficient for fostering a robust formal job sector. Thus, amplifying the social investment approach is crucial.\par \par \uc2 In particular, vocational education and training programs have shown promise in enhancing workforce competencies, making candidates more attractive to formal sector employers (Heintz & Valodia, 2008).\par \par \uc2 Additionally, implementing social protection initiatives such as unemployment benefits and healthcare services can mitigate the risks tied to transitioning into formal employment (Marx & Nelson, 2013). Moreover, establishing child and elder care programs can significantly mobilize the workforce, especially women, facilitating their entry into formal jobs (Esping-Andersen, 2002).\par \par \uc2 Evidence varies on the effectiveness of social investment strategies in promoting labor market formalization.\par \par \uc2 A study in Latin America indicates that increased social \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is correlated with a reduction in informal employment (Levy, 2008). Conversely, research in sub-Saharan Africa suggests that the success of social investment in formalizing labor markets depends heavily on the broader \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and institutional backdrop (Garc?a-Verd? et al., 2015).\par \par \uc2 Global experiences underscore that transitioning more workers into the formal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  not only benefits employees with higher productivity, decent work and social protections, but also advantages the business sector.\par \par \uc2 While the situations in countries typically cited in discussions on formalization are markedly different from Indonesia's context, now is an opportunity to align with future trends.\par \par \uc2 In conclusion, social investment emerges as a key driver in accelerating formalization of the workforce, a move that becomes increasingly critical to improving working conditions in Indonesia and elsewhere.\par \par \uc2 ___________________\par \par \uc2 A social \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  research fellow at Lingnan University in Hong Kong and a faculty member of the Social Development and Welfare Department at Gadjah Mada University in Yogyakarta. The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240627ek6s00007\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
