\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Maintaining the resilience of Indonesia's export performance\b0\par\par\uc2 1,021 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 July 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Andhi Prasetyo Hadi, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The year 2024 presents a challenging landscape for the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 High levels of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 , driven by geopolitical tensions, high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  and persistent inflation, have disrupted supply chains. These conditions significantly impact global trade performance, including that of Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Domestic trade performance is also affected by the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown in China, initiated by the trade war with the United States and followed by a crisis in the property sector.\par \par \uc2 The Chinese government's strict policies, coupled with demographic issues such as a large and non-productive elderly population and high social burdens, have limited China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 The weakening of China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is evident from its average \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth since 2012 until pre-COVID-19, which was only 6.29 percent, lower than the 2003-2011 average of 10.86 percent. The weakening Chinese \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  also directly impacts global commodity prices and negatively affects commodity-dependent countries like Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has long relied on China, with this dependency understood from various perspectives.\par \par \uc2 China is Indonesia's largest trading partner, with significant trade volumes between the two countries. Additionally, China is a major investor in Indonesia, especially in the infrastructure and natural resources sectors. Direct investment from Chinese companies has influenced Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, particularly in job creation and infrastructure improvement.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, China's substantial \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  power and high production capacity make it a primary choice for Indonesia in importing consumer and capital goods. This dependency allows Indonesia access to cheaper products but also involves supply failure risks if there are disruptions in China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 In 2023, Indonesia's export market share in the global market was only 1.1 percent of the total global export value, with total exports reaching US$258.8 billion, a decline of 11.34 percent year-on-year (yoy), impacted by the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown, particularly in China, which accounts for 22.9 percent of Indonesia's exports, significantly affecting Indonesia's export value, even if export volume may not change significantly.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's export performance in the first five months of 2024 reached $104 billion, a decline of 3.52 percent yoy.\par \par \uc2 Although still contracting, there are signs of improvement compared with the first five months of 2023, which saw a decline of 6.1 percent yoy.\par \par \uc2 This improvement is due to better performance from export destination countries, especially non-oil and gas, which account for 93.6 percent of total exports, with destinations such as India, the US, the Philippines, Japan and the Netherlands.\par \par \uc2 With a significant share of non-oil and gas exports, we must continue to increase capacity to ensure export performance grows. Despite some indicators showing signs of improvement, these challenges require appropriate policies and international cooperation to ensure long-term \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability and growth.\par \par \uc2 In the current sluggish global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions, we need to map Indonesia's export commodities and destinations to be more resilient in case of a slowdown in the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  or demand from one of our trading partners.\par \par \uc2 With proper mapping, Indonesia's export performance is expected to continue growing to maintain competitiveness and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 Mapping and strategies can be pursued in various ways.\par \par \uc2 First, classification of trading partners and diversification of export products. By identifying trading partners more precisely and not relying on a single country, export performance can be improved.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, product diversification will help mitigate risks arising from global commodity price fluctuations and increase export revenue stability.\par \par \uc2 The government can provide incentives to producers to develop high-value-added and technology-based products.\par \par \uc2 Second, identifying trading partners' potential demand and promoting exports. Discussions can be held with export destination countries to understand demand preferences and trends for specific products.\par \par \uc2 We can map whether export destination countries can directly accept consumer goods from Indonesia or capital goods or raw materials by discussing with local and international chambers of commerce to gather information about market needs and opportunities to adjust exportable products or services.\par \par \uc2 The government can also conduct export promotion campaigns through international exhibitions, trade missions and mass media promotion.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, the government can provide incentives to exporting companies to participate in export promotion.\par \par \uc2 Third, improving product quality and added value. The government needs to enhance supervision and quality control of exported products and ensure that producers meet established standards.\par \par \uc2 Improving certification and accreditation is also important in building consumer confidence in Indonesian products. The government can also seek products from new potential exporters with superior product quality and quantity by creating platforms and training related to export product standards (product quality, packaging, acceptable product composition for export destination countries).\par \par \uc2 The government can also provide education and training to producers to improve product quality.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, collaboration between the private sector and the government is also essential in developing new technologies and increasing production efficiency.\par \par \uc2 Fourth, improving human resource quality. We must continuously strive to produce skilled workers through education and training to produce high-value goods and support sophisticated manufacturing technology operations. Labor competitiveness must also be maintained to stay competitive. India and Bangladesh are examples of countries that have successfully built their manufacturing sectors and boosted exports with competitive labor costs.\par \par \uc2 Last, and equally important, is improving trade policies. The government needs to make improvements, including simplifying trade procedures, reducing import tariffs and enhancing market access. The government can also negotiate trade agreements with potential partner countries to increase market access for Indonesian products.\par \par \uc2 With the various existing strategies, Indonesia still faces challenges that need to be addressed, as the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown continues. The potential for a renewed trade war is also possible if Donald Trump wins the US presidential election.\par \par \uc2 The risk of a trade war must be mitigated to prevent further disruption of global supply chains. Implementing the mitigation steps and strategies outlined above will help reduce the risk of a trade war and protect the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  from potential negative impacts.\par \par \uc2 It is crucial for the government and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  actors to collaborate in facing these risks and formulate appropriate strategies to protect the domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 ___________________\par \par \uc2 Economist at \uc2 Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240702ek7300003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
