\par\par \b \uc2 Examining the decline in the national poverty rate\b0\par\par\uc2 972 \uc2 words\par \uc2 5 July 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Lili Retnosari , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The poverty data released by Statistics Indonesia (BPS) on July 1 showed that the percentage of people living below the poverty line in March 2024 decreased to 9.03 percent (25.22 million people), from 9.36 percent (25.90 million people) year-on-year.\par \par \uc2 Even though the decline is still below the government's target of 7 percent by 2024, the reduction in the poverty rate can be considered an achievement, partly due to the global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the rising prices of essential commodities. In fact, the poverty rate in March 2024 was the lowest in the country's history, beating the mark before the COVID-19 pandemic struck.\par \par \uc2 The decline in poverty has also been observed in both urban and rural areas. The percentage of the urban population living below the poverty line in March 2024 decreased to 7.09 percent, while in rural areas it was 11.79 percent. These figures are lower than those in March 2020.\par \par \uc2 Although the disparity between urban and rural poverty rates remains significant, the trend of declining poverty from March 2020 to March 2024 indicates an improvement in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions in both urban and rural areas.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the number of poor people in all regions of Indonesia, including Sumatra, Kalimantan, Java, Sulawesi, Bali and Nusa Tenggara, and Maluku and Papua, has also dropped.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, looking at other poverty indicators, the depth and severity indices of poverty in March 2024 also showed declines both in urban and rural areas. The decrease in the depth index of poverty indicates that the average shortfall of income among the poor relative to the poverty line is decreasing. Meanwhile, the decreasing severity index of poverty suggests a more equitable distribution of income among the poor.\par \par \uc2 When comparing March 2023 with March 2024, prices of several staple commodities indeed experienced significant increases, such as rice rising by 20.07 percent, eggs by 11.56 percent, red chilies by 45.94 percent and granulated sugar by 18.41 percent.\par \par \uc2 These price hikes inevitably put additional pressure on low-income households, as a substantial portion of their income is spent on basic necessities. Moreover, these price increases contributed to a rise in the poverty line in March 2024, increasing by 5.9 percent compared with the poverty line in March 2023.\par \par \uc2 The method used by BPS to calculate poverty in Indonesia follows the basic needs approach, referencing the Handbook on Poverty and Inequality published by the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 . To measure poverty, a poverty line is necessary.\par \par \uc2 Individuals whose average per capita \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  per month falls below this poverty line are categorized as poor. The poverty line reflects the minimum \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  in rupiah needed for a person to meet their basic needs for food and nonfood items for one month.\par \par \uc2 The poverty line in March 2024 was set at Rp 582,932 (US$37.6) per capita per month. This means that if a person has monthly expenditures of less than Rp 582,930, they are categorized as poor. Meanwhile, in March 2023, the poverty line was lower at Rp 550,458 per capita per month. This implies that if a person had monthly expenditures below this poverty line, they were considered poor in March 2023.\par \par \uc2 In calculating the poverty line, in addition to considering the poverty line from the previous period, changes in prices (inflation/deflation) are also taken into account. Therefore, price increases that drive up the poverty line could potentially increase poverty.\par \par \uc2 However, the very big increase in the various types of social assistance disbursed between January to March 2024 (notably before the Feb. 14 general election), such as rice assistance, direct cash transfers (BLT) for food risk mitigation, noncash food assistance (BPNT), the Family Hope Program (PKH) and Smart Indonesia Program (PIP), have helped maintain and even increase the purchasing power of the poor and vulnerable population, leading to a decrease in poverty.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, positive macroeconomic conditions such as \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and wages in the agricultural labor sector have also contributed to this trend.\par \par \uc2 Based on BPS data, with robust domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  grew solidly by 5.11 percent year-on-year in the first quarter of 2024. In February 2024, the average wage for labor in the agriculture, forestry and fisheries sectors also increased by 8.42 percent annually, which surpassed the national average of 3.27 percent. These positive macroeconomic conditions indirectly contributed to the decline in poverty rates in March 2024.\par \par \uc2 Overall, the decline in the poverty rate in March 2024 demonstrates that the government's efforts have yielded positive results. However, achieving the previously set target in the National Medium-Term Development Plan (RPJMN) 2020-2024 of curbing the poverty rate to the range of 6-7 percent will require extra efforts.\par \par \uc2 Maintaining price stability, especially for essential commodities consumed by the general population, is one key solution. The government needs to continue market interventions to ensure that basic necessities remain affordable, not only for the poor but also for vulnerable populations, preventing them from falling into poverty.\par \par \uc2 The ongoing social safety net programs such as social assistance also need to be continued, monitored and continuously evaluated to ensure effectiveness and prevent misuse.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  empowerment programs for the poor through skills training, access to capital for micro, small and medium enterprises (MSMEs), and labor-intensive programs must also be enhanced to provide opportunities for the poor to increase their income.\par \par \uc2 Lastly, improving the quality of education and health care is crucial to provide greater opportunities for the poor to enhance their well-being. Through these empowerment programs, the aim is not only to provide temporary assistance but also to empower people to break free from the shackles of poverty.\par \par \uc2 _____________________\par \par \uc2 A statistician at Statistics Indonesia (BPS). The views expressed are personal\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240704ek7500008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
