\par\par \b \uc2 Govt to reconsider import duty plan pending industry probe\b0\par\par\uc2 663 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 July 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 11\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 The Jakarta Post,\par \par \uc2 Continued from page 1\par \par \uc2 The move came on the heels of the United States slapping high import duties on Chinese solar panels, batteries and electric vehicles (EVs), in addition to a host of other goods already subject to various measures. The \uc2 European Union\uc2  followed this week with its own tariffs on Chinese EVs.\par \par \uc2 Amid \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  global geopolitical conditions, particularly because of tensions between the US and EU with China and Russia, Indonesia "must firmly establish its position in line with national interests" by imposing import \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures, Coordinating Maritime Affairs and Investment Minister \uc2 Luhut Pandjaitan\uc2  said on Friday.\par \par \uc2 "This is a very important baseline. Indonesia does not want to simply follow other countries if that is contrary to Indonesia's national interests," Luhut said.\par \par \uc2 "We are not targeting any specific country, especially China," he asserted, noting that "all actions are taken based on our national interests."\par \par \uc2 China is one of Indonesia's most important strategic partners in trade and investment, and the government is committed to maintaining this strong relationship through continuous dialogue on \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  measures, Luhut added.\par \par \uc2 President Jokowi also called for stricter import controls, particularly on second-hand clothing and illegal goods "disrupting" domestic markets, he added.\par \par \uc2 'Ineffective' measures\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian Retail and Tenants Association (Hippindo) opposes new import duties, arguing that such tariffs will not effectively address the declining retail industry performance, as the root of the problem is not regular imported goods but the influx of illegal goods, including both ultra cheap and luxury products.\par \par \uc2 "These tariffs will only affect importers who self-report and go through legal avenues, while illegal importers remain unchecked," Hippindo secretary-general Haryanto Pratantara said at a media briefing on Friday.\par \par \uc2 Regulatory changes conducted over the past few months only targeted legal importers, Haryanto argued, which cannot solve the problem and will "only increase the number of illegal importers, if not accompanied by policies to combat illegal imports."\par \par \uc2 Hippindo chairman Budihardjo Iduansjah said at the same event there was a widening discrepancy between data on Chinese exports to Indonesia from the International Trade Center (ITC) and Statistics Indonesia's (BPS) data on imports from China, which amounted to US$1.4 billion in 2022, suggesting that a significant volume of trade was bypassing official channels.\par \par \uc2 Details needed\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has seen an influx of Chinese products since the establishment of the China-ASEAN Free Trade Agreement (\uc2 CAFTA\uc2 ), a multilateral deal eliminating tariffs on nearly 90 percent of products, in 2010.\par \par \uc2 "Indonesia is bound by the \uc2 CAFTA\uc2 , which has resulted in a surge of Chinese goods to this date," Center of Reform on Economics (CORE) executive director Mohammad Faisal told The Jakarta Post on Friday.\par \par \uc2 With countries worldwide raising tariffs as drastic measures against China, Faisal questioned whether Indonesia pursuing a similar approach would tackle the root problems and whether the government was ready for the reactions to such measures.\par \par \uc2 "While imposing tariffs is good, is the government prepared for China's retaliation? Does this really solve the underlying problems?" Faisal said. "This issue must be addressed thoroughly and not just as a political stunt before the end of the administration."\par \par \uc2 Center of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Law Studies (CELIOS) executive director Bhima Yudhistira noted that antidumping duties could be an important strategy to level the playing field within the textile industry, but they need to be accompanied by support for the declining industry.\par \par \uc2 Additional policies will be needed to boost investment and improve the workforce in the manufacturing sector to match the current standards, he added.\par \par \uc2 "The government can support capital goods investment through incentives, and sales can be facilitated by business matching, connecting with promising alternative markets in neighboring countries or previously untapped nations via trade attach?s," Bhima suggested.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, high \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  were also hampering domestic industries. "The government could give the industry special \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Business capital financing at 2 to 3 percent could help make industries more competitive," he added.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240705ek7600004\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Opinion\par \b \uc2 Is Wind Farm Development in Low-Wind Regions a High-Stakes Gamble?\b0\par\par\uc2 1,090 \uc2 words\par \uc2 6 July 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 To achieve energy security and meet the net-zero emissions target by 2060 set by the Indonesian government, wind energy can play a crucial role in reducing reliance on fossil fuels. However, Indonesia's location along the equator generally results in low wind potential, with exceptions in regions such as South Sulawesi, Nusa Tenggara Timur, and the South Coast of Papua.\par \par \uc2 Current state-of-the-art wind turbines are designed for high wind potential areas like the North Sea, where the average wind speed at 100 meters exceeds 10 m/s. These turbines typically feature large capacities and longer blades, such as the 15 MW Siemens Gamesa turbine with a 236-meter rotor. They have a cut-in speed of 4 m/s and a cut-out speed of around 32 m/s. The rated power region in the power curve generally begins at 11 m/s. In contrast, the average wind speed in Indonesia ranges from 3 to 6 m/s, whereas an excellent wind site requires an average of at least 7 m/s. This disparity raises questions about the viability of wind farm development in Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Understanding the Major Challenges\par \par \uc2 The future of energy resources hinges not only on sustainability and affordability but also on reliability. Even though the levelized cost of electricity (LCOE) for wind energy has significantly decreased in recent decades, wind energy is inherently intermittent. This means it is not constantly available or predictable, which impacts grid stability. Grid operators must use balancing mechanisms to match supply with demand at any given time. In Europe, gas turbines are often used for balancing power. Consequently, adding more wind turbines also necessitates adding more gas turbines, which undermines the sustainability of wind energy if the balancing power relies on fossil fuels. Another option to stabilize the grid is through energy storage, but large-scale energy storage systems are expensive to build. To measure reliability, grid operators use the parameter loss of load expectation (LOLE), which indicates the probability of a loss of load event over a specific planning horizon. In the US, the target LOLE value is 2.4 hours per year, implying one outage day every ten years. In regions with low wind speeds like Indonesia, wind energy appears to be neither sustainable nor reliable.\par \par \uc2 Germany's energy transition \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , Die Energiewende, highlights the challenges of replacing baseload power with intermittent resources like wind and solar. \uc2 Fatih Birol\uc2 , head of the \uc2 International Energy Agency\uc2  (\uc2 IEA\uc2 ), called Germany\u8217\'20\'19s decision to prematurely close nuclear plants a historic mistake. Germany now imports nuclear-generated energy from France. Replacing baseload power with intermittent sources has demonstrated significant technical and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  challenges.\par \par \uc2 A recent study by TU Delft shows that the most economically feasible wind farm locations are offshore. This makes sense due to stronger winds in offshore areas. However, offshore wind farms are three times more expensive to build because of the complexity of construction and installation. They are also more expensive to operate, requiring specialized vessels for maintenance. Although offshore wind is a mature technology, floating wind farm technology, which is available for water depths exceeding 60 meters, has its drawbacks. For example, the first commercial floating wind farm, the Hywind Scotland, had to be towed to Norway for heavy maintenance. This process is time-consuming, costly, and shows that floating wind is unreliable.\par \par \uc2 The Opportunities\par \par \uc2 Developing wind turbines for low-speed regions presents significant opportunities for research and development. One potential solution is to design smaller capacity turbines, in the range of 2-3 MW, with significantly longer blades. This configuration can ensure that the power curve is steep enough to achieve the rated capacity at lower wind speeds. However, this design also shortens the rated power region, meaning the turbine will operate at its optimal capacity over a narrower range of wind speeds. Further research is needed to optimize blade length, turbine height, and other factors to maximize efficiency and energy output in low-wind conditions. Additionally, advancements in materials and aerodynamic designs could enhance the performance and durability of these turbines, making them more viable for widespread deployment in regions with low wind speeds.\par \par \uc2 Another promising opportunity is to utilize wind power for power-to-hydrogen processes, producing green hydrogen, which is essential for decarbonizing the transport sector. Beyond cars, hydrogen is being used to fuel ships and trains. Large-scale development of hydrogen production is currently underway, and it is projected that this will eventually make green hydrogen cost competitive. By integrating wind energy with hydrogen production, we can create a sustainable energy cycle that reduces dependence on fossil fuels and lowers carbon emissions across multiple transportation modes. Furthermore, advancements in electrolysis technology and infrastructure development for hydrogen storage and distribution are critical areas for ongoing research and investment.\par \par \uc2 In the wind energy value chain, significant job creation is expected across various sectors. This includes roles such as turbine technicians, engineers, component manufacturers, project developers, and financial analysts, among others. Each stage of the wind energy lifecycle, from design and manufacturing to installation, maintenance, and operation, will generate diverse employment opportunities. Engineers and technicians will be essential for the design, assembly, and upkeep of wind turbines, while component manufacturers will produce the necessary parts and materials. Project developers will oversee the planning and execution of wind farm projects, and financial analysts will evaluate and manage the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  aspects.\par \par \uc2 The Verdict\par \par \uc2 The increasing demand for renewable energy necessitates a diverse array of clean energy resources. Wind energy, as one of the key low-carbon solutions, plays an essential role in the energy mix. However, its overall contribution may be relatively minor in low-wind regions. Additionally, the sustainability and reliability of wind energy pose challenges, particularly due to the need for balancing power, making large-scale deployment a high-stakes gamble. This necessitates extensive consideration of technological and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  aspects, as the effectiveness of wind farms in such areas is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Government support, in the form of \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , is crucial to boost wind energy investments, but these \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2  must be carefully calibrated to avoid dependency. Sustainable growth in the wind energy sector will depend on strategic policymaking, ongoing technological advancements, and balanced financial incentives to ensure long-term viability and integration into the broader energy landscape.\par \par \uc2 ---\par \par \uc2 Agus Hasan is a professor in cyber-physical systems at the Department of ICT and Natural Sciences, \uc2 Norwegian University of Science and Technology\uc2  (NTNU)\par \par \uc2 The views expressed in this article are those of the author.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240706ek7600003\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Risks of Removing  \highlight22\uc2 Budget Deficit \highlight\uc2  Cap\b0\par\par\uc2 431 \uc2 words\par \uc2 7 July 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 THE risks outweigh the benefits. That is the danger of removing the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  limit in the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . According to Teguh Dartanto, the government\u8217\'20\'19s plan to exceed the 3 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  limit without urgent reasons\u8212\'20\'14such as during the Covid-19 pandemic\u8212\'20\'14could have fatal consequences for national \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CWhen there is no \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  control like during the New Order era, our debt burden, especially foreign debt, soared,\u8221\'20\'1D the Dean of Economics and Business School, University of Indonesia, told Tempo, July 4. Consequently, during the 1998 monetary crisis, \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions worsened due to the burden of debt.\par \par \uc2 Teguh believes imprudence in managing debt and \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  can ultimately lead to \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and investor distrust in the government\u8217\'20\'19s credibility in managing state finances. \u8220\'20\'1CThe financial market will always penalize imprudent behavior in managing national finances,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 When the government loosens its \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  and increases its debt, financial market players and investors will be wary about its ability to pay obligations in the future. \u8220\'20\'1CInvestors will release government bonds and exchange them for other safer assets,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. This capital rush will drive the weakening of the rupiah.\par \par \uc2 Yusuf Wibisono, Executive Director of the Institute for Demographic and Poverty Studies, states that a \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  limit is essential so that every regime has a buffer during \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  crises. According to Yusuf, \u8220\'20\'1CUncontrolled \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  debt surges can put pressure on inflation and disrupt banking intermediation.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 It is not just that. Yusuf believes that the government\u8217\'20\'19s efforts to widen the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  space and increase debt dominated by issuing government securities can also trigger fierce competition for funds in the financial market. Instead of channeling credit to the real sector, banks tend to prefer buying government securities because the risks are lower. \u8220\'20\'1CThis condition is already happening,\u8221\'20\'1D he said. Evidence shows that bank investment growth in securities instruments is higher than credit growth.\par \par \uc2 Abdul Manap Pulungan, a researcher at the Center of Macroeconomics and Finance Institute for Development of Economics and Finance, said that removing the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  cap would not guarantee that debt withdrawals will be productive and beneficial to the welfare of society and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. \u8220\'20\'1CIt may end up being used to pay debts with loans,\u8221\'20\'1D he said.\par \par \uc2 For developing countries with high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  and low levels of state revenue, removing the \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  cap will only undermine the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . \u8220\'20\'1CThe \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  tends to be ineffective, and the potential for moral hazard increases,\u8221\'20\'1D Abdul said. \u8220\'20\'1COnce you lose control, there\u8217\'20\'19s no stopping it.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/07/07/864856/864856_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240708ek770000e\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
