\par\par \b \uc2 Expanding trade:  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  diplomacy in  \highlight22\uc2 uncertain \highlight\uc2  times\b0\par\par\uc2 795 \uc2 words\par \uc2 9 July 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Alda Mayo Panadjam Panjaitan , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has emerged as a major \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  power in the region, consistently achieving robust \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. In 2023, Indonesia's gross domestic product (GDP) reached Rp 20.89 quadrillion (US$1.31 trillion), with an annual growth rate of 5.05 percent.\par \par \uc2 This growth trajectory is expected to continue, fostering long-term \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resilience. However, the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has become increasingly volatile, starting with the shaky aftermath of the COVID-19 pandemic and now exacerbated by various geopolitical tensions, including the ongoing \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  skirmish between the United States and China.\par \par \uc2 In response to these challenges, Indonesia has proactively expanded its trade horizons and intensified its trade diplomacy by establishing new trade agreements and preferential trade agreements (PTAs).\par \par \uc2 These agreements involve countries conceding some of their defensive measures to allow more goods, services or investments to flow into their jurisdictions. The ultimate goals are to secure better market access, attract foreign investment, foster more intensive people-to-people contact and integrate more effectively into global supply chains.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia currently has several high-profile trade agreements in force, including the Indonesia-Japan \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Partnership Agreement (IJEPA), the Indonesia-Korea Comprehensive \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Partnership Agreement (IK-CEPA), the Indonesia-Australia Comprehensive \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Partnership Agreement (IA-CEPA) and the \uc2 Regional Comprehensive \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Partnership\uc2  (\uc2 RCEP\uc2 ).\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 RCEP\uc2 , in particular, is a monumental agreement that includes all 10 ASEAN member states and five other major trading partners: China, Japan, South Korea, Australia and New Zealand.\par \par \uc2 These agreements provide Indonesian businesses with a significant network of trade opportunities. However, in these \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  times, Indonesia must do more to open new trade opportunities with developing country partners, particularly through PTAs. PTAs are simpler forms of free trade agreements (FTAs), focusing primarily on eliminating customs duties for a limited number of \b \highlight22\uc2 tariff\b0 \highlight\uc2  lines without any liberalization commitment on services, investment, intellectual property or other issues typically covered under FTAs or CEPAs. To date, Indonesia has entered into bilateral PTAs with Pakistan, Mozambique and Iran.\par \par \uc2 To say the impact is profound would be an understatement. With Pakistan, Indonesia has gained better market access for its palm oil products and has actually become the market leader for palm oil in Pakistan. With Mozambique, it was recorded that trade between the two nations has increased by 78 percent, an impressive figure, taking into account this is Indonesia's first trade agreement with a country from the African continent. As for Iran, the ratification process from both countries has started and is expected to be completed in the near future.\par \par \uc2 Some observers may view these bold initiatives with non-traditional markets as less beneficial than trade agreements with more industrialized and developed countries. However, negotiating more PTAs is crucial in the bigger picture as it underscores Indonesia's strategic role as both a developing country and a middle power.\par \par \uc2 These initiatives align with the philosophy of free and active diplomacy and the "Bandung spirit" of the 1955 Asia-Africa Conference. By working together, developing countries can leverage their collective bargaining power to negotiate better terms and conditions, and come up with novel, innovative ideas in the global market. This kind of cooperation may lead to more equitable trade practices and fairer \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefits.\par \par \uc2 The \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to establish new trade agreements with nontraditional markets also falls under the Foreign Ministry's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  diplomacy priorities, which include a priority to "strengthen \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  cooperation with established markets and explore ways to penetrate new potential markets, through the establishment of trade agreements".\par \par \uc2 As such, the ministry, through its extensive network of missions, has further intensified contact with partners to find new opportunities to create trade agreements, with a preference for PTAs for developing countries.\par \par \uc2 From a pragmatic perspective, expanding trade partnerships to nontraditional markets allows Indonesia to diversify its \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and reduce its reliance on major, established players.\par \par \uc2 This diversification is expected to enhance \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resilience and open new growth opportunities for both Indonesia and its partner countries.\par \par \uc2 More agreements also mean more concessions, which can lead to freer trade and a reduction in various nontariff barriers such as regulatory standards, customs procedures and technical requirements. Achieving this will facilitate a smoother and freer flow of goods, benefiting everyone involved.\par \par \uc2 In the end, Indonesia's diplomacy in pursuing new PTAs with nontraditional markets is a strategic response to global volatility and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Through active diplomacy and well-equipped diplomats, Indonesia aims to expand its trading network, gain a stronger presence, diversify its networks and promote sustainable growth in the partner countries.\par \par \uc2 In a world where multipolarity is steadily becoming the norm, it is time for Indonesia to think quick and act accordingly in expanding its trade horizons boldly.\par \par \uc2 _______________________\par \par \uc2 A legal adviser at the Foreign Ministry.\par \par \uc2 The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240708ek7900006\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
