\par\par \b \uc2 Insight: Unlocking Indonesia's prosperity through climate finance\b0\par\par\uc2 1,177 \uc2 words\par \uc2 20 July 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 William Sabandar,\par \par \uc2 The election dust has settled, and a new administration prepares to take the helm in a few months. Its in-tray is overflowing: Ambitious \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth targets hover around 8 percent, coupled with the urgent need to expand access to affordable health care, education and free nutritious meals.\par \par \uc2 However, Indonesia's current financial landscape presents an intense challenge. In this tight \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  environment, securing the necessary funds to achieve these goals is shrouded in \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The question is not just how to achieve these goals, but also where the necessary funds will come from. Tight finances demand creative solutions.\par \par \uc2 The challenge is also amplified by the need to address the climate crisis. Indonesia, like the rest of the world, faces a critical responsibility to transition toward sustainable practices. Accordingly, this agenda also requires substantial funding.\par \par \uc2 According to the estimates of Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  in 2023, Indonesia needs at least Rp 4 quadrillion (US$250 billion) to meet its Nationally Determined Contribution (NDC) and achieve its greenhouse gas emission reduction targets by 2030--she added that the annual state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  could barely afford 20 percent of it.\par \par \uc2 This, again, raises a precarious question: Where will the 80 percent come from? Unfortunately, relying solely on state resources to take on both national development and climate change is simply not feasible in today's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  climate. This is where climate finance emerges as a bridge to thrive on.\par \par \uc2 There is a crucial misconception to bust: Climate finance is not solely about mitigating climate change. It is a powerful development tool in its own right.\par \par \uc2 At its core, climate finance is about fostering people's prosperity and well-being. By empowering communities, alleviating poverty and strengthening a nation's overall capability, climate finance enables sustainable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 This, in turn, equips the country to tackle climate challenges with greater resilience and resources.\par \par \uc2 Multiple avenues exist to access climate finance, each offering unique advantages and considerations. International \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  sources like the Green Climate Fund offer grants and loans. The private sector offers carbon markets where companies can trade emission reduction credits called cap allowances, creating a financial incentive for sustainability.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia currently has two carbon trading mechanisms. Compliance markets (mandatory participation) offer larger volumes but complex regulations, while voluntary markets (choice-based) provide flexibility with plausibly lower volumes and transparency. In September 2023, the \uc2 Indonesia Stock Exchange\uc2  (IDX) launched IDXCarbon, the official platform for compliance-based carbon trading.\par \par \uc2 With these diverse funding mechanisms in place, the question remains: How big is the funding potential for the climate sector, really?\par \par \uc2 While the exact figure is difficult to predict, the Climate \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  Initiative suggests global investments in climate finance should reach an increase of $9 trillion annually by 2030. Even within Europe, substantial resources require 800 billion euros ($871 billion) specifically for energy infrastructure upgrades. Unlocking this prospect requires coordinated efforts from governments, businesses and international organizations.\par \par \uc2 Examining recent \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  developments around the world reveals a growing appetite for innovative approaches to climate finance. The United States Inflation Reduction Act (IRA) showcases large-scale financial commitment by allocating billions toward clean energy and green initiatives, offering \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  breaks for electric vehicles (EVs) and renewable energy production, while pushing for domestic clean energy production to ultimately reduce emissions. This act highlights the power of \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  in driving a green transition.\par \par \uc2 The Asia Zero Emission Community (AZEC), launched in 2023 by Japan and 10 partner countries, offers a distinct approach to climate finance. Unlike programs focused on domestic \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  or emissions trading, AZEC leverages regional cooperation. Prime Minister \uc2 Fumio Kishida\uc2  estimates that achieving regional decarbonization requires 4,000 trillion yen ($25.56 trillion), and AZEC's launch is expected to create a new, large decarbonization market in Asia, attracting global capital.\par \par \uc2 By facilitating resource pooling from member states, international donors and the private sector, it intends to unlock larger sums for green projects in Southeast Asia, promoting sustainable development across the region. This collaborative approach complements Japan's support for Asian decarbonization efforts, which includes technology transfer and over 350 tangible projects with Japanese companies.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia boasts significant potential for generating climate and development funds, especially through carbon markets. President \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2  emphasized this strength, highlighting the potential of the country's carbon market to reach Rp 3 quadrillion. Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister \uc2 Airlangga Hartarto\uc2  even pointed to the potential for Indonesia to earn Rp 8 quadrillion through carbon trading in key sectors like forestry, mangroves and peatlands.\par \par \uc2 These figures were based on a carbon credit price of around $5 per tonne. However, if Indonesia can develop an innovative and globally competitive market, there is an opportunity to significantly increase the value of its carbon credits to reach $100 per tonne, which would result in a cumulative potential of Rp 160 quadrillion.\par \par \uc2 Building on this potential, Indonesia has the opportunity to explore its own adaptation of climate finance that aligns with its specific needs and development goals. Furthermore, this approach requires a comprehensive package of policies that address climate change through the lens of "climate-sensitive development".\par \par \uc2 This solution integrates climate action with essential development goals, ensuring both environmental and social progress. The ideal climate finance \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will not be limited to traditional climate mitigation and adaptation strategies. It should act as a catalyst for wider development goals.\par \par \uc2 Translating climate-sensitive development into reality requires meticulous preparation. First, a comprehensive \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  framework anchored in \b \highlight22\uc2 legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  is essential, aligned with the Sustainable Development Goals (SDGs) and Indonesia's NDC for a cohesive process.\par \par \uc2 Second, a dedicated institution directly reporting to the President is crucial to acquiring and mobilizing international funding, overseeing implementation and facilitating collaboration across sectors. This will include efforts to make sure that the funds are well-implemented and distributed to the society.\par \par \uc2 The program's effectiveness will be demonstrably linked to the well-being of Indonesian society by establishing a framework that monitors key metrics like job creation, small and medium enterprise (SME) growth and sustainable housing development.\par \par \uc2 Third, ensuring effective implementation tools through internationally recognized monitoring, reporting and verification systems (MRVs) is paramount. This allows for transparency while also promoting \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  coherence across sectors and government levels, as well as identifying and resolving implementation bottlenecks.\par \par \uc2 While the technical considerations outlined above are essential for success, a critical, yet often overlooked element, lies in the power of narrative. One of the best ways to get everyone on board with climate action is to show how it directly benefits their lives.\par \par \uc2 This means effectively communicating how climate-sensitive development can improve basic needs like food, energy, and social security. This narrative should transcend technical jargon and complex \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  frameworks, instead focusing on the tangible benefits it offers for the people.\par \par \uc2 Imagine a future free from poverty, where clean air, abundant jobs and a thriving environment become the norm for all. This future is not only possible, but achievable through collective efforts on climate finance.\par \par \uc2 Op-Ed page 7\par \par \uc2 ____________________\par \par \uc2 Chief operating officer of the Indonesian Business Council. The views expressed are his own.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240719ek7k00003\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
