\par\par \b \uc2 Will Indonesia join \uc2 NATO\uc2 -like Mineral Security Partnership?\b0\par\par\uc2 1,044 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 July 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Galuh Maulana Yusuf , Washington, DC\par \par \uc2 In a significant move that could reshape the geopolitical landscape in the Indo-Pacific, during his visit to Jakarta on July 14, United States Undersecretary for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Growth, Energy and the Environment Jose Fernandez invited Indonesia to join the Mineral Security Partnership (MSP).\par \par \uc2 With its vast \b \highlight22\uc2 reserves\b0 \highlight\uc2  of critical minerals like nickel, cobalt and bauxite, Indonesia is a key player in the global minerals market. However, the country's traditional nonalignment \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and substantial Chinese investments in its mining sector complicate this decision.\par \par \uc2 The US-led MSP aims to restructure critical mineral supply chains among allied nations, driven by Washington's urgency to secure essential minerals for energy transition and industrial competitiveness in the face of China's strategic dominance in the sector.\par \par \uc2 These geopolitical and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  concerns have led the US to model the MSP on the principles of \uc2 NATO\uc2  (V. Vivoda, R. Matthews and N. McGregor, 2024). By prioritizing trade and supply chain arrangements with nations that share common values with the US, the MSP implicitly excludes China and Russia.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 NATO\uc2 -like partnership seeks to counter China's dominance in critical mineral supply chains, making the inclusion of mineral-rich countries like Indonesia essential. Fears of China using its control over these minerals for political gain, similar to Russia's use of natural gas supplies in Europe, intensify the urgency (J.F. Kirkegaard, 2023).\par \par \uc2 Interestingly, despite Indonesia's foreign \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  posture and substantial Chinese investment, recent developments and global trends suggest that Indonesia could potentially join the club.\par \par \uc2 While significant Chinese investment has propelled Indonesia to become the world's largest nickel miner, this comes at a cost. Chinese firms often operate with lower environmental, social and governance (ESG) standards compared to their Western counterparts (G. Baskaran, 2024). This includes lax environmental regulations, reduced labor costs and minimal social protections, all of which have led to significant environmental and social issues.\par \par \uc2 In December 2023, a furnace explosion at a Chinese-owned nickel factory in Central Sulawesi's Morowali Industrial Park resulted in 20 fatalities. Additionally, China's assertive behavior, particularly its frequent incursions into Natuna Islands waters, challenges Indonesia's territorial claims and strains bilateral relations. These events underscore Jakarta's concerns about overreliance on Beijing and the need to improve its ESG standards to attract more diverse investments (J. Blank, 2021).\par \par \uc2 Amid these internal and external pressures, Indonesia has sought stronger security partnerships with the US, especially after ASEAN's failure to take unified action on China's assertive behavior in the South China Sea.\par \par \uc2 During President \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2 's visit to the White House in November 2023, President \uc2 Joe Biden\uc2  announced the elevation of US-Indonesia relations to a comprehensive strategic partnership.\par \par \uc2 The new status not only enhances defense cooperation through the new Defense Cooperation Arrangement, but also underscores cooperation on inclusive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, trade through the US-Indonesia Trade and Investment Framework Agreement and support for Indonesia's \uc2 OECD\uc2  accession.\par \par \uc2 The partnership also focuses on strengthening critical mineral value chains, sustainable mining and Indonesia's domestic semiconductor ecosystem, aided by the 2022 US CHIPS and Science Act. This development reflects a flourishing relationship with deepened commitment to shared values, as well as Indonesia's significant role in the US' global clean energy transition.\par \par \uc2 Amid this evolving partnership, other key US allies in the Indo-Pacific are also recalibrating their strategies to address regional challenges.\par \par \uc2 Japan and South Korea, key US allies in the Indo-Pacific and MSP members, view China's military expansion and growing influence as major threats to a free, open and stable international order. Both nations are concerned about Southeast Asia's heavy reliance on China's trade and investment.\par \par \uc2 Recognizing that their military capabilities cannot rival those of the US or China, Japan and South Korea are focusing on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  strategies to counter China's influence. They aim to diversify their economies from China by increasing trade and investment with Southeast Asian countries. This approach provides Indonesia with a cover to strengthen its ties with the US while also offering \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  alternatives to reduce its dependency on China.\par \par \uc2 Amid these strategic realignments, Indonesia's approach under the incoming leadership of president-elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  will be pivotal. Prabowo is eager to capitalize on Indonesia's strategic geopolitical position amid the US-China strategic competition (P. Parameswaran, 2024).\par \par \uc2 Proven by his frequent appearances at international forums such as \uc2 CSIS\uc2 , \uc2 Bloomberg\uc2  interviews and the Shangri-La Dialogue, Prabowo emphasizes his strategic focus on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, defense modernization and maintaining a balanced approach in Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and security relations, avoiding dependency on any single major power.\par \par \uc2 He often states his intention to maintain favorable relations with China while strengthening cooperation with Western countries and regional partners. He also assures that he will continue the initiatives of his predecessors, provided they align with the greater good of the Indonesian people.\par \par \uc2 Prabowo has set an ambitious goal to achieve 8 percent \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, recognizing the necessity of diversifying investments and capitalizing on cooperation with other countries, especially given the global demand for critical minerals, of which Indonesia has an abundance.\par \par \uc2 As the US and its allies race to secure critical mineral supply chains and counter China's dominance in Southeast Asia, Indonesia's potential MSP membership intersects with Prabowo's diplomatic and leadership skills.\par \par \uc2 If Indonesia were to join the MSP, it would offer significant strategic and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefits, aligning with Prabowo's vision for a balanced approach to regional security.\par \par \uc2 Joining the MSP would place Indonesia among 14 developed countries with advanced expertise in mining, processing and refining critical minerals, thereby decreasing its reliance on China and protecting against geopolitical disruptions. This partnership would accelerate Indonesia's growth in electric vehicles, renewable energy and high-tech industries by ensuring a stable supply of essential minerals.\par \par \uc2 While there is a potential risk of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  backlash from China, the outcome will depend on Prabowo's diplomatic finesse.\par \par \uc2 With Prabowo's inauguration still three months away, Indonesia's entry to the MSP remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . However, it is certain that under his leadership, Indonesia will become more engaged on the global stage.\par \par \uc2 ____________________\par \par \uc2 A defense and geopolitical analyst pursuing a graduate degree in \uc2 Georgetown University\uc2 's Security Studies Program\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240721ek7m0000d\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Why We Need the Great Critics Council\b0\par\par\uc2 740 \uc2 words\par \uc2 22 July 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 THERE is no pressing need for the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) and the government to revive the Supreme Advisory Council (DPA). Instead of displaying a desire to form a clean government, President-elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  is actually looking for a way of giving his supporters a share in power.\par \par \uc2 Proposed by a number of members of the Gerindra Party, the revision of Law No. 19/2006 changes the Presidential Advisory Board into the Supreme Advisory Council. Deliberations in the DPR\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 Legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Body already began on July 9. Rapidly and without any debate, the nine factions in the DPR agreed to discuss revisions to the law, which was not included in the 2020-2024 Priority National \b \highlight22\uc2 Legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Program.\par \par \uc2 It is easy to guess that \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2  is almost certain to welcome this proposal. The President will then issue a document appointing a government representative to participate in the deliberations of the revisions to the law, which is targeted for completion just before the new government is formed next October.\par \par \uc2 This new law does not have any substantive content apart from the change of name and staffing structure. The organization will not be the same as the DPA of the New Order regime. As well as not being a senior state institution, the DPA will be no different from the Presidential Advisory Board, which is nothing more than a body to support the work of the president. The draft revision will only change the provision regarding the number of members, which was previously limited to eight, but will now be at the full discretion of the president.\par \par \uc2 The proposal to give the president the authority to determine the DPA membership is in line with Prabowo\u8217\'20\'19s plan to establish a presidential club, which was announced in May. According to Prabowo, this presidential club will be a forum for former presidents to meet with the president-elect. It will be difficult not to see this gathering of former presidents as an effort to accommodate those who supported Prabowo in February\u8217\'20\'19s presidential election.\par \par \uc2 The establishment of the DPA without any limits on the number of members also gives Prabowo the right to give a slice of power to more people. At present, Prabowo is trying to work out how to accommodate members of all the parties in the coalition supporting him. He has already increased the number of ministerial posts from 34 to 40.\par \par \uc2 From the organizational point of view, the DPA will not improve the system of government or make the organization of government any more effective. Without any special powers, recommendations issued by the DPA will only justify government policies. In other words, the DPA will become a rubber stamp. Another possibility is that the DPA will only be a political instrument to muzzle critics. We have often seen those with dissenting voices being given positions in order to soften their criticism.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, the DPA is bound to be a burden on state finances. As well as receiving salaries and facilities, the DPA members will be given staff and supporting organizations. At a time of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  disarray\u8212\'20\'14with Rp800 trillion of foreign debt due for repayment this year\u8212\'20\'14the DPA will only be an additional extravagance.\par \par \uc2 What Prabowo needs is not an advisory council whose supremacy is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Prabowo needs critics who continually examine his policies. With such a large coalition behind him, in practice, there is no significant opposition to Prabowo.\par \par \uc2 Even when coalition parties have differing opinions, this may well be simply a way of increasing their bargaining position for cabinet seats or for the sharing out of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  concessions. And do not place any hope in opposition parties. After Prabowo\u8217\'20\'19s inauguration on October 20, it is believed that the most critical parties will join the new government for fear of missing out.\par \par \uc2 This Great Critics Council\u8212\'20\'14as we will call it\u8212\'20\'14would be tasked with building a national critical ecosystem. Members could work together with non-governmental organizations, the press or other critical groups. This council would not be established to bring down the government\u8212\'20\'14because it would be a part of the government\u8212\'20\'14but as a body tasked with asking questions about government policies.\par \par \uc2 And most importantly, members of the Great Critics Council must be suspended if they are proved to have curried favor or are just trying to keep the boss happy.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/07/22/865886/865886_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240722ek7m00004\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
