\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Indonesia's consumers: Shift in  \highlight22\uc2 spending \highlight\uc2  trends\b0\par\par\uc2 1,254 \uc2 words\par \uc2 24 July 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Bobby Hermanus and Andry Asmoro, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 Household consumption's contribution to the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is falling.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  still promises high \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth in the range of 5 percent in 2024 and 2025. Fundamentally, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has always been supported by consumption growth which contributes around 54 percent.\par \par \uc2 We note several interesting conditions related to the development of consumption in Indonesia after the pandemic, namely consumption growth has not exceeded the 5 percent level for the last two years (2022-2023).\par \par \uc2 In the first quarter of 2024, consumption growth even only grew at 4.97 percent even though it had been supported by the general election and Ramadan.\par \par \uc2 To see the current development of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  consumption and what the outlook is, we analyzed using big data analysis, Mandiri \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  Index (MSI) and, at the same time, we reconfirmed with some data from other prominent institutions. Our findings are as follow.\par \par \uc2 The size of the middle class has shrunk significantly.\par \par \uc2 Using the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 's definition of consumer classes, we can track consumer class dynamics from the pre-pandemic period to the present. This consumer class grouping is based on per capita consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which is then compared to the poverty line. Only the top (upper class) and bottom (poor) classes saw relatively little change in proportions between their pre- and post-pandemic periods.\par \par \uc2 More significant changes in proportion can be seen in the middle part, which includes the middle class, the aspiring middle class and the vulnerable.\par \par \uc2 For example, the proportion of Indonesia's middle class has decreased from approximately one fifth (21.4 percent) prior to the pandemic to less than one fifth (17.4 percent) today.\par \par \uc2 After the pandemic, the proportion of the middle class in Indonesia has decreased by 4 percentage points, with many people moving down to lower \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  classes rather than moving up.\par \par \uc2 Among all classes, only the middle class experienced a decrease in proportion compared to pre-pandemic levels, with a drop of up to 4.0 percentage points. Of course, some middle-class people have moved to the upper class, but many more have moved down to a lower class.\par \par \uc2 This is demonstrated by the increase in the proportion of the upper class, which was only 0.1 percentage points, while the proportion of the aspiring middle class increased even more, going up 1.3 percentage points to 49.5 percent.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, some people of the aspiring middle class have dropped to a lower class (vulnerable), causing the share of this class to increase to 23.3 percent in 2023, the highest increase among all classes (+2.7 percentage points). This means that, in proportion, the middle class is shrinking, whereas the lower classes are growing.\par \par \uc2 Suppose the proportion of the middle class declines while the overall household consumption falls. In that case, it may indicate that more people currently have less disposable income, thus lowering the overall consumer purchasing power. This may weaken the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  confidence.\par \par \uc2 The concerns of the lower-income group regarding income reflect their sluggish \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Using the Mandiri \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  Index (MSI), we can see that the lower-income group's per capita \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  falls behind the middle and upper groups. The lower-income group's per capita \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  remained below the pandemic level (index = 100) until 2023. Only in 2024 has \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  slightly exceeded the pandemic levels (104.6 percent).\par \par \uc2 In contrast, the middle and upper groups have been above their pandemic levels since 2022. The difference is that the lower group's per capita \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  has continued to rise since 2022, whereas the middle and upper groups' \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  has stagnated, which is consistent with their declining income perceptions in 2024.\par \par \uc2 The lower-income group is using savings to maintain consumption, with their \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  surpassing pre-pandemic levels just recently in 2024. This group's rising per capita \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  is eroding their savings.\par \par \uc2 The MSI data reveals that since April 2023, or after Ramadan 2023, the majority of the lower-income group's per capita \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  has surpassed the pandemic level (January 2020 = 100). This means that, until 2023, this group's per capita \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  was generally <100, reflecting that their \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  per capita has not yet returned to normal. This is unlike in the middle and upper classes, whose \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  levels have returned to normal since 2022.\par \par \uc2 Social assistance could be a critical tool to boost \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  for the low-income group. After Ramadan 2023, the lower-income group's savings index has continued to decline, currently at 41.8 (Jan-2022 = 100). This phenomenon demonstrates that this group's income is insufficient to meet its consumption needs.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, this confirms previous findings from the \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  Consumer Survey,which found that those with the lowest incomes were the most concerned about their current income.\par \par \uc2 Managing finances among households can be challenging when prices are high, especially for necessities. Inflation for basic necessities, such as food and beverages, is generally much higher than the headline inflation.\par \par \uc2 In May 2024, the annual food and beverage inflation reached 5.6 percent, twice as high as the headline inflation (2.8 percent).\par \par \uc2 With relatively high prices, the proportion of food and beverages as basic necessities in the consumption basket tends to rise. It is currently 41.6 percent, up from ~39 percent before the pandemic. This increase is influenced by price factors as well as volume.\par \par \uc2 Under these conditions, making smaller and more frequent purchases helps consumers adjust their \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  to price changes. Hence, it keeps them on \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  while still meeting their needs.\par \par \uc2 Consumers are opting for cheaper alternatives more frequently, a behavior known as downtrading. We see that the behavior of "making smaller in size and more frequent purchases" has appeared in 2024. The average basket value (measured by \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  per trip) in 2024 fell 0.9 percent from the same period in 2023.\par \par \uc2 However, shopping visits in 2024 (measured as trips per capita) increased by 3.3 percent from 2023. This suggests that consumers prefer to visit more frequently while decreasing their basket value, also known as downtrading. Downtrading is a type of consumer behavior wherein individuals or households choose less expensive alternatives to what they have previously purchased or would normally purchase. This phenomenon is frequently caused by a combination of factors, including \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  pressures, changes in personal financial situations, and shifts in consumer preferences.\par \par \uc2 Consumers are increasingly demanding policies that address their financial security concerns and promote \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. Possible policies include \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  support, safety nets, support for micro, small and medium businesses (MSMEs) and employment, and monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  adjustments.\par \par \uc2 In the short term, strengthening unemployment benefits and other social safety nets protect consumers from financial \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This can alleviate concerns about income and encourage consumers to spend. However, we also need targeted income assistance, such as direct cash transfers or \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives for low- and middle-income households.\par \par \uc2 This can boost disposable income and encourage consumption. Over the medium and long terms, we must continue to promote job creation policies.\par \par \uc2 Investing in infrastructure projects, green technologiesand other sectors that generate jobs can boost \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and consumer confidence.\par \par \uc2 Aside from natural resource extractions and downstream processes, tourism is Indonesia's most promising sector, with a significant presence throughout the country. It has the potential to stimulate \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth due to its vast ecosystem and direct impact on key societal and MSME sectors, such as trade and agriculture.\par \par \uc2 __________________\par \par \uc2 Economists at \uc2 Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240723ek7o00008\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b \uc2 President Jokowi's  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  Policies Receive High Praise from \uc2 World Bank\b0\par\par\uc2 404 \uc2 words\par \uc2 25 July 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. In a recent meeting at the Presidential Palace in Jakarta, \uc2 Anna Bjerde\uc2 , Managing Director of Operations at \uc2 The World Bank\uc2 , lauded Indonesia's impressive \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  performance and the success of various government initiatives.\par \par \uc2 "The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  acknowledges Indonesia's stable \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of over 5 percent and its low inflation rate. We particularly commend the country\u8217\'20\'19s growth rate of 5.11 percent and an inflation rate of 2.58 percent," reported Airlangga Hartarto, Chief \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs Minister, after the meeting on Thursday.\par \par \uc2 Despite the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth rate hovering around 2.6 to 2.7 percent, Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s growth remains strong at approximately 5 percent. The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  forecasts a global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth of 4.8 percent for the coming year.\par \par \uc2 Airlangga highlighted that the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  also recognized several government programs aimed at poverty reduction and infrastructure development, including irrigation projects for agriculture.\par \par \uc2 "The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  delegation, who recently visited Lombok in West Nusa Tenggara, noted the improvements in farmer incomes and the effectiveness of irrigation systems. These advancements have led to increased agricultural output and higher farmers' exchange rates," Airlangga explained.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  praised Indonesia's efforts to reduce stunting, particularly through the Early Childhood Program and the strategic use of Village Funds.\par \par \uc2 "President Jokowi shared that the stunting rate has decreased from 37 percent to 21 percent, and extreme poverty has fallen from 6.2 percent to 0.8 percent. The President also emphasized the Village Funds program, which allocates Rp 71 trillion for rural development, including stunting reduction," Airlangga added.\par \par \uc2 Airlangga concluded that the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  considers Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s programs to be large-scale and exemplary, with the potential to serve as models for other nations. "The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  anticipates that these impactful programs will set a precedent for countries beyond Indonesia," he noted.\par \par \uc2 In June, the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  revised Indonesia's projected gross domestic product (GDP) growth upward, estimating an average annual growth of 5.1 percent from 2024 to 2026, up from the previous forecast of 4.9 percent for both 2024 and 2025.\par \par \uc2 According to the \uc2 World \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank\b0 \highlight\b \highlight22\uc2 , Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is expected to continue its steady growth trajectory, supported by increased \b \highlight22\uc2 public spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , rising business investments, and stable consumer demand. This positive outlook remains despite challenges such as a declining commodity boom, fluctuations in food and energy costs, and rising geopolitical \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240725ek7p00009\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw177\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2655\pichgoal600
