\par\par \b \uc2 Why We Need the Great Critics Council\b0\par\par\uc2 773 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 July 2024\par \uc2 Tempo.co\par \uc2 TEMPOE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk \par \par \uc2 TEMPO.CO, Jakarta - Rather than establishing a Supreme Advisory Council, \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  should form a council of critics. Its job would be to examine policies.\par \par \uc2 There is no pressing need for the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  (DPR) and the government to revive the Supreme Advisory Council (DPA). Instead of displaying a desire to form a clean government, President-elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  is actually looking for a way of giving his supporters a share in power.\par \par \uc2 Proposed by a number of members of the Gerindra Party, the revision of Law No. 19/2006 changed the Presidential Advisory Board into the Supreme Advisory Council. Deliberations in the DPR\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 Legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Body already began on July 9. Rapidly and without any debate, the nine factions in the DPR agreed to discuss revisions to the law, which was not included in the 2020-2024 Priority National \b \highlight22\uc2 Legislation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Program.\par \par \uc2 It is easy to guess that \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2  is almost certain to welcome this proposal. The President will then issue a document appointing a government representative to participate in the deliberations of the revisions to the law, which is targeted for completion just before the new government is formed next October.\par \par \uc2 This new law does not have any substantive content apart from the change of name and staffing structure. The organization will not be the same as the DPA of the New Order regime. As well as not being a senior state institution, the DPA will be no different from the Presidential Advisory Board, which is nothing more than a body to support the work of the president. The draft revision will only change the provision regarding the number of members, which was previously limited to eight, but will now be at the full discretion of the president.\par \par \uc2 The proposal to give the president the authority to determine the DPA membership is in line with Prabowo\u8217\'20\'19s plan to establish a presidential club, which was announced in May. According to Prabowo, this presidential club will be a forum for former presidents to meet with the president-elect. It will be difficult not to see this gathering of former presidents as an effort to accommodate those who supported Prabowo in February\u8217\'20\'19s presidential election.\par \par \uc2 The establishment of the DPA without any limits on the number of members also gives Prabowo the right to give a slice of power to more people. At present, Prabowo is trying to work out how to accommodate members of all the parties in the coalition supporting him. He has already increased the number of ministerial posts from 34 to 40.\par \par \uc2 From the organizational point of view, the DPA will not improve the system of government or make the organization of government any more effective. Without any special powers, recommendations issued by the DPA will only justify government policies. In other words, the DPA will become a rubber stamp. Another possibility is that the DPA will only be a political instrument to muzzle critics. We have often seen those with dissenting voices being given positions in order to soften their criticism.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, the DPA is bound to be a burden on state finances. As well as receiving salaries and facilities, the DPA members will be given staff and supporting organizations. At a time of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  disarray\u8212\'20\'14with Rp800 trillion of foreign debt due for repayment this year\u8212\'20\'14the DPA will only be an additional extravagance.\par \par \uc2 What Prabowo needs is not an advisory council whose supremacy is \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Prabowo needs critics who continually examine his policies. With such a large coalition behind him, in practice, there is no significant opposition to Prabowo.\par \par \uc2 Even when coalition parties have differing opinions, this may well be simply a way of increasing their bargaining position for cabinet seats or for the sharing out of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  concessions. And do not place any hope in opposition parties. After Prabowo\u8217\'20\'19s inauguration on October 20, it is believed that the most critical parties will join the new government for fear of missing out.\par \par \uc2 This Great Critics Council\u8212\'20\'14as we will call it\u8212\'20\'14would be tasked with building a national critical ecosystem. Members could work together with non-governmental organizations, the press or other critical groups. This council would not be established to bring down the government\u8212\'20\'14because it would be a part of the government\u8212\'20\'14but as a body tasked with asking questions about government policies.\par \par \uc2 And most importantly, members of the Great Critics Council must be suspended if they are proved to have curried favor or are just trying to keep the boss happy.\par \par \uc2 Read the Complete Story in Tempo English Magazine\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://statik.tempo.co/data/2024/07/08/id_1317177/1317177_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMPOE0020240726ek7q0002w\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Jokowi\u8217\'20\'19s Ambitions in Nusantara City\b0\par\par\uc2 1,549 \uc2 words\par \uc2 26 July 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 THESE days are a test for President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2  regarding the Nusantara Capital City (IKN) project. He had promised to move to Nusantara this month and to hold the Independence Day ceremony for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s 79th anniversary there on August 17. However, as of Wednesday, July 24, the former Mayor of Solo, Central Java, is still working from the Presidential Palace in Jakarta.\par \par \uc2 Jokowi has postponed the move because the new capital in North Penajam Paser, East Kalimantan, is not ready. \u8220\'20\'1CAs soon as we get the green light, I will start working there,\u8221\'20\'1D he said after watching the opening match of the 2024 President\u8217\'20\'19s Cup soccer tournament at Si Jalak Harupat Stadium, Bandung, West Java, on Friday, July 19. Heavy rains frequently hitting IKN have been blamed for the construction delays.\par \par \uc2 Previously, Jokowi was confident that he would soon take up office at the Presidential Palace at IKN, although at that time he was still waiting on the completion of primary facilities and infrastructure, including the availability of water supply. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are still waiting for one thing, namely water," he said in North Penajam Paser.\par \par \uc2 President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2  conducts the final topping-off ceremony for the housing of civil servants and defense and security personnel in the Nusantara Capital City, East Kalimantan, March 1. BPMI Setpres/Muchlis Jr\par \par \uc2 According to Jokowi, the inauguration of the Sepaku Semoi Dam on June 4, was expected to solve the water issue there. \u8220\'20\'1CWe are just waiting for the pump to lift the water and then channel it to the buildings and houses in IKN,\u8221\'20\'1D he explained. On the early morning of July 23, \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Works and Housing Minister Basuki Hadimuljono finally announced that water had begun flowing in IKN.\par \par \uc2 The IKN development is one of Jokowi\u8217\'20\'19s flagship projects. Besides Jakarta\u8217\'20\'19s overcrowding and its subsiding ground level, Jokowi argues that moving the capital is necessary for \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  distribution.\par \par \uc2 The 2020-2024 National Medium-Term Development Plan states that the funding needed for IKN amounts to Rp466 trillion (around US$28.6 billion). Of this total funding requirement, the portion from the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  (APBN) is only Rp90.4 trillion (US$5.5 billion), or about 19.39 percent.\par \par \uc2 The government hopes for investments to cover the rest, namely funding by businesses or private entities amounting to Rp123.2 trillion (US$7.5 billion or 26.44 percent), as well as cooperation schemes between the government and business entities worth Rp252.5 trillion (US$15.5 billion or 54.18 percent).\par \par \uc2 In reality, IKN construction continues to rely on the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Finance Minister \uc2 Sri Mulyani Indrawati\uc2  said that the IKN project \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  absorption as of April 30 was recorded at Rp4.8 trillion (US$294.9 million) or around 12.1 percent of the 2024 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocation of Rp39.8 trillion (US$2.4 billion). Last year, Rp27 trillion (US$1.6 billion) from the State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  was used for the IKN project. In 2022, Rp5.5 trillion (US$337.8 million) of State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  funds were used. Thus, the total use and \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  allocation for three consecutive years was Rp72.3 trillion (US$4.4 billion).\par \par \uc2 The problem, according to Bhima Yudhistira, Executive Director of the Center of \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and Law Studies, is that the IKN development is currently entirely a part of State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , even though the government hopes that the portion of State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  will decrease and be replaced by investment, especially foreign. \u8220\'20\'1CBut investments have yet to come in,\u8221\'20\'1D he said on Monday, July 22.\par \par \uc2 Another issue is that the capital returns or break-even point, as well as the return on investment for government building construction and various infrastructures, cannot be calculated. Meanwhile, interest and principal repayments on debt continue.\par \par \uc2 The large funding required for IKN also affects state-owned enterprises (SOEs) assigned to the project. \u8220\'20\'1CIt can impact liquidity, credit ratings, and other factors,\u8221\'20\'1D said Bhima. Meanwhile, IKN is not a project that can be expected to deliver \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  benefits. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s just about building government facilities. Unless, at some point, IKN will be sold.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 \u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\u8226\'20\'22\par \par \uc2 APPARENTLY, the incentive is still being discussed with the Finance Ministry. \u8220\'20\'1CIt is still under discussion because it has to be detailed and precise,\u8221\'20\'1D said Mohammad Averrouce, Head of Legal, Communications, and \b \highlight22\uc2 Public\b0 \highlight\uc2  Information Bureau at the Ministry of Administrative and Bureaucratic Reform, on Monday, July 22. Therefore, this Ministry has not yet disclosed the form and nominal value of the incentives that will be given to civil servants who move to the Nusantara Capital City.\par \par \uc2 Although it is not yet clear, Septian Hario Seto is determined to move there. The Deputy for Investment and Mining Coordination at the Coordinating Ministry for Maritime Affairs and Investment has registered as one of the officials at his office who will move to the new capital. \u8220\'20\'1CI am in the second batch, scheduled to leave in September,\u8221\'20\'1D said the father of four on Wednesday, July 17.\par \par \uc2 One by one, officials and employees of the Coordinating Ministry for Maritime Affairs and Investment will move to IKN. However, this is not the case with Minister \uc2 Luhut Binsar Pandjaitan\uc2 . The former Presidential Chief of Staff will remain in Jakarta as his retirement approaches. Luhut will be 77 years old on September 28.\par \par \uc2 The Ministry of Administrative and Bureaucratic Reform plans to move civil servants to the new capital in stages, according to housing availability and institutional screening. Screening is done by considering efficiency and effectiveness for the government. The priority is 179 echelon-I units from 38 ministries/agencies, 91 echelon-II units from 29 ministries/agencies, and several other options. The government offers pioneer allowances as incentives for civil servants willing to move.\par \par \uc2 The government has prepared 12 apartment towers for civil servants as well as for defense and security personnel. The target is for these buildings to be completed by the 79th Indonesian Independence Day celebration. \u8220\'20\'1CFor August 17, we are preparing 12 towers,\u8221\'20\'1D said Imam Santoso Ernawi, Chair of the IKN Infrastructure Development Planning Task Force, in a statement to the media on July 11.\par \par \uc2 However, on Independence Day, the 12 apartment towers will not yet be ready for occupancy. The IKN Infrastructure Development Planning Task Force targets the construction of eight towers for civil servants and four towers for defense and security personnel to be completed by August. The occupancy or utilization phase is scheduled for September. The government has set a target for completion of the construction of apartments for civil servants and defense and security apparatus in October.\par \par \uc2 The delay in infrastructure completion is good news for some civil servants registered for the first phase of relocation. For instance, Bima, a young civil servant from one of the coordinating ministries, expressed relief upon hearing about the postponed schedule for President \uc2 Joko Widodo\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s move to IKN due to delays in water and electricity facilities. This means he can spend more time with his family. \u8220\'20\'1CThank goodness, it\u8217\'20\'19s safe for now,\u8221\'20\'1D said the man who requested to remain anonymous.\par \par \uc2 Bima said that information about the civil servant relocation program to IKN is still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Initially, the government planned to relocate civil servants gradually starting in July. However, with housing still not ready, the relocation schedule has been changed to September 1. The plan is to move 1,740 civil servants to the new capital.\par \par \uc2 Coincidentally, the ministry where Bima works is scheduled for the first wave of relocation. However, he has not yet received clear information about his specific departure date. \u8220\'20\'1CHonestly, I\u8217\'20\'19m not interested in moving,\u8221\'20\'1D said Bima, who claimed that the lack of complete infrastructure and facilities at IKN as the reason for his reluctance to move there.\par \par \uc2 Likewise, Susi\u8212\'20\'14a civil servant from another ministry\u8212\'20\'14showed a grim expression when asked about the IKN relocation program. However, she is not as concerned as Bima because, in her office, the relocation plan is still just talk and has not been officially announced, nor is there a list of employees who will move. \u8220\'20\'1CIt\u8217\'20\'19s still \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 ,\u8221\'20\'1D said Susi, who also requested anonymity.\par \par \uc2 The promise of incentives for civil servants willing to relocate in the first phase is equally unclear. Susi and several of her colleagues previously heard rumors of incentives, such as a salary increase, child and spouse allowances, household assistant benefits, and other allowances up to Rp50 million (US$3,000). \u8220\'20\'1CBut it\u8217\'20\'19s not clear which employee level will be eligible.\u8221\'20\'1D\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, Christian Samosir, a staff member at the Communications Bureau of the Ministry of Tourism and Creative \b \highlight22\uc2 Economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , is weighing his options. He felt anxious that as a young ASN, he would be prioritized for moving. He hopes the government will give younger employees the right to choose and prioritize volunteers for relocation.\par \par \uc2 There are also employees willing to move voluntarily. One of them is Anton Rumanto, an employee at the Nuclear Energy Supervisory Agency. He considers the assurance of housing from the government as a positive aspect. \u8220\'20\'1CNo need to worry about finding a place to live because an apartment unit is provided.\u8221\'20\'1D Therefore, he is ready to move, as long as he can bring his family.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/07/27/866414/866414_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/07/27/866415/866415_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/07/29/866498/866498_1200.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMGEN0020240729ek7q0000l\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
