\par\par \b \uc2 Analysis: Surfing the slowing global  \highlight22\uc2 economy \highlight\uc2 : How has Indonesia fared so far?\b0\par\par\uc2 949 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 July 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 4\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Shahifa Assajjadiyyah, Mandiri, Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is facing a challenging period this year, characterized by a notable slowdown that poses significant risks and \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2  for emerging markets.\par \par \uc2 According to the July 2024 World \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook Update of the \uc2 International Monetary Fund\uc2 , global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has moderated due to a combination of factors, including persistent inflationary pressures, tightening financial conditions and geopolitical tensions.\par \par \uc2 The global slowdown has profound implications for emerging economies, and Indonesia is a prominent example of a country navigating these turbulent waters.\par \par \uc2 The latest World \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Outlook Update projects a deceleration in global growth to 3.2 percent in 2024, down from 3.3 percent in 2023. The slowdown is a consequence of the cumulative impacts of monetary tightening by major central banks aimed at curbing inflationary pressures from geopolitical conflicts and supply chain issues.\par \par \uc2 Inflation remains a persistent concern as high consumer prices in many countries prompt central banks to maintain restrictive monetary policies. Financial markets are also feeling the impacts through increasing volatility, further dampening investor confidence and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  activity.\par \par \uc2 Emerging economies, including Indonesia, are particularly vulnerable to global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fluctuations, as they often rely heavily on exports, foreign investment and capital inflows.\par \par \uc2 The consequences of this global deceleration for Indonesia are multifaceted. Its impacts so far have been seen in the trade and investment channel. The slowdown in major economies, such as China and the United States, has led to declining demand for our main exports like palm oil, textiles and minerals.\par \par \uc2 The resulting decline in export revenue in turn puts pressure on Indonesia's trade balance as evident in the country's trade surplus, which reached just US$15.4 billion in the first six months of 2024, lower than last year's surplus of $19.9 billion.\par \par \uc2 A slowing global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  often leads to lower foreign direct investment (FDI) and portfolio investment. Investors will tend to seek safer assets, such as \uc2 US Treasury\uc2  bonds, during periods of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Yet in Indonesia, the Investment Ministry revealed positive FDI performance. As of the first half of 2024 (H1 2024), FDI reached Rp 217.3 trillion ($13.31 billion), or 16.6 percent growth on an annual basis.\par \par \uc2 The encouraging data show that Indonesia remains an attractive investment destination.\par \par \uc2 Increasing volatility also appears in the financial market as fluctuation impacting portfolio investment flows. Foreign investors in Indonesian bonds and equities have posted year to date net outflow of around Rp 33 trillion.\par \par \uc2 The global market is currently waiting for the \uc2 Federal Reserve\uc2  to start cutting its benchmark rate. The US' recent weak \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data have raised market expectations of a rate cut, with the US personal consumption expenditures (PCE) inflation rate slowing to 2.5 percent in June 2024, down from 2.6 percent in May 2024.\par \par \uc2 Cooling PCE inflation has increased the likelihood that the Fed might cut \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  soon, with markets currently betting that potential Fed cuts could start as early as September.\par \par \uc2 This would have a positive ripple effect on global financial markets, especially emerging markets. Rate cut optimism should attract more capital inflows to emerging countries including Indonesia, which is seen to receive increased capital inflows from foreign investors.\par \par \uc2 So far, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been resilient amid rising global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and geopolitical risks. Since the main driver of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still household consumption, it is important for Indonesia to maintain consumer purchasing power, one way of which is to manage inflationary pressures.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia experienced rising inflationary pressures early this year, driven in part by energy and food price fluctuations. Yet, \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  synergy between authorities has succeeded in lowering inflationary pressures so far.\par \par \uc2 In June 2024, Indonesia's consumer price index posted month-to-month deflation of minus 0.08 percent amid lower food commodity prices. Statistics Indonesia (BPS) is soon to disclose its data for July, and we expect we could still see a small monthly deflation.\par \par \uc2 To maintain \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resilience and boost growth, the government has continued to implement a series of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms, including policies to boost the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , enhance infrastructure and improve the investment climate.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, it is also continuing efforts to strengthen social safety nets to mitigate the impact of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  challenges on the most vulnerable populations.\par \par \uc2 The government had distributed total funding of Rp 22.5 trillion through the basic food assistance (Bansos) program to 18.8 million beneficiary families by early June. Government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  for food security also recorded 31.4 percent year-on-year (yoy) growth until June, mainly for agricultural infrastructure and facilities to ensure food availability and maintain stable domestic food prices.\par \par \uc2 Overall, the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is coping quite well and is expected to remain robust in 2024, even amid the continuing global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fluctuation. We project that Indonesia will maintain stable growth of 5.06 percent yoy this year, compared to 5.05 percent yoy last year.\par \par \uc2 Despite challenges such as fluctuating commodity prices and rising geopolitical tensions, Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is still supported by strong household consumption, steady investment inflows and a government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  boost.\par \par \uc2 Our Mandiri \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  Index (MSI) shows that aggregate \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth this year still remains positive at 206.7 in the first quarter of 2024, higher than the 199.1 recorded in the fourth quarter of 2023. Furthermore, with the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  expected to widen to 2.7 percent of GDP this year, compared to an initial \b \highlight22\uc2 deficit\b0 \highlight\uc2  target of 2.29 percent, we hope this will give an added boost to the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 With a positive outlook for growth and stability, Indonesia is well-positioned to maintain its resiliency in a challenging global environment.\par \par \uc2 __________________\par \par \uc2 Economist at \uc2 Bank Mandiri\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST002024073