\par\par \b \uc2 Small reactors the future of RI's nuclear energy\b0\par\par\uc2 1,141 \uc2 words\par \uc2 3 August 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Toronata Tambun , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 I applied the political and cultural lenses framework in analyzing the nuclear energy option in Indonesia in my two previous articles in The Jakarta Post (July 6; July 20). The feedback from readers that struck my conscience was the cynical yet revealing fact that Indonesia has other priorities besides developing its untapped nuclear energy resources, such as \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, education, health care, trade, political stability, national security and other viable energies.\par \par \uc2 With this feedback in the back of my mind, I cannot help but apply the last lens of the three-lens framework, the structural lens.\par \par \uc2 Is the feedback valid? The Java-Bali region currently has an electricity oversupply of 4 gigawatts (gw), though this has been reduced from 7 gw at the end of 2022. This significant oversupply underscores the lack of necessity in adding new power plants, including nuclear.\par \par \uc2 The oversupply is attributed to lower-than-expected industrial demand and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, which has remained consistently below the 7-8 percent growth projection used in the 35 gw megaproject. Instead, the national \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has grown at a rate of 5-6 percent, leading to an accumulation of excess power.\par \par \uc2 To manage this situation, the Energy and Mineral Resources Ministry is delaying the commercial operating dates of several new power plants to alleviate the take-or-pay (ToP) burden on state electricity company PLN. This approach aims to prevent accumulating further oversupply and financial strain on PLN.\par \par \uc2 Given this context, the focus has shifted to optimizing existing capacity and exploring renewable energy sources rather than expanding capacity with new power plants, including nuclear options.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, Indonesia's long-term energy plans, as outlined in the National Energy \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and various road maps, do not prioritize nuclear power in the national energy mix by 2050, focusing instead on renewable energy sources to meet its sustainability targets.\par \par \uc2 Prior to 2015, Indonesia's electricity generation capacity was significantly lower at around 22 gw from coal-fired power plants.\par \par \uc2 The substantial increase to 35 gw was part of the 35,000-megawatt (mw) megaproject initiated in 2015 to support anticipated \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth and industrial demand. This expansion was pursued despite Indonesia's ratification of international agreements, such as the Kyoto Protocol and the Paris Agreement.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia ratified the Kyoto Protocol on Dec. 3, 2004 and committed to reducing greenhouse gas emissions. Effective from Feb. 16, 2005, the protocol aimed to cut emissions from industrialized nations and transition toward cleaner energy sources.\par \par \uc2 Similarly, Indonesia ratified the Paris Agreement on April 22, 2016, further committing to global efforts to limit temperature rise and promote sustainable energy practices.\par \par \uc2 The agreement encourages countries to reduce their reliance on fossil fuels, including coal, and increase the share of renewable energy in their energy mix.\par \par \uc2 Despite these commitments, Indonesia continued to build new coal power plants to meet its growing energy demand.\par \par \uc2 My readers' comment about Indonesia having other priorities than building nuclear power plants for energy provision may be correct after all. The existing 35 gw capacity in Java-Bali has a 4 gw overcapacity.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, without the addition of significant industries and if the government still pursues building the remaining 10.252 gw, the energy oversupply will only continue to grow.\par \par \uc2 The situation is further complicated by the potential sidelining of nuclear power as a priority in Indonesia's energy strategy. What will happen to the country's current resources in the nuclear energy sector, especially human resources?\par \par \uc2 Indonesia has invested significantly in nuclear and nuclear engineering education, producing a workforce of highly trained scientists, engineers and researchers. If the nuclear energy sector does not expand as anticipated, these professionals might face unemployment or be forced to seek opportunities in other industries.\par \par \uc2 Historically, large-scale unemployment among skilled professionals has led to significant social and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  challenges.\par \par \uc2 For Indonesia, the risk of having a surplus of highly skilled, unemployed professionals could have serious implications. The government and industry leaders must address this issue to ensure that the country's investment in nuclear education and training does not lead to an employment crisis.\par \par \uc2 While the future of these professionals remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2 , the government could explore various sectors to absorb this skilled workforce. Ensuring the continued use of their expertise, even in nonnuclear fields, will be crucial to maintaining social stability and leveraging the high level of training these professionals possess. Without a clear pathway for employment, the potential for widespread dissatisfaction and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  inefficiency grows.\par \par \uc2 Instead of focusing on large-scale nuclear power plants, which might not materialize given Indonesia's current energy landscape, the country could pivot to immediate needs that grid-independent small nuclear reactors can serve.\par \par \uc2 These include powering remote cities that need a reliable electricity supply and supporting AI mainframes and other power-hungry servers that require substantial and continuous energy.\par \par \uc2 Innovators in small nuclear reactor technology and advanced battery storage are identifying data centers as a prime target due to their substantial and growing energy demands.\par \par \uc2 NuScale Power\uc2  highlights the compatibility of their small modular reactors (SMRs) with the energy requirements of the data industry. Each of NuScale's SMRs can generate 77 mw of continuous, carbon-free power, potentially enabling data centers to operate independently from a traditional power grid.\par \par \uc2 Data centers, especially those focused on AI applications, require a significant amount of energy of up to 80 mw, compared to the 32 mw used by non-AI data centers. This makes them ideal candidates for energy solutions like nuclear power, which can deliver large amounts of electricity with a small footprint.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, companies are developing microreactors, which are even smaller. These units can serve as cleaner alternatives to diesel backup generators or provide additional power when needed. Their 1 mw reactors can be deployed quickly and are well suited for edge data centers or microgrids, becoming fully operational within a few days.\par \par \uc2 Despite these promising developments, challenges remain, such as the long-term storage\par \par \uc2 of spent nuclear fuel and navigating rigorous regulatory approval processes.\par \par \uc2 However, the potential for nuclear energy to contribute to a carbon neutral energy system is significant due to its ability to offer stable, carbon-free power.\par \par \uc2 Integrating these advanced nuclear technologies could also provide a pathway for Indonesia's nuclear workforce. By shifting focus from traditional large-scale nuclear power plants to innovative applications like SMRs and microreactors, the expertise of these professionals can be used effectively.\par \par \uc2 This approach not only addresses the country's energy needs, but also ensures that its investment in nuclear education and training continues to yield benefits. By focusing on these smaller-scale applications, Indonesia can efficiently use its trained workforce, manage its energy surplus and align with its sustainability goals.\par \par \uc2 ___________________\par \par \uc2 An En-Roads climate ambassador of the Climate Interactive and an alumnus of the Gadjah Mada University Nuclear Engineering School\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240802ek830000a\par }\page {\par\fs20\b \uc2 Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s Debt Ceiling Exceeded, Rupiah Struggles\b0\par\par\uc2 673 \uc2 words\par \uc2 4 August 2024\par \uc2 Tempo Magazine\par \uc2 TEMGEN\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk. \par \par \uc2 GLOBAL investors once again focus their attention on the Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meeting held last week. The long-awaited news of when the \uc2 Federal Reserve\uc2  will lower its benchmark \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  has finally arrived. The FOMC meeting did not cut the rates just yet, but strong signals have emerged indicating that the rate cut is likely to occur this September.\par \par \uc2 This is indeed splendid news for developing markets like Indonesia. Lower Fed rates will attract global investment funds that always seek the most profitable destinations back here. For instance, these funds may flow back into Indonesian government bonds, which become more attractive to investors when \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the United States are lower.\par \par \uc2 Apart from the news on the Fed\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 , another positive sentiment for Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s financial markets emerged on Tuesday, July 30. S&P Global, one of the world\u8217\'20\'19s leading rating agencies, upheld Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s investment-grade rating at BBB/A-2 with a stable outlook.\par \par \uc2 S&P assessed that Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  remains resilient despite global market turbulence and high political and \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Regarding \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth, S&P is optimistic that Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  will still enjoy an average growth of about 5 percent per year, driven by strong domestic consumption.\par \par \uc2 However, there are several significant risks that could threaten the realization of this optimistic projection. For example, potential shocks from declining prices of various Indonesian export commodities, whether due to escalating conflicts in the Middle East or the intensifying trade war between China and Western countries.\par \par \uc2 These shocks could exacerbate the current downward trend in export revenues. If this trend persists, the ongoing decline in trade surplus could ultimately threaten Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s external balance, undermining both the country\u8217\'20\'19s current account and balance of payments.\par \par \uc2 Another crucial factor is the change of government in two months. The market is still scrutinizing whether the incoming President \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2  is truly willing to maintain \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  discipline and avoid increasing the government\u8217\'20\'19s debt excessively.\par \par \uc2 The market still believes that Prabowo is inheriting an \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  with a strong footing. Some increase in government debt would be manageable. However, there are certain thresholds that must not be breached.\par \par \uc2 First, the additional government debt each year should not exceed 3 percent of the gross domestic product (GDP). Second, interest payments each year should not be higher than 15 percent of government revenues. If these limits are consistently breached, market confidence in Indonesia will decline, potentially forcing S&P to downgrade its rating.\par \par \uc2 Alarmingly, some of these limits are close to being breached or even already surpassed. Let us look at the figures. Indonesia\u8217\'20\'19s GDP in 2024 is projected to be around Rp21.9 trillion, assuming a 5 percent growth. This means the government\u8217\'20\'19s additional debt limit this year is Rp658.3 trillion. According to the 2024 State \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  (APBN), the government plans to add Rp648 trillion in debt, very close to the safety threshold.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the other cap, which prohibits interest payments from exceeding 15 percent of government revenues, has already been breached. Last year, it stood at 16.9 percent. This year, according to the 2024 APBN, the ratio would be even higher, 17.9 percent.\par \par \uc2 These figures speak for themselves. Prabowo can still increase debt, but it must be within a very limited and safe corridor. There is no room for him to add a massive amount of debt to finance new and ambitious programs that require significant funding. Such a reckless move could jeopardize the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This partly answers the question of why the rupiah remains unmoved, despite the positive sentiment about \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2 . Its exchange rate is still above Rp16,200 per US dollar, reluctant to go down below Rp16,000. It seems the market is still not confident that the new government will accept the dire situation of its \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2 . The message is obvious: there is no more opportunity for Prabowo\u8217\'20\'19s government to spend lavishly financed with debt.\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://images-tm.tempo.co/all/2024/08/04/867014/867014_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to