\par\par \b \uc2 Improving financial literacy among Gen-Z in Indonesia\b0\par\par\uc2 980 \uc2 words\par \uc2 12 August 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Wawan Sugiyarto , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 As Generation Z (Gen-Z, those born between 1997 and 2012) in Indonesia enter adulthood, a unique financial challenge in an increasingly digital and complex financial environment will be encountered. Despite being the most digitally connected generation, many young Indonesians struggle with financial literacy, which is a crucial aspect in making informed financial decisions.\par \par \uc2 Gen-Z in Indonesia faces several financial literacy challenges. One of the main challenges is the low level of financial literacy.\par \par \uc2 Based on a survey by the \uc2 Financial Services Authority (OJK)\uc2  and Statistics Indonesia (BPS) in 2024, the 15-17-year-old age group included in Gen-Z has the lowest financial literacy index, 51.7 percent, far below the financial literacy index of the other 65.43 percent of the population. This figure shows that many of them do not have adequate understanding of how to manage personal finances.\par \par \uc2 The problem's root lies in the lack of a comprehensive financial education within the formal school system. While there have been efforts to integrate financial literacy into the school curriculum, these are often limited and not sufficiently practical, leaving many young people unprepared to manage their finances effectively. Without a strong foundation in financial literacy, individuals are more likely to make poor financial decisions.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, Gen-Zers are heavily influenced by digital culture, where social media platforms often promote consumerism and a lifestyle of instant gratification. A study by \uc2 McKinsey & Company\uc2  (2023) highlights that young Indonesians are highly influenced by online trends and peer pressure, leading to impulsive \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  behavior and a lack of long-term financial planning.\par \par \uc2 The prevalence of "buy now, pay later" schemes and easy access to credit through digital platforms further exacerbates this issue, as many young people do not fully understand the implications of these financial products. Moreover, the COVID-19 pandemic has led to high youth unemployment rates and job insecurity, making financial planning more critical yet more difficult for young people.\par \par \uc2 According to a report by the \uc2 Asian Development Bank\uc2  (2022), the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  has made it harder for young Indonesians to save and invest, as many are focused on immediate financial survival rather than long-term wealth building.\par \par \uc2 While access to financial products has increased significantly with the rise of fintech and digital banking, this accessibility does not necessarily translate into understanding. A report by \uc2 KPMG\uc2  (2023) notes that while Gen-Zers are eager to engage with new financial technologies, their lack of financial literacy often leads to misuse of these tools.\par \par \uc2 For example, young people may invest in high-risk financial products without fully understanding the risks involved, leading to potential financial losses.\par \par \uc2 In Indonesian society, cultural norms and family influence play a significant role in financial decision-making. However, if parents or older family members lack financial literacy, they may pass down poor financial habits to the younger generation. This intergenerational cycle of financial illiteracy can be difficult to break, especially in communities where formal financial education is lacking.\par \par \uc2 Improving financial literacy among Gen-Zers in Indonesia is a multifaceted challenge that requires coordinated efforts from various stakeholders.\par \par \uc2 First, the OJK's National Strategy on Financial Literacy (SNLKI) 2021-2025 is a comprehensive framework aimed at increasing the financial literacy index across all demographics, including Gen-Z. The strategy includes integrating financial literacy programs into the national education curriculum, promoting the use of digital tools for financial education and encouraging collaboration between the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  and private sectors to expand the reach of these programs.\par \par \uc2 In addition, the OJK has introduced regulations, such as the revised POJK No. 3/2023, which mandates financial institutions to actively participate in financial literacy programs. This \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  emphasizes the use of innovative and technology-driven approaches to make financial education more accessible and engaging for the younger generation.\par \par \uc2 Second, educational institutions play a crucial role in shaping the financial literacy of Gen-Zers. There has been a growing emphasis on incorporating financial education into the school curriculum, starting from elementary levels to higher education.\par \par \uc2 Universities and vocational schools are also offering specialized courses and workshops on financial management, investment and entrepreneurship. For instance, the Education, Culture, Research and Technology Ministry in collaboration with the OJK, has developed financial literacy modules that are integrated into subjects such as mathematics, economics and social studies. These modules are designed to teach students practical financial skills, such as budgeting, saving and understanding credit.\par \par \uc2 Third, fintech companies in Indonesia are leveraging technology to provide financial education and services tailored to the needs of Gen-Z. These platforms often use gamification, interactive content, and social media to engage young users and improve their financial literacy. Fintech should help users understand the basics of investing and personal finance when offering investment opportunities.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -private partnerships are essential in scaling financial literacy efforts across the country. Collaborative initiatives among the government, financial institutions, tech companies and NGOs are creating broader access to financial education.\par \par \uc2 For example, the OJK, in partnership with the Indonesian Fintech Association (AFTECH), has launched campaigns aimed at educating young people about the risks and benefits of digital financial products. Community-based programs are also crucial in reaching segments of the population that may not have easy access to digital resources. These programs often involve workshops, seminars and financial counselling sessions conducted in collaboration with local governments, universities and community organizations.\par \par \uc2 In summary, the government's strategic initiatives, integration of financial education in schools, the innovative use of digital platforms by fintech companies, and the role of \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 -private partnerships are all contributing to this goal. As these efforts continue to evolve, they hold the promise of equipping young Indonesians with the knowledge and skills they need to navigate the increasingly complex financial landscape.\par \par \uc2 ______________________\par \par \uc2 An analyst at the Directorate General of \b \highlight22\uc2 Budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  Financing and Risk Management, Finance Ministry. The views expressed are personal.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240811ek8c0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
