\par\par \b \uc2 Jokowi's presidency leaves behind narrow  \highlight22\uc2 fiscal \highlight\uc2  space\b0\par\par\uc2 880 \uc2 words\par \uc2 14 August 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Winarno Zain , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 In the 10 years of \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2 's presidency (2014-2024) Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth has been sustainable, resilient and relatively high. It has managed to navigate safely in the midst of global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  headwinds and turbulence.\par \par \uc2 The gross domestic product (GDP) stood at US$1.42 trillion in 2023, $559 billion larger than in 2015. Its GDP per capita rose nearly 50 percent to $4,940 in 2023.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  was one of the reasons behind this relatively high and stable growth. During Jokowi's presidency, his \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been characterized as prudent and disciplined. It has contributed to the macroeconomic stability, and has been flexible enough to act as a buffer and a counter cyclical \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  during \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  downturns. Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  appears to have been effective in cushioning short-term shocks.\par \par \uc2 The post-COVID-19 global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  landscape was full of \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 , created by geopolitical tension and aggressive monetary tightening in advanced countries. Given the prospect of low global growth, moderating commodity prices and a higher cost of borrowing, the Jokowi administration took a conservative approach to \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  by narrowing the \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  deficits to ease financing pressures, despite a significant revenue windfall in 2022 amid skyrocketing commodity prices.\par \par \uc2 But the \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal budget\b0 \highlight\uc2  has been plagued with low revenue collection, as the \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratio to GDP has been persistently low during Jokowi's presidency, despite several \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  reforms that have been implemented. In 2023 the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratio was 9.6 percent, compared with Malaysia (12.2 percent), Thailand (16.7 percent) and Vietnam (11.6 percent).\par \par \uc2 The relatively low \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  ratio has constrained the government's pursuit of a more expansionary \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to grow the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  above 5 percent annually.\par \par \uc2 As result, government \b \highlight22\uc2 expenditure\b0 \highlight\uc2  has hovered around 15 percent of GDP since 2015, which is lower than its peers in the \uc2 Group of 20\uc2  such as India (28 percent), Brazil (48 percent), Turkey (28 percent) and Malaysia (23 percent).\par \par \uc2 Jokowi's administration spent Rp 3.15 quadrillion ($210 billion) on infrastructure between 2015 and 2023, an average of 2.2 percent of GDP. This compared with India (3.3 percent), China (6.7 percent) and Vietnam (6 percent).\par \par \uc2 However, according to a recent \uc2 World Bank\uc2  report, Indonesia's logistics performance ranking fell to 61st in 2023 down from 45th in 2018 out of 139 countries. The fall in ranking was due to its score in the logistics component (transportation cost, inventory cost, administration cost, bribery, illegal payments) despite an improvement in its physical infrastructure.\par \par \b \highlight22\uc2 Spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on social aid has been one of the important features in Jokowi's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . It was designed to stabilize the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , prevent recession and reduce poverty and to establish a social safety net for the vulnerable population. The Jokowi government spent Rp 3.31 quadrillion between 2015 and 2023 on social aid, 2.2 percent GDP. This was well below Vietnam (7.6 percent), Thailand (6.4 percent), Malaysia (5.5 percent) and the Philippines (3.8 percent).\par \par \uc2 This highlights the constrained \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  space for social protection in Indonesia and the pressing need for strategic and efficient use of available resources, especially the effectiveness of this program to alleviate poverty.\par \par \uc2 The number of people living in poverty declined from 27.7 million in 2014 to 25.2 million in March 2024, which was not commensurate with the Rp 3.3 quadrillion spent on social assistance programs by the government between 2015 and 2023.\par \par \uc2 In addition, about 120 million people, 40 percent of the total population, still live near the poverty line, meaning that they are prone to falling into poverty at the slightest decline in \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions.\par \par \uc2 The Jokowi government spent Rp 4 quadrillion on education between 2015 and 2023. But this has not translated into improvement of the quality of education.\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian student performance in the \uc2 Organization for \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Cooperation and Development\uc2 's (\uc2 OECD\uc2 ) Program for International Student Assessment (PISA) has declined since 2015.\par \par \uc2 There are still large regional disparities in the quality of education delivered. And \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on tertiary education is regressive.\par \par \uc2 Government debt has been kept at a manageable level, taking into account risk and ability to pay. The procurement of debt has been managed strategically to moderate risk, by optimizing alternative and domestically sourced financing. A wide investor base with different types of instruments has helped to spread risk and provide flexibility.\par \par \uc2 Domestically debt management has also improved through the expansion of local currency issuance including conventional and sharia instruments. The average tenor of the debt is now eight years, the dominance of local currency debt has reduced exchange rate risk, and the declining foreign-owned debt has reduced capital outflow impact on the balance of payments.\par \par \uc2 But risk perception of investors has kept Indonesia's 10-year bond yields higher than its peers, hovering at 7 percent, compared with Malaysia and Thailand at 3 percent.\par \par \uc2 According to CNBC news, the government spends Rp 500 trillion annually on maturing bonds and the installment of debt principals, including Rp 82 trillion on foreign debt. In 2023, for example, debt interest costs and debt repayments totaled Rp 937 trillion, about 46 percent of total \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  revenues and 30 percent of total government \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240813ek8e0000a\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
