\par\par \b \uc2 Job Creation Law Erodes Workers' Purchasing Power: Labor Party\b0\par\par\uc2 382 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 August 2024\par \uc2 Tempo.co\par \uc2 TEMPOE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Tempo Inti Media, Tbk \par \par \uc2 TEMPO.CO, Jakarta - The Labor Party's \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Affairs Spokesperson, Gede Sandra, has spoken out that the Job Creation Law has negatively impacted workers' welfare, particularly through a decline in purchasing power. This is because the \b \highlight22\uc2 regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  allows the concept of minimum wages to low wages, threatening workers\u8217\'20\'19 welfare.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe biggest problem among our members, particularly the working class, is their declining purchasing power,\u8221\'20\'1D Gede told Tempo on Tuesday, August 20.\par \par \uc2 Gede noted that wage increases have only been around one percent per year, lagging behind inflation rates which reached 3 to 4 percent in recent years. This resulted in a decrease in real income for workers.\par \par \uc2 The decline in purchasing power is exacerbated by the increasingly \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions of work contract systems. Gede said that the Job Creation Law allows the contract systems to be extended indefinitely, meaning that there is no assurance for workers to be permanent workers.\par \par \uc2 \u8220\'20\'1CThe law's extension of contract systems and increased outsourcing practices have further undermined job stability,\u8221\'20\'1D he remarked.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, the Job Creation Law's severance pay provisions are detrimental to workers. \u8220\'20\'1CIn the past, we could get severance pay of up to 12 or even 16 times of our salary, now it's only 3 to 6 times of our salary. This is very unfair,\u8221\'20\'1D he underlined.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, the Labor Party urged the government to immediately review and revise the Job Creation Law to address these detrimental effects on worker welfare.\par \par \uc2 On Tuesday, August 20, 2024, the Confederation of Indonesian Trade Unions (KSPI) and the Labor Party held simultaneous demonstrations throughout Indonesia, demanding the revocation of the Job Creation Law.\par \par \uc2 The rally took place at the Constitutional Court Building with protestors gathering at the Horse Statue area in Monas. President of the Labor Party, Said Iqbal, reported that around 200 people participated in the protests.\par \par \uc2 The demonstrators also expressed support for the Constitutional Court's decision to grant the Labor Party's judicial review request regarding the age limit for regional head candidates regulated in the Regional Election Law.\par \par \uc2 MHD RIO ALPIN PULUNGAN\par \par \uc2 Editor\u8217\'20\'19s Choice: Jokowi Grateful for New Criminal Code, Job Creation Law\par \par \uc2 Click here to get the latest news updates from Tempo on Google News\par \par {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://statik.tempo.co/data/2024/07/17/id_1319587/1319587_720.jpg"}}{\fldrslt{\cf2 \uc2 Click here to view picture}}}\par \par \uc2 Document TEMPOE0020240821ek8l0005l\par }\page {\par\fs20\uc2 Business\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia \highlight\uc2  Holds Benchmark Rate Steady at 6.25 Pct\b0\par\par\uc2 370 \uc2 words\par \uc2 21 August 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Globe\par \uc2 JGLOBE\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. PT Jakarta Globe Media. \par \par \uc2 Jakarta. \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  has decided to keep its benchmark interest rate (BI Rate) at 6.25 percent, the deposit facility rate at 5.5 percent, and the lending facility rate at 7 percent.\par \par \uc2 Governor \uc2 Perry Warjiyo\uc2  said that this decision aligns with BI's commitment to stability, aiming to further stabilize the rupiah and manage inflation within the target range of 2.5 plus-minus 1 percent for 2024 and 2025.\par \par \uc2 "These decisions are consistent with our pro-stability monetary \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  focus, aimed at strengthening the rupiah and ensuring inflation remains controlled," Warjiyo said during a press conference on Wednesday.\par \par \uc2 The global \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is projected to grow by 3.2 percent in 2024, with signs of a slowdown. The US \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  is anticipated to decelerate in the second half of the year due to reduced domestic demand. Meanwhile, China's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  recovery remains weak, while Europe continues to show improvement.\par \par \uc2 Inflation is decreasing and remains within the target range. The Consumer Price Index (CPI) for July 2024 recorded an inflation rate of 2.13 percent year-on-year (yoy), down from 2.51 percent yoy in June 2024.\par \par \uc2 As of Aug. 20, the rupiah has strengthened to Rp15,430 per USD, marking a 5.34 percent appreciation from the end of July 2024. This strengthening is more significant compared to the appreciation of other regional currencies, including the Thai Baht, Japanese Yen, Philippine Peso, and South Korean Won.\par \par \uc2 "BI continues to strengthen \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  coordination with the government to mitigate risks from ongoing global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainties\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Warjiyo said.\par \par \uc2 Economist Hosianna Evalita Situmorang from Bank Danamon said that the potential for a rate cut depends on \uc2 Federal Reserve\uc2  policies in September and US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data developments.\par \par \uc2 Hosianna noted that if US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  data, particularly labor and inflation indicators, weaken further, it could support a BI rate cut in Q4 2024. She highlighted that foreign investors are currently favoring Indonesia, with expectations of a possible Fed rate cut making Indonesian financial assets more attractive.\par \par \uc2 "However, even with lower Fed rates, a sluggish global and regional outlook may not necessarily drive up the rupiah\u8217\'20\'19s value, as investors may still prefer safe havens," Hosianna said.\par \par \uc2 Document JGLOBE0020240821ek8l00008\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw298\pich36\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal4470\pichgoal540
