\par\par \b \uc2 How global interest rate cuts will impact on RI\b0\par\par\uc2 846 \uc2 words\par \uc2 28 August 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 7\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Fikri C. Permana , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 United States Federal Reserve\uc2  chair \uc2 Jerome Powell\uc2  on Aug. 23 delivered a keynote address at the annual gathering of central bankers and economists in Jackson Hole, Wyoming, stating, "The time has come for \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  to adjust."\par \par \uc2 This statement reinforces the dovish stance the Fed is expected to adopt by lowering its benchmark interest rate in the upcoming Federal Open Market Committee (FOMC) meeting.\par \par \uc2 This sentiment was previously echoed by \uc2 San Francisco Fed\uc2  president \uc2 Mary Daly\uc2 , \uc2 Chicago Fed\uc2  president \uc2 Austan Goolsbee\uc2  and \uc2 Minneapolis Fed\uc2  president \uc2 Neel Kashkari\uc2 . They separately hinted at the possibility of a Fed rate cut in September, underscoring the need for careful attention to the current US \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions, particularly the rising \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  in the labor market.\par \par \uc2 This concern follows a sharp increase in unemployment and a rise in the Sahm Rule index, a recession indicator in the US, along with its potential impact on inflation.\par \par \uc2 Meanwhile, the global trend of interest rate cuts began with the \uc2 Bank of Canada\uc2 's decision to lower rates by 25 basis points (bps) on June 5. This trend gained momentum when the \uc2 Reserve Bank of New Zealand\uc2 , known for pioneering the Inflation-Targeting Framework now used by most central banks, cut its benchmark interest rate by 25 bps on Aug. 14, marking its first reduction since March 2020.\par \par \uc2 The expectation of a Fed rate cut and concerns about a deteriorating US labor market have led to a significant decline in the US Dollar Index (DXY) since early August.\par \par \uc2 On Aug. 23, the DXY reached its lowest level in the past 13 months. As a result, despite the lack of significant improvement in \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  conditions and the current account balance--two fundamental concerns for any currency--there has been a strong appreciation of various currencies against the US dollar.\par \par \uc2 The Indonesian rupiah, for example, has appreciated by 5.44 percent over the past month, slightly trailing the Japanese yen, which appreciated by 6.43 percent, bolstered by a 15 bps increase in Japan's benchmark interest rate on July 31.\par \par \uc2 On the other hand, \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  has sought to maintain the momentum of rupiah appreciation by keeping its benchmark interest rate steady at 6.25 percent during the BI Board of Governors Meeting on Aug. 21. This pro-stability \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , particularly concerning the rupiah, aims to sustain the attractiveness of domestic portfolio assets.\par \par \uc2 BI's efforts have been supported by a triple-intervention strategy, involving interventions in the spot and forward markets, particularly through domestic non-deliverable forwards (DNDF), and interventions in government securities (SBN) in the secondary market. Additionally, BI has collaborated with other central banks to promote the use of local currencies in cross-border transactions (Local Currency Transaction (LCT).\par \par \uc2 Simultaneously, on Aug.15, the Finance Ministry imposed operational restrictions on 69 companies that failed to comply with the mandatory placement of export proceeds (DHE). This move sends a clear signal that the government and \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  authorities are also committed to maintaining the rupiah stability.\par \par \uc2 The positive developments in the rupiah have been accompanied by an increase in domestic portfolio inflows. BI reported a net purchase by nonresidents totaling Rp 15.91 trillion (US$994 million) based on transactions between Aug. 19 and 22. This positive sentiment was also reflected in the Aug. 20, government bond (SUN) auction, which saw a significant increase in bid submissions, totaling Rp 104 trillion, the highest in the past three years.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, the significant decline in the weighted average yield awarded across all tenors in the auction indicates investor optimism about future monetary easing, both globally and domestically.\par \par \uc2 The ongoing global monetary easing is expected to have a positive impact on Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , particularly through the potential for stronger capital inflows into domestic portfolio assets, especially in the bond (SBN and corporate bonds) and stock markets (IDX Composite). Lower \b \highlight22\uc2 interest rates\b0 \highlight\uc2  in advanced economies are likely to push global investors to seek higher yields offered by emerging markets like Indonesia.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, with increased demand for government bonds, the cost of financing infrastructure projects and other government expenditures can be reduced. This would allow the government greater flexibility in planning \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on other critical sectors without worrying about rising debt servicing costs.\par \par \uc2 However, despite these potential benefits, there are risks to be mindful of. Rapid capital inflows into the domestic market could lead to an overly rapid appreciation of the rupiah, negatively affecting Indonesia's export competitiveness. Furthermore, there is a concern that these capital inflows could suddenly reverse (sudden reversal) if there is a shift in global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  sentiment, particularly in the US.\par \par \uc2 Therefore, domestic monetary authorities (BI), \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  authorities (the government), macroprudential regulators and other \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stakeholders need to take preventive measures to maintain the positive momentum in rupiah stability, enhance domestic liquidity without overheating the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and keep inflation within BI's target range.\par \par \uc2 Additionally, they must work together to ensure a conducive environment for domestic businesses and financial markets.\par \par \uc2 _______________________\par \par \uc2 A senior economist at PT KB Valbury Sekuritas. The views expressed are personal.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240827ek8s00009\par }\page {\par\fs20{\*\shppict{\pict\pngblip\picw139\pich40\picscaley100\picscalex100\picwgoal2085\pichgoal600
