\par\par \uc2 BUSINESS\par \b \uc2 REIMAGINING THE ROLE OF STATES IN A FRACTURED  \highlight22\uc2 ECONOMY \highlight\b0\par\par\uc2 Bayu Prasetyo \par \uc2 967 \uc2 words\par \uc2 29 August 2024\par \uc2 LKBN ANTARA\par \uc2 ANTARA\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 Copyright 2024. LKBN Antara \par \par \uc2 Jakarta (ANTARA) - In 1945, most of the world lived in poverty due to war and colonization. To avert a similar situation during the interwar period, the United States (US) and its allies designed a new international \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  system that ensured \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  stability and a free flow of capital and goods.\par \par \uc2 The post-war era marked the rise of the liberal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  as the primary guide to global prosperity. Despite its shortcomings, the liberal \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  regime indeed delivered its promise. Over four decades, it accelerated global growth and significantly reduced poverty worldwide.\par \par \uc2 As we stepped into the 21st century, the global \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  landscape started shifting, accompanied by slower growth.\par \par \uc2 The latest data from the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  reveals that out of 107 countries classified as middle-income countries in 2000, only 16 managed to join the high-income club by 2023, while the rest hardly climbed the development ladder.\par \par \uc2 Economists are worried about the prospects of future \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth. After the Global Financial Crisis (GFC) of 2007\u8211\'20\'132008, the world \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has become more fragmented and distrustful. Global capitalism is looking frail and discouraging.\par \par \uc2 Even the US and Western countries, which are considered the biggest proponents of the liberal \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , seem to have diverted from it by erecting protectionist policies.\par \par \uc2 Moreover, rising geopolitical tensions have exacerbated the fear of an interconnected \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . For low and middle-income countries, a fractured world means limited room for growth, higher obstacles to knowledge and technology diffusion, and increased vulnerabilities in facing future risks posed by climate change and artificial intelligence.\par \par \uc2 In "The World Development Report 2024," the \uc2 World Bank\uc2  has provided \u8220\'20\'1Cprescriptions\u8221\'20\'1D for middle-income countries to escape their ill-fated economies. The ideas are neither unheard of nor inventive.\par \par \uc2 They put forward a classic development approach focused on three drivers of growth: investment, technology infusion, and innovation. The report highlights that middle-income countries seeking to achieve sustainable high income must undergo two \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  transitions.\par \par \uc2 The first transition should prioritize investment and technology transfer to foster domestic industry development. Once technological mastery is achieved, focus on innovation to increase product value-added and achieve global technological leadership.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2  has warned middle-income countries to refrain from bypassing the initial \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  transitions. Moving from investment-driven growth to innovation-driven growth could result in a weak \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  foundation that is insufficient to support long-term development.\par \par \uc2 This was the case in Brazil after it achieved middle-income status in the 1970s. Brazil was on the right path before it tried to establish an innovation-driven \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that failed due to inadequate technological quality and a robust \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  foundation.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia escaped low-income status in the 1980s but has yet to reach upper-middle income, despite its "Golden Indonesia 2045" vision. The future remains \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  as it falls short of the upper-middle income GNI per capita range of US$4,256\u8211\'20\'1313,205.\par \par \uc2 According to the \uc2 World Bank\uc2 , based on the current trend, it would take Indonesia 70 years to reach one-fourth of the current US GNI per capita (US$65.103 constant price, 2015).\par \par \uc2 Assuming other countries will grow too, it would be difficult to narrow the development gap if Indonesia uses the same \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  playbook.\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 World Bank\uc2 \u8217\'20\'19s recommendations for middle-income nations aiming to achieve high-income status do not sufficiently emphasize, nor explicitly mention, the importance of a proactive government for stoking \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 In a world of polycrisis, the need for the active role of the state in shaping the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  has become increasingly apparent. It is difficult to imagine middle-income countries catching up with their high-income counterparts if the state remains at the periphery of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , solely as a regulator.\par \par \uc2 A proactive state is crucial for driving innovation, as evidenced by Maria Mazzucato\u8217\'20\'19s work, "The Entrepreneurial State." Many technologies, from the internet to semiconductors, were developed with significant state involvement, demonstrating the state\u8217\'20\'19s essential role in shaping the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 The \uc2 US government\uc2 , for instance, through the \uc2 Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency\uc2  (DARPA), was instrumental in early semiconductor development. It funded research, linked academics with entrepreneurs, and connected startups with investors.\par \par \uc2 DARPA\uc2  also assisted semiconductor companies in product commercialization by awarding them government contracts. In the process, \uc2 DARPA\uc2  successfully created a system sustained by a free flow of knowledge and competition among companies.\par \par \uc2 Historically, the state often took the risk of early investment in cutting-edge technologies at a time when private companies were hesitant to commit their resources.\par \par \uc2 If Indonesia"s state role is crucial, how should it proceed? Despite familiar industrial policies like \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  incentives, \b \highlight22\uc2 subsidies\b0 \highlight\uc2 , and SEZs, the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  structure has not shifted. \b \highlight22\uc2 Policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  evaluation is essential.\par \par \uc2 Indonesia can implement at least four things for the evaluation. First, Indonesia must determine which industries to prioritize to make the most of its limited resources. Indonesia may focus on those that \u8220\'20\'1Cshould become its comparative advantage,\u8221\'20\'1D such as maritime-based industries and green technology.\par \par \uc2 Second, the Indonesian government should employ the various policies at its disposal to support the private sector; however, the government must not blindly incentivize companies. It must select companies with potential growth and a willingness to innovate to avoid resource misallocation.\par \par \uc2 Third, the Indonesian government should strive to integrate itself into the global value chain to bolster technology transfer. Lastly, Indonesia and other middle-income countries may need to reimagine how to design their \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  and monetary policies to strengthen \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  growth.\par \par \uc2 *) Baginda Muda Bangsa is a political \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  analyst with LAB 45\p