\par\par \b  \highlight22\uc2 Economic \highlight\uc2  and political turmoil call for VAT increase delay\b0\par\par\uc2 1,012 \uc2 words\par \uc2 30 August 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 6\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Agatha Bagus Ilhamy , Jakarta\par \par \uc2 The increase of the value-added \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  (VAT) rate from 11 percent to 12 percent is set to take effect by Jan. 1, 2025, as stipulated in the \b \highlight22\uc2 Tax Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  Harmonization (HPP) Law.\par \par \uc2 While this increase is part of a broader strategy to enhance government revenue, the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social realities in Indonesia call for a careful reconsideration of this \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . At this critical juncture, it is essential to weigh the potential impact of the VAT hike against the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  pressures faced by the populace.\par \par \uc2 The purchasing power of the people is the heartbeat of the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 . When this heartbeatweakens, the entire \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  body feels the strain.\par \par \uc2 Data reveals that the proportion of household \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2  on basic necessities steadily increased from 13.9 percent in January 2023 to 27.4 percent in July 2024. This trend is more than just numbers, it reflects the harsh reality where people are forced to sacrifice other needs just to ensure they can meet their basic living expenses.\par \par \uc2 Such a condition embodies an injustice that should be remedied, not exacerbated by policies that could further worsen the situation.\par \par \uc2 Adding to this concern, the manufacturing sector, the backbone of Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , is showing clear signs of weakness. The Purchasing Managers' Index (\uc2 PMI\uc2 ) for Indonesia's manufacturing sector dropped to 49.3 in July 2024, indicating a contraction.\par \par \uc2 When the manufacturing sector contracts, jobs are lost, incomes shrink and the vicious cycle of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  slowdown ensues. Increasing the VAT in this context would likely add significant pressure to an already fragile sector, raising production costs and potentially leading to further job cuts.\par \par \uc2 Another alarming trend is the decline of Indonesia's middle class, which is steadily shrinking as more individuals fall into the aspiring middle-class category. In 2018, the middle class comprised around 60 million people, but by 2023, this number had dropped to 52 million.\par \par \uc2 The decline is a clear indicator that \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  pressures are pushing more people toward financial instability. In such a delicate situation, raising the VAT could further erode the purchasing power of this vulnerable group, exacerbating income inequality and deepening social divisions.\par \par \uc2 Various stakeholders, from business leaders to academics, have voiced their concerns. They argue that while the VAT hike might generate some additional revenue, the overall impact on consumer \b \highlight22\uc2 spending\b0 \highlight\uc2 , which accounts for a significant portion of Indonesia's gross domestic product, could be detrimental.\par \par \uc2 With household consumption growth stagnating below 5 percent for three consecutive quarters, any additional \b \highlight22\uc2 tax\b0 \highlight\uc2  burden could dampen consumer confidence even further, counteracting efforts to boost the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Academics also highlight that such a move could reduce the competitiveness and profitability of small and medium enterprises (SMEs), which are already grappling with rising production costs. Increasing VAT at a time when many SMEs are still recovering from the pandemic's impact could lead to a reduction in their operations or even force some to close down.\par \par \uc2 Beyond the \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  rationale, the current political climate in Indonesia must also be considered. The nation is experiencing significant political turmoil, with widespread \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  dissatisfaction and protests against the government.\par \par \uc2 In such a volatile atmosphere, introducing a \b \highlight22\uc2 policy\b0 \highlight\uc2  that directly increases the financial burden on the populace could be perceived as a lack of empathy and further fuel \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2  anger.\par \par \uc2 This could be seen as ethically problematic, as it ignores the principle of distributive justice, where the burden of \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  hardship should be shared equitably.\par \par \uc2 Given this context, it is crucial to emphasize and urge both the government and the \b \highlight22\uc2 House of Representatives\b0 \highlight\uc2  to engage in a serious and thorough discussion on this matter before the government transition in October. With the current \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and political turbulence, it is imperative that any decision to raise the VAT is made with the utmost caution and consideration for its potential impact on the broader society.\par \par \uc2 Delaying the VAT hike is not just a rational choice, it is a moral imperative for the government. By postponing the increase, the government would provide much-needed breathing space for both the \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and the \b \highlight22\uc2 public\b0 \highlight\uc2 , allowing time for recovery and for tensions to subside.\par \par \uc2 This move would also send a positive signal to the incoming administration, allowing it to begin its governance on a strong and populist note, one that resonates with the needs and concerns of the people. Politically, this would be a strategic advantage, positioning the new government as responsive and in tune with the populace, fostering goodwill and trust from the very start.\par \par \uc2 Importantly, there remains room within the law to reconsider the timing and extent of the VAT increase. While the planned VAT increase from 11 percent to 12 percent is mandated, the same law allows for flexibility based on \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  developments and/or increased funding needs for development.\par \par \uc2 According to Article 7, paragraph 3 of the VAT Law as amended by the HPP Law, the VAT rate can be adjusted to as low as 5 percent and as high as 15 percent.\par \par \uc2 Furthermore, as outlined in Article 7, Paragraph 4, any changes to the VAT rate must be regulated by a Government \b \highlight22\uc2 Regulation\b0 \highlight\uc2  (PP), which is to be proposed by the government and then discussed and agreed upon by the House in the preparation of the state \b \highlight22\uc2 budget\b0 \highlight\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 This legal framework provides the necessary flexibility for the government to delay the VAT increase, ensuring that any decision made is aligned with the broader \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  and social context, especially in the lead-up to the next administration.\par \par \uc2 In \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertain\b0 \highlight\uc2  times, the choices we make today will define our nation's future. While the VAT increase may be fiscally necessary, it should not come at the expense of the people's well-being. The new government has a chance to set a compassionate and visionary tone, balancing state needs with the struggles of people.\par \par \uc2 Delaying the VAT hike is not a retreat but a strategic choice that ensures we move forward together, with resilience and unity.\par \par \uc2 __________________\par \par \uc2 An official at the Finance Ministry. The views express