\par\par \b \uc2 Investors take comfort in RI fundamentals\b0\par\par\uc2 Deni Ghifari, The Jakarta Post, Jakarta \par \uc2 807 \uc2 words\par \uc2 31 August 2024\par \uc2 The Jakarta Post\par \uc2 JKPOST\par 2\par \uc2 English\par \uc2 (c) 2024 The Jakarta Post \par \par \uc2 Indonesia has been through some turbulent weeks that could have swung investor sentiment either way, but market actors appeared largely nonchalant in a reflection of their confidence in the country's political stability and solid \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  fundamentals.\par \par \uc2 The first big event that could have shaken the market was the presentation of the government's \b \highlight22\uc2 fiscal\b0 \highlight\uc2  blueprint for 2025 on Aug. 16, one day ahead of Independence Day.\par \par \uc2 The following Monday, President \uc2 Joko "Jokowi" Widodo\uc2  rearranged the cabinet, spurring speculation about his intentions just weeks before handing the baton to his successor, president-elect \uc2 Prabowo Subianto\uc2 .\par \par \uc2 Mere days later, protests erupted nationwide over a controversial regional election ruling, with some rallies turning into chaos and some groups pushing for a weeklong demonstration to ensure that their demands are met.\par \par \uc2 Irrespective of the political nuances in the cabinet reshuffle and the thousands of demonstrators chanting "Revolution!" in front of the Senayan \b \highlight22\uc2 legislative\b0 \highlight\uc2  complex, the market seemed undeterred.\par \par \uc2 When all was said and done, the rupiah had strengthened by 1.27 percent from Rp 15,690 per United States dollar on Aug. 15 to Rp 15,490 on Tuesday, certainly helped by the greenback's weakness as the dollar index -- a matrix that measures the US currency against six foreign ones -- went down by 2.2 percent over the same period.\par \par \uc2 Analysts and \b \highlight22\uc2 Bank Indonesia\b0 \highlight\uc2  (BI)\uc2  officials say the rupiah's movement today is largely dictated by what the dollar does and by global circumstances in general, rather than by recent domestic events.\par \par \uc2 BI spokesperson Erwin Haryono told reporters on Friday that the market's indifference to recent domestic events was "a good thing", because it exhibited how investors were guided more by the archipelago's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  foundation rather than political sentiment.\par \par \uc2 "Foreign investors' confidence in the Indonesian \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 , with regard to both the real \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2  and portfolio [investment], is quite high," said Erwin, pointing out that investors tended to flock to Indonesia once concern over global \b \highlight22\uc2 uncertainty\b0 \highlight\uc2  diminished.\par \par \uc2 He said the country had come a long way from 20 years ago, when the market was very susceptible to changes on the domestic political front.\par \par \uc2 Dorodjatun Kuntjoro-Jakti\uc2 , who served as Indonesia's coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  minister from 2001 to 2004, concurred.\par \par \uc2 The situation back then was altogether different from now, he told The Jakarta Post on Tuesday, noting that the rupiah had become a lot more stable than it was in the "transition time" when he was in charge, not long after Indonesia adopted a new democratic system following the toppling of Suharto's New Order regime in 1998.\par \par \uc2 "For me, [volatility] was an everyday problem, unlike now. So, decision-making had to be conducted very, very carefully back then," Dorodjatun added.\par \par \uc2 Susiwijono Moegiarso, secretary of the Office of the Coordinating \b \highlight22\uc2 Economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  Minister, said the market had its own mechanism for measuring the short-, medium- and long-term effects of what recently played out domestically.\par \par \uc2 "Right now, whatever the story, whatever the political situation -- in the middle of a [government] transition and all -- investors are lining up," Susiwijono told reporters at his office on Tuesday.\par \par \uc2 "So, believe that, regardless of the political noise, [Indonesia's] macroeconomic fundamentals remain very strong," he added.\par \par \uc2 Bank Central Asia (BCA)\uc2  chief economist David Sumual told The Jakarta Post on Wednesday that the market's detachment from Indonesia's politics was nothing new, as it has been sustained for the past 20 years. This impartiality, he argued, stemmed from the belief that the country is and will be politically stable.\par \par \uc2 "Since they are considered normal in a democracy, and given the expectation that they're temporary, the demonstrations related to today's politics are perceived [as something that will] die down," David answered when asked why the market had not responded negatively to the political turbulence.\par \par \uc2 The market would certainly respond if the protests were to prolong their demonstrations, David said, adding however that he had not seen any internal shakeups that played a bigger role than international events in driving Indonesian markets over the past 20 years.\par \par \uc2 However, should the archipelago slip back into the kind of political instability it went through in the late 1990s and early 2000s, domestic conditions, not external ones, would be the heavy hitter, David said.\par \par \uc2 Concurring, \uc2 Bank Permata\uc2  chief economist Josua Pardede told the Post on Wednesday that an "extreme negative sentiment" would only take hold once political stability stood on a knife-edge, which might happen if the protests are drawn out and gain a "massive" magnitude.\par \par \uc2 "For foreign investors, demonstrations are something ordinary and common, so long as they don't keep growing to the point of directly impacting [the flow of] the real \b \highlight22\uc2 economy\b0 \highlight\uc2 ," Josua said.\par \par \uc2 Josua also noted that market actors felt reassured by Indonesia's \b \highlight22\uc2 economic\b0 \highlight\uc2  resilience amid a global slowdown.\par \par \uc2 Document JKPOST0020240830ek8v0000d\par }\par \b \uc2 Search Summary\b0\par \par  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9072\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Text\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \li50\uc2 (economic or economy) and (uncertain or uncertainty or uncertainties) and (policy or public or tax or taxation or taxes or taxed or spending or expenditure or fiscal or stimulus or budget or deficit or national debt or tariff or subsidies or subsidy or Bank Indonesia or central bank or reserves or interest rates or fiscal or legislation or legislative or house of representatives or regulation)\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9072\row } \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9072\pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \uc2 Date\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\intbl\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 \li50\uc2 All Dates\cell \pard \ql \li0\ri0\widctlpar\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0 {  \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx2000\clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\brdrs \cellx9072\row } \trowd\trgaph15\trqc\trleft-15 \clvertalt\clbrdrt\brdrs\clbrdrl\brdrs\clbrdrb\brdrs\clbrdrr\